<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Is Pope Making Final Visit Home? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GDANSK, Poland (AP) -- Agnieszka Kaliszewska was born the same  
year that Karol Wojtyla became the first Polish pope. In a devout 
Roman Catholic country, her faith has been shaped and inspired by 
the personal connection Poles feel with their beloved ``papa.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now the 21-year-old economics student is wondering if the  
elderly pope she waited more than six hours to see is making his 
final visit home. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is the only pope we've known,'' she said amid 700,000 other  
believers at a huge outdoor Mass. ``We've gotten used to the fact 
that the pope is Polish.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Poles of all ages, John Paul represents the light at the end  
of a century of mostly darkness -- two world wars, Nazi and Soviet 
domination, communist oppression. His papacy raised Poland's status 
in the world and helped create the Solidarity movement that toppled 
communist rule in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people identify with soccer teams. We identify with the  
pope,'' Jola Lopaciuk, 45, explained at a Sunday morning Mass in 
the northern town of Pelplin. 
</P>
<P>
	Now 79, John Paul is visibly weakened, walking slowly and  
stiffly with a cane. His left hand shakes noticeably and his speech 
sometimes slurs, raising suspicions of Parkinson's disease. 
</P>
<P>
	No one wants to call the 13-day pilgrimage that began Saturday  
in this Baltic coast city their last chance to see him, but the 
question inevitably enters any discussion. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think this is his last visit,'' Lopaciuk says. ``He's  
so beautiful and smiles so well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yet Teresa Rosinska, 60, traveled more than 180 miles from  
Wroclaw to see the pope Sunday partly because of her concern. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is probably his last visit because of health reasons, and  
that's why this Mass has a special dimension for us,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, Kaliszewska arrived at the horse track in Gdansk at  
10 a.m. to get a good spot near the front for the Mass that began 
at 5:15 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	Her boyfriend, Pawel Maciejewski, 26, said he feared the worst  
when John Paul visited Poland in 1997, his infirmities more evident 
than on previous trips. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was thinking that might be the last time,'' he recalled.  
``(Now) my fears have gone away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In any case, a new pope should mean little change for Poland,  
according to Maciejewski. 
</P>
<P>
	``The pope is the deputy or substitute of Christ in the world,  
and Christ is always the same,'' he said. ``It will certainly 
affect Poland in some way, perhaps in a political dimension. But in 
a religious dimension, it will have no effect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kaliszewska isn't worried that the church's influence will  
disappear with Poland's pope. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is our task, that we convey it to the next generation,''  
she said, smiling. ``We are young and we have to do it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
