<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gates Tape Played for Bristol Jurors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- As Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates  
answered questions in an antitrust case filed by a tiny Danbury 
software firm, he was less combative than he had been when 
government lawyers grilled him in the larger antitrust case filed 
by the U.S. Justice Department and 19 states. 
</P>
<P>
	But Gates' message was the same. He said Microsoft had not tried  
to squash its competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	In a videotaped deposition played for jurors in U.S. District  
Court Monday, Gates denied Microsoft had tried to freeze out 
Bristol Technology Inc. of Danbury after initially giving it access 
to Windows programming code. 
</P>
<P>
	But lawyers for Bristol peppered Gates with questions on an  
e-mail message in which he wrote that Microsoft was choosing 
Bristol's main competitor, Mainsoft Inc., as its partner, and 
``revving up their activities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gates, who appeared combative and forgetful during a lengthy  
deposition last year for the antitrust case being heard in 
Washington, D.C., was generally congenial and relaxed during the 
deposition for the Bristol case. 
</P>
<P>
	During his deposition for the Justice Department case, Gates  
appeared so evasive in interviews with government lawyers that the 
judge laughed and shook his head while watching the testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	Bristol makes a product called Wind/U, which allows programs  
that were written for Windows to run on computers with different 
operating systems, such as Unix. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, Microsoft signed a three-year contract with Bristol  
giving the company access to programming code -- the software 
blueprints -- for Windows NT 3.0, a version of its operating system 
designed to work with powerful corporate computers. 
</P>
<P>
	When the contract expired in 1997, the two companies could not  
come to an agreement. Bristol claims Microsoft promised to make the 
code available into the future. Microsoft says Bristol is trying to 
get more favorable licensing terms for a new contract. 
</P>
<P>
	In the deposition, Bristol's lawyers questioned Gates about a  
September 1997 e-mail he sent to several Microsoft employees. In 
it, Gates lists eight actions Microsoft was taking, including 
choosing Mainsoft as a partner in its cross-platform program, 
called the Windows Interface Source Environment, or WISE. 
</P>
<P>
	Bristol had also been a WISE partner with Microsoft.  
</P>
<P>
	``Now what did you mean -- if you didn't mean to exclude Bristol  
from the WISE program -- then what did you mean by picking Mainsoft 
as your partner?'' Bristol attorney Patrick Lynch asked Gates. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't mean anything about whether it was Mainsoft or  
Bristol, I'm just talking about the things we're doing, so for 
total completeness, maybe I should have listed Bristol,'' Gates 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``OK, and you didn't mean to tell your people that for some  
reason you had decided to freeze Bristol out of the WISE program?'' 
Lynch asked. 
</P>
<P>
	``No,'' Gates replied.  
</P>
<P>
	The jury appeared alternately amused and bored by Gates'  
testimony. At one point, several jurors chuckled when Gates became 
animated about the competitive threat posed by Netscape -- an issue 
in the case brought by the Justice Department case and 19 states. 
</P>
<P>
	In that case, the government contends that Microsoft illegally  
wielded monopoly power from its dominant Windows product to expand 
into new markets, such as Internet software, and thus crush 
competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	``Netscape stated very clearly that their goal was to put  
Windows out of business, to make it obsolete and useless, and that 
Microsoft would go bankrupt based on their activities,'' Gates 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``And that caused you to believe that it was a serious  
competitive threat?'' asked Lynch. 
</P>
<P>
	``Generally, when people say those things, it gets my  
attention,'' Gates said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
