<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.N. Resolution Negotiations Stall  
</P>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and  
foreign ministers negotiating Balkan peace failed to agree today on 
a U.N. resolution critical to ending the Kosovo crisis. The impasse 
came after the Russian delegation contested three key points and 
requested time to consult with Moscow. Despite the stalemate, 
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic offered assurances that he 
intends to carry out a peace agreement, a U.S. official said. 
Western officials indicated that the talks were stalled on NATO's 
insistence that it be at the core of a peace force. Discussions are 
to resume tomorrow. 

</P>
<P>
	East Simmers in Hot, Humid Weather  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Temperatures soared into the 90s today across  
much of the East, making it hot and sticky early in the season. 
Readings rose past the 90-degree mark by early afternoon from the 
Mississippi Valley to the East Coast, and all the way north to New 
England, where Portland, Maine, topped out at 95, a full 10 degrees 
over today's record and the hottest day there since July 1995. In 
North Carolina, a section of Business Interstate 40 was closed at 
Winston-Salem because the pavement buckled in the heat. 

</P>
<P>
	Study of Mentally Ill Proposed  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton asked Congress today to  
ensure that Americans with mental illness get the same benefits 
they have for a broken leg or an asthma attack. Without proper 
treatment, he told a White House conference, ``the loss of human 
potential is staggering.'' The conference was led by Tipper Gore, 
who recently disclosed she suffered clinical depression after her 
son was hit by a car 10 years ago. The conference focused on making 
people understand that mental illness is a sickness much like any 
other and that no one should feel shame or suffer discrimination 
for getting treatment. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Signs Letter for Gore  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After acknowledging concerns about the slow  
start of Al Gore's campaign, President Clinton lent a hand by 
signing a fund-raising letter mailed to 750,000 Democrats by Gore's 
team. Clinton's letter includes a swipe at unidentified ``powerful 
forces'' -- a clear reference to congressional Republicans. ``They 
continue to resist change -- trying, over and over again, to return 
our country to the policies that have failed,'' Clinton wrote. 
Clinton has said he will formally endorse Gore once the vice 
president officially declares his candidacy. 

</P>
<P>
	Study Dispels Doubts on Heart Pills  
</P>
<P>
	STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) -- The second large-scale study of beta  
blockers found they should be prescribed to more heart failure 
patients, researchers said today. The findings, to be published in 
Saturday's British journal Lancet, ought to dissolve lingering 
questions about the drug, the study's chairman said. Beta blockers 
have been used since the 1960s to treat high blood pressure and 
certain heart conditions. Doctors initially doubted they also could 
help congestive heart failure patients, and worried the drugs 
instead could do harm. But in recent years, scientists have found 
that beta blockers, which work by reducing the heart's workload, 
can help heart failure patients. 

</P>
<P>
	Free Voice Mail Service on Internet  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- People juggling a flood of messages from  
e-mail, answering machines, and pagers can organize the calls with 
free services offered through the Internet. Onebox.com announced 
its services today, joining a growing list of companies offering 
free communications on the Web. Users get a free, personal local 
telephone number and e-mail address. Anyone who calls the telephone 
number can leave voice mails and faxes. Users can instantly 
retrieve those messages over the phone or log on to a Web site, 
where they can click on audio files that will play the message. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Closes Up 109.54  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose for a third-straight session today  
as corporate mergers and bargain prices lured investors back to a 
market that is again inching toward record heights. The Dow Jones 
industrial average closed up 109.54 at 10,909.38. The Nasdaq closed 
up 45.80 at 2,524.14. On the NYSE, advancing issues outnumbered 
decliners 1,747-1,255. 

</P>
<P>
	Ban Upheld for Irish Swimmer  
</P>
<P>
	LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- Olympic star Michelle Smith de  
Bruin lost her appeal today of a four-year drug ban, which could 
end the Irish swimmer's career. The Court of Arbitration for Sport 
upheld the decision by FINA, the sport's governing body. Smith was 
suspended Aug. 6 after being found guilty of tampering with a urine 
sample. Smith, who won three gold medals at the 1996 Atlanta 
Olympics, is ineligible for the 2000 Sydney Olympics and the 2001 
world championships. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
