<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 11:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Monday's Supreme Court Actions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The Supreme Court took the following actions Monday:  
</P>
<P>
	--Limited, by a 6-3 vote in an Illinois case, state prison  
inmates' access to federal courts by ruling that federal appeals 
cannot raise claims omitted from appeals to their state's highest 
court. 
</P>
<P>
	--Ruled by a 7-1 vote in a Colorado case that billions of dollars  
worth of methane gas found with coal under federal land is not 
owned by the government and can be claimed by companies that 
purchase the right to drill for natural gas. The court said coal 
bed methane found under the Southern Ute Tribe's reservation is not 
part of the coal the government owns in trust for the tribe. 
</P>
<P>
	--Rejected an appeal made on behalf of about 14,000 current and  
former federal law enforcement officers who say they were 
improperly denied overtime pay. The officers worked between 1984 
and 1995 for agencies including the Customs Service, the Secret 
Service, the Internal Revenue Service and the Drug Enforcement 
Administration. 
</P>
<P>
	--Refused to let federal prosecutors use as evidence the child  
pornography seized from a Georgia man's office. The justices, 
without comment, let stand rulings that deemed the search a 
violation of the constitutional protection against unreasonable 
searches. 
</P>
<P>
	--Turned away an appeal in which environmental groups sought to  
force the government to act more quickly to reduce noise from Grand 
Canyon sightseeing planes. 
</P>
<P>
	--Agreed to use a Florida case to clarify the reach of a federal  
law that allows people to file lawsuits alleging existence of a 
racketeering conspiracy. At issue is whether someone can file such 
a lawsuit even if the harm was caused by an act that did not amount 
to racketeering. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
