<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 12:10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UAW Pleads for Buick City Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) -- Union leaders made a last-ditch plea to  
General Motors Corp. management Monday to replace the aged Buick 
City car assembly plant in Flint, Mich., after it closes next 
month. 
</P>
<P>
	But with declining demand for large cars, it remains unlikely  
the plant will be replaced, GM President G. Richard Wagoner Jr. 
said at the company's annual meeting. GM has been plagued for years 
with too many car plants as more consumers have shifted to light 
trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	Art McGee, president of United Auto Workers Local 599 in Flint,  
noted that the plant recently earned the top award for initial 
vehicle quality from J.D. Power and Associates. 
</P>
<P>
	McGee urged management to keep the work force intact to take  
advantage of the teamwork that resulted in the award. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know they can make money if they put another plant at that  
facility,'' McGee said later. ``We're telling them something that's 
good for the business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wagoner said the Buick City workers were being offered jobs at  
other GM plants and that the automaker ``will continue to pursue 
opportunities'' for other investments in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	Until two weeks ago, the plant made the Buick LeSabre and  
Pontiac Bonneville; pending its closure July 2, the plant is only 
producing Bonnevilles. Production of both full-size sedans is 
shifting to two plants near Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	Though UAW headquarters in Detroit will not make Buick City an  
issue in this year's national contract talks with GM, McGee said 
the local will continue pressing GM to replace the plant, even 
after its closure. 
</P>
<P>
	Wagoner said after the meeting that he expected GM's U.S. market  
share to go up, but that the company won't spend much more in the 
form of discounts to buy share. GM has been struggling since last 
year's devastating parts plant strikes in Flint to get its share 
back above 30 percent, the level at which its North American 
operations are designed to operate. 
</P>
<P>
	GM chairman Jack Smith said little about the pending contract  
talks, which officially get under way next week. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're focused on a good working relationship,'' he said.  
``We're putting a lot of effort into it. The union leadership is as 
well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During his speech to shareholders, Smith said GM will introduce  
14 new vehicles in the U.S. market this year -- about half of which 
``will be innovative concepts aimed at redefining product segments 
and creating new segments.'' 
</P>
<P>
	GM has long been criticized for a lack of leadership in styling  
and innovation. At this year's Detroit auto show, GM showed off 
some small ``crossover'' concept vehicles that combine features of 
cars and sport utility vehicles 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 09:30:30 </DATE_TIME>
