<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 14:20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Honeywell Has Diverse History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- During the Vietnam war, protesters regularly  
circled Honeywell Inc. headquarters and chained themselves near the 
entrance to condemn the manufacture of a shrapnel-producing bomb. 
</P>
<P>
	Police with gas masks used billy clubs and Mace to clear  
protesters gathered outside the 1970 annual meeting as the smell of 
marijuana hung in the air. 
</P>
<P>
	Those days are gone. Honeywell spun off its bomb business in  
1990. After ventures into mainframe computers and 
telecommunications, Honeywell went back to what it did best, making 
control systems for buildings, industry and aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, the company best known for its trademark round  
thermostats is a beloved corporate citizen with roots deep in the 
city's center and deep pockets for funding community projects. 
</P>
<P>
	At Honeywell's annual meeting in April, there was not a single  
question or comment from shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	So community leaders were staggered Monday when Honeywell  
announced it would be acquired by AlliedSignal Inc. and give up its 
Minneapolis headquarters. The combined company will keep the 
Honeywell name, but it will be based at Allied's home of 
Morristown, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	Minneapolis Mayor Sharon Sayles Belton was shocked and said  
there was no opportunity for officials to try to change Honeywell's 
mind. 
</P>
<P>
	Honeywell, with its headquarters building in the middle of a  
decaying part of the city's near south side that is known as the 
Phillips neighborhood, has been working with other Minneapolis 
companies to revitalize the area. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's what people are most worried about,'' Sayles Belton  
said. ``You have people in the Phillips neighborhood moving from 
poverty to self-sufficiency because of the efforts of Honeywell ... 
and will that stop? That can't stop.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Bonsignore -- Honeywell's chief executive, who will lead  
the combined company -- immediately gave assurance that Honeywell 
will not diminish its community and philanthropic support of $7 
million a year. 
</P>
<P>
	It has been a wide-ranging patronage.  
</P>
<P>
	Under a five-year program that began in 1995, Honeywell is  
providing Habitat for Humanity with 4,000 employee volunteers and 
10,000 energy-saving home thermostats, plus annual donations of 
more than $100,000 for construction material. 
</P>
<P>
	Honeywell also houses New Vistas High School within its  
corporate headquarters, giving pregnant and teen-age mothers the 
chance to continue their education. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Honeywell is among companies that support the  
Success by Six program that helps children from infancy to age six, 
and it backs Minnesota HEALS (Hope, Education And Law &AMP; Safety), a 
public-private collaboration that implements crime prevention 
strategies in troubled neighborhoods. 
</P>
<P>
	While the merger is expected to eliminate 1,500 jobs in and  
around Minneapolis, the announcement comes at a time when 
Minnesota's unemployment rate is at a record low 2.1 percent and as 
other companies are begging for workers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unfortunately today's business climate is such that many of  
Minnesota's very successful businesses need to grow in order to 
remain competitive in a global economy,'' said Gov. Jesse Ventura. 
</P>
<P>
	``Often the way to grow is to consolidate or merge with similar  
companies,'' Ventura added. ``Given these circumstances, we are 
fortunate that Honeywell has found a continued path of success and 
will be part of our state for years to come.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Honeywell traces its roots to 1885, when Al Butz invented a  
device in his Minneapolis workshop that used electrical signals to 
adjust the damper of a coal furnace in an attempt to regulate 
heating and make Minnesota winters more livable. 
</P>
<P>
	His Damper Flapper became the foundation of an international  
controls business that had $8.43 billion in sales last year and 
57,500 employees in 95 countries. 
</P>
<P>
	About 45 percent of Honeywell's sales still come from home and  
building controls. Industrial controls make up an almost a third of 
its sales and space and aviation controls account for the rest. 
</P>
<P>
	The company didn't take on the Honeywell name until 1927, when  
Minneapolis Heat Regulator Co. merged with Mark Honeywell Heating 
Specialties Co., of Wabash, Ind., to become Minneapolis-Honeywell 
Regulator Co. The next year, the company went public. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1953, Honeywell introduced the Honeywell Round thermostat.  
The design later was registered as a trademark. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's name was officially changed to Honeywell Inc. in  
1964. 
</P>
<P>
	Honeywell worked with the military during World War II to design  
instruments and control systems for bombers as it was expanding its 
product line. It entered the computer business through acquisitions 
in the 1970s, but fled the field by the early 1990s. In 1990, 
Honeywell renamed its defense and marine systems holdings Alliant 
Techsystems Inc., then shed that business. 
</P>
<P>
	During the 1990s Honeywell has been refocusing on its core  
business of controls and growing through acquisitions in both the 
United States and overseas. In 1995, Honeywell built its first 
manufacturing plant in China to produce heating controls for 
apartment and commercial buildings. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 07:43:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  NATO To Intensify Airstrikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TABANOVCE, Macedonia (AP) -- NATO threatened to intensify its  
airstrikes against Yugoslavia after talks on implementing a Kosovo 
peace plan collapsed early today, putting the entire settlement in 
question. 
</P>
<P>
	In the wake of the talks' failure -- which U.N. and NATO  
officials blamed on Belgrade -- Secretary of State Madeleine 
Albright arrived in Bonn, Germany, for talks today with foreign 
ministers from Russia and the other members of the Group of Eight, 
which drew up the principles of the Kosovo peace plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright also will meet separately with Russian Foreign Minister  
Igor Ivanov. A Russian envoy pressed Yugoslav President Slobodan 
Milosevic to accept the peace deal, but since then Russian leaders 
have bristled at its provisions for a NATO-led peacekeeping force 
in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said the Yugoslav troop  
withdrawal would be brought up at the G-8 meeting, which aims to 
draw up a U.N. resolution endorsing the peace plan. 
</P>
<P>
	The failure to reach agreement after two days of NATO-Yugoslav  
talks threatens the entire Kosovo settlement. NATO and Yugoslav 
officials held low-level ``liaison talks'' in Macedonia today. But 
little was expected from them. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement calls for the complete withdrawal of Yugoslav  
forces from Kosovo and the deployment of international peacekeepers 
to protect more than 855,000 ethnic Albanian refugees when they are 
repatriated. 
</P>
<P>
	The alliance has ``no alternative but to continue and intensify  
the air campaign until such time as the Yugoslavs are prepared to 
implement the agreement fully and without ambiguity,'' said Lt. 
Gen. Michael Jackson, the commander of NATO troops in Macedonia. 
</P>
<P>
	In Brussels, Belgium, a NATO spokesman said the alliance's  
attacks were ``accelerating towards their prior intensity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sorties by allied jets had fallen to below 500 a day -- down from  
nearly 700 at the height of the bombing -- after Milosevic agreed to 
the peace plan on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO officials said the Yugoslavs had put forward an  
unacceptable plan for the troop withdrawal during talks at an air 
base at Kumanovo, Macedonia, that began late Sunday and lasted 
until the early hours today. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said the Yugoslav proposals ``failed  
to guarantee the safe return of the refugees ... and the withdrawal 
of all Yugoslav forces.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he said Jackson was ready to reopen talks ``at any time.''  
Soon afterwards, the liaison talks -- designed primarily to keep 
communication channels open and not to make any decisions -- began 
at Tabanovce on the Yugoslav-Macedonia border. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav Foreign Ministry spokesman Nebojsa Vujovic, who took  
part in the failed meeting, said Belgrade was ready to continue the 
talks. 
</P>
<P>
	British leaders said the Yugoslav proposals aimed to keep a  
significant military presence in Kosovo and they accused Belgrade 
of stalling in the pullback to eliminate evidence of war crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	``There have been reports that behind this foot-dragging is a  
drive to destroy the evidence of their ethnic cleansing before the 
Serb troops depart,'' Defense Secretary George Robertson told a 
briefing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Reports of burning of bodies are all too credible,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Foreign Secretary Robin Cook told BBC television the Yugoslav  
generals wanted to keep ``peacetime levels'' of troops in Kosovo -- 
possibly up to 15,000 soldiers. ``Well, that's a nonstarter,'' he 
said. NATO has said only hundreds of Yugoslav policemen could 
return into the province after the peacekeepers were in place. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, Bacon said another sticking point was a timetable  
for the withdrawal of the estimated 40,000 Serb army and special 
police forces in Kosovo. He said the Yugoslav proposal would have 
``caused a delay in the entrance'' of the NATO-led peacekeeping 
force into Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	There were other problems for NATO. Greece refused permission  
today for 2,200 U.S. Marines to pass through its territory en route 
to Macedonia -- fearing an escalation of anti-NATO protests. The 
Marines were being sent to help set up a possible peacekeeping 
mission in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Air raid sirens sounded early today in Belgrade, the capital,  
for the first time in two days. Alerts were also sounded in Pancevo 
and Novi Sad to the north. But most major attacks were reported in 
Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO said this morning that over the past 24 hours its planes  
hit four tanks, 20 artillery pieces and 17 armored personnel 
carriers in attacks against Serb forces. 
</P>
<P>
	Two waves of NATO jets attacked the Podujevo area, north of  
Kosovo's capital Pristina, early today, the state-run Tanjug news 
agency reported. Attacks were reported in six other Kosovo towns 
overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Tanjug said alliance aircraft launched more than 100 pieces of  
ordnance on targets throughout Kosovo over the last 24 hours. It 
said one person was killed and another wounded Sunday when NATO 
planes struck Donja Budriga village near Gnjilane, southeast of 
Pristina. 
</P>
<P>
	Attacks late Sunday also targeted Yugoslav troops near the  
Albanian border fighting guerrillas of the Kosovo Liberation Army, 
but Yugoslav artillery continued to fire. 
</P>
<P>
	Kosovo is the southernmost province of Serbia, the dominant  
republic in Yugoslavia. NATO's 11-week bombardment was designed to 
get President Slobodan Milosevic to accept a peace deal for Kosovo. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 07:43:48 </DATE_TIME>
