<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 19:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gaines To Coach San Diego's IBL Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- David ``Smokey'' Gaines, who coached Tony Gwynn  
and Michael Cage at San Diego State, is set to return to the San 
Diego basketball scene. 
</P>
<P>
	Gaines will be named coach of San Diego Stingrays of the new  
International Basketball League on Wednesday, a source close to the 
team said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Gaines didn't immediately return a phone call.  
</P>
<P>
	Gaines coached at San Diego State from 1979-87, compiling a  
112-117 record. His 1984-85 team went 23-8 and gained the school's 
only NCAA tournament berth. 
</P>
<P>
	Gwynn was a star point guard from 1978-81 before starring with  
the San Diego Padres. He still holds San Diego State's assists 
records. 
</P>
<P>
	Cage played for the Aztecs from 1981-84 and was a first-round  
draft pick of the NBA's Los Angeles Clippers in 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	Gaines was fired as San Diego State's coach in 1987 and  
reassigned within the athletic department. After he left the school 
in 1989, he worked in private business and as a scout for the 
Denver Nuggets. 
</P>
<P>
	Before coming to San Diego State, Gaines coached for two seasons  
at the University of Detroit, going 47-10 and reaching the NCAAs 
once. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stingrays begin play in November.  
</P>
<P>
	San Diego has had miserable luck with pro basketball. The NBA's  
Rockets moved to Houston in 1971 and the Clippers to Los Angeles in 
1984; the ABA's Conquistadors and Sails folded; and a CBA team that 
moved here from Mexico City folded halfway through the 1995-96 
season. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 16:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Rivers Will Coach Magic As He Played </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Doc Rivers plans to coach the same way he  
played. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm up here giving you no promises, except for I'm going to  
work as hard as I can work to try to make this a success,'' the 
ex-point guard said today after being named coach of the Orlando 
Magic. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's something new. I'm not walking into this saying that I  
know how to do it, that I'll be perfect at it,'' Rivers added. 
``I'm not going to tell you that. What I'll tell you is I'll work 
at it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's more than enough for the Magic, who aren't nervous about  
passing the reigns of the team from a Hall of Fame coach to one 
with no previous experience. 
</P>
<P>
	Rivers, who played with four different teams during a 13-year  
career that ended in 1996, becomes the second-youngest coach in the 
league behind New York's Jeff Van Gundy, who's also 37. 
</P>
<P>
	He inherits a team that could be headed for a massive overhaul  
after overachieving during the lockout-shortened regular season 
only to stumble in the first round of the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides losing former coach Chuck Daly, who retired May 24, the  
Magic face the prospect of starting next season without four-time 
All-Star Penny Hardaway, who has said he'll exercise an option in 
his contract to become a free agent this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``This process many times comes down to a gut feeling, a gut  
instinct of who the right person is,'' general manager John Gabriel 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``With Chuck, we got up here and said he's a guy who's seen it  
all and done it all. Doc's not going to be able to say that. His 
last experience was as a player. So what we did was we researched 
him like a player, talking to trainers and coaches and ex-G.M.'s 
and teammates of his. The information that came back was very 
special.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rivers, who also interviewed for the Washington Wizards'  
coaching vacancy, signed a four-year guaranteed contract worth just 
over $8 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1983 second-round draft pick of Atlanta played 13 seasons  
for the Hawks, Los Angeles Clippers, New York Knicks and San 
Antonio Spurs before retiring in 1996. He's spent the last three 
years working as a television analyst for Turner Sports. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot people ask why. They say: `You're doing TV. You have  
five and 10 seconds to second-guess everyone. If you go to the 
other side, that's going to change ... It's a big risk,''' Rivers 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``My answer is I'm a risk taker. My answer is this is what I  
want to be. This is what I want to do. And who cares about the 
risk. Look at the reward if things pay off. I don't really worry 
about risks. I tend to look at how I can be successful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rivers averaged 10.9 points, 5.7 assists and 3 rebounds per game  
as a player and his teams made the playoffs 10 times. He played for 
the first eight years of his career in Atlanta, was an All-Star in 
1988 and is the Hawks' all-time leader in assists with 3,866. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Rivers has no previous coaching experience, he played  
for some of the league's best, including Pat Riley, Larry Brown and 
Mike Fratello. 
</P>
<P>
	His philosophy and style, Rivers said, probably will reflect  
things he's learned from each of those coaches. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully I can take all their best attributes. But if I had  
to say one thing I can guarantee we'll do, it's play defense,'' he 
said. ``You look at the history of this league. You win by stopping 
people at the end of the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Because of his lack of experience, Rivers intends to hire a  
veteran as his top assistant. Three former NBA coaches -- Dave Wohl, 
Jim Cleamons and Johnny Davis -- reportedly are under consideration. 
</P>
<P>
	There were more questions Monday, though, about how he might get  
along with Hardaway, who sulked at times about his relationship 
with Daly. 
</P>
<P>
	Rivers said he will relate to the players by simply ``telling  
them the truth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no doubt that I'll be challenged at times. I'm new.  
When the substitute teacher comes, you challenge her or him ... I 
think I'm up to that,'' he said. ``I just think you have to sell 
what you're trying to do. And that's win. There's no agenda with 
me. It's only about winning. I want to get to that point as soon as 
possible.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 17:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NRA Tries to Rally Lawmakers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In the wake of the school shootings this  
spring in Colorado, House Republican leaders discussed legislation 
Monday that would restrict youth access to video games, movies and 
other items containing violent as well as sexually explicit 
material, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal also would require the music industry to provide  
stores with copies of song lyrics as a means of allowing adults to 
keep questionable products from their children. 
</P>
<P>
	The provisions were among several prepared by Rep. Henry Hyde,  
R-Ill., chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, for inclusion in 
legislation cracking down on juvenile crime. The measure is 
expected to reach the House floor by next week, and has become the 
focus for responding to the April shooting deaths at Columbine High 
School in Littleton, Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats, however, are attempting to force passage of gun  
control provisions that cleared the Senate, including a requirement 
for mandatory background checks for all gun show sales. The 
National Rifle Association has launched a fresh effort to derail 
that proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	Congressional Republicans have said for weeks that the shootings  
underscored the need for steps to crack down on the often-violent 
images that youngsters are exposed to. 
</P>
<P>
	Depending on its precise wording, the proposal circulated by  
Hyde could spark strong objections from civil libertarians, as well 
as from the manufacturers of video games and other popular consumer 
items. 
</P>
<P>
	A summary of Hyde's proposal, made available to The Associated  
Press, calls for prohibition of the sale or showing of ``explicit 
sexual or violent material which fails to qualify for First 
Amendment protection.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The impact would be to restrict explicitly violent images, much  
as sexually explicit material is now prohibited for minors. 
</P>
<P>
	``The First Amendment is not absolute and does not protect  
obscenity,'' the summary states. ``Furthermore, it is 
constitutionally permissible to accord minors under 17 a more 
restricted right'' to pornography than adults have. 
</P>
<P>
	Several sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said  
Hyde's proposal, which relates to pictures, sculpture, video games, 
movies, books, magazines and other printed matter, were greeted 
enthusiastically by members of the Republican leadership. 
</P>
<P>
	The prohibition is aimed at ``the kind of violence that appeals  
to the prurient, morbid or shameful interest of children without 
social redeeming value for children,'' according to the summary. 
</P>
<P>
	Other provisions drafted by Hyde include the requirement for  
printed lyrics to accompany CDs. 
</P>
<P>
	The gun issue has sparked a counteroffensive by the NRA, which  
is trying to persuade the House to reject a proposal that cleared 
the GOP-controlled Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	The issue, expected on the House floor by midmonth, is ``the  
most critical gun vote in over five years,'' the NRA said in a 
recent mailing urging its members to contact their representatives 
at the Capitol. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation would ``impose a cradle-to-grave massive federal  
regulatory scheme on gun owners throughout America -- and that's no 
exaggeration,'' said the mailing, which requested $35 to $85 for 
membership renewals. A copy was made available to the AP. 
</P>
<P>
	The appeal was crafted in the days after the proposal squeaked  
through the Senate on the strength of a tie-breaking vote cast by 
Vice President Al Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	House GOP leaders have agreed to allow gun-control legislation  
to the floor next week. Aides said that no decision has been made 
whether to have the Judiciary Committee consider the issue before 
the full House votes. 
</P>
<P>
	Gun control became a pressing political issue after the Colorado  
shootings in which two student gunmen killed 12 fellow students and 
a teacher before turning their weapons on themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	With public polls indicating a surge in support for gun control,  
President Clinton responded with a call for fresh restrictions. In 
a political debacle for the majority Republicans, the Senate 
adopted some of them last month in broader legislation relating to 
juvenile crime. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate-passed measure requires instant background checks for  
all gun-show purchases, closing what supporters said was a loophole 
that permitted some transactions to proceed without checks. In 
addition, it outlawed importation of large-capacity ammunition 
clips, required the sale of safety locks with handguns and barred 
juveniles with felony convictions from ever buying guns. 
</P>
<P>
	The outcome in the House is unpredictable, aides in both parties  
said. While Republicans hold a 222-211 majority, with one 
Democratic-leaning independent, Democrats say an estimated two 
dozen to three dozen members of their rank and file, mostly those 
from rural areas, can be expected to oppose some gun-control 
proposals. Likewise, a similar number of Republicans, principally 
those from the Northeast, can be expected to embrace gun control. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 16:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
