<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 02:20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Mob Lawyer To Become Vegas Mayor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- When there's talk of a hit in Las Vegas these  
days, it's normally about slot machines, not the mob. 
</P>
<P>
	This booming city has come a long way since Bugsy Siegel moved  
the mob west with the opening of the Flamingo Hilton on the 
fledgling Las Vegas Strip in 1946. But now a man with ties to Las 
Vegas' checkered past is poised to become its next mayor. 
</P>
<P>
	Flamboyant criminal defense attorney Oscar Goodman, who freely  
admits he was once the mouthpiece to the mob, is known for 
defending characters like Meyer Lansky and Anthony ``Tony the Ant'' 
Spilotro, who once reputedly placed a rival's head in a vise and 
squeezed his eyeballs out. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was just their attorney and their mouthpiece and  
spokesman,'' Goodman said last month. ``When the media took a whack 
at my clients, I would speak on their behalf.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people just have the image of the mob lawyer  
things,'' he said. ``But I, honest to God, believe I'm going to be 
the best mayor Las Vegas ever had.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Goodman's opponent, Arnie Adamsen, said a win by his opponent  
would lend a new mob aura to Las Vegas. ``His past will become our 
future,'' Adamsen said. 
</P>
<P>
	That hasn't seemed to matter much to Las Vegas voters. Goodman,  
59, has emerged as a populist candidate, coming within 277 votes of 
winning the primary election outright in May. Recent polls show him 
coasting to victory in Tuesday's general election. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't so long ago that federal authorities and gambling  
regulators ran the mob out of Las Vegas, transforming the town into 
a top vacation destination where parents feel comfortable bringing 
their children. 
</P>
<P>
	But from 1971 to 1986, brash Chicago enforcer Spilotro ruled Las  
Vegas with Fat Herbie Blitzstein, his longtime pal, at his side. 
Spilotro's role was captured by actor Joe Pesci in the movie 
``Casino,'' and Goodman appeared as himself in the film. 
</P>
<P>
	The mob's influence in Las Vegas waned when Spilotro, facing  
trial on racketeering charges in 1986, was buried alive in an 
Indiana cornfield at the behest of fearful Chicago mob bosses. 
Blitzstein went to prison that year on federal tax and credit fraud 
charges, and was killed in an alleged mob hit two years ago. The 
rest of Spilotro's crew eventually found their way to prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Now Las Vegas is dominated by casino corporations, and the FBI  
says any mobsters left in town are low-level Mafia soldiers. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's not a lot of old Italian mob activity going on,'' said  
Kevin Caudle, a FBI spokesman in Las Vegas. Goodman's election, he 
said, ``probably would not make it better or worse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Against this backdrop, Goodman has campaigned for mayor seeking  
to increase fees on developers to provide more money to refurbish 
older neighborhoods near downtown, and to help solve the city's 
traffic and air pollution woes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm colorful, and that's what got me in the limelight,''  
Goodman told a reporter. ``If I were a podiatrist running for 
mayor, you wouldn't be here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though the mayor has only one of five votes on the City Council  
and doesn't represent the famed Strip or its glittering resorts, 
Goodman has promised to turn the job from one of cutting ribbons 
and settling neighborhood disputes into a position yielding real 
clout. 
</P>
<P>
	That could ``add some pizzazz to an otherwise boring job,'' said  
Lamond Mills, a former U.S. attorney who prosecuted ``Tony the 
Ant'' but supports Goodman. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he's going to give the city a good shaking,'' Mills  
said. ``It's going to be refreshing.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
