<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dupont Cutting Polyester Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) -- DuPont Co. is slashing about 1,400  
positions from its troubled polyester division as a decline in 
demand for its products has forced the company to look for ways to 
reduce costs and restructure the business. 
</P>
<P>
	The company announced Monday that 800 employees and 600  
contractors will be laid off. That accounts for about 14 percent of 
the polyester division's global workforce. About 80 percent of the 
positions are in North America. 
</P>
<P>
	``The deep and prolonged decline in the global polyester market  
is driving fundamental structural change in the industry, making it 
imperative that we take additional steps now to strengthen our 
business,'' said George MacCormack, vice president for DuPont 
Polyester Enterprise. 
</P>
<P>
	The move is expected to result in a pre-tax savings of $90  
million that will begin accruing in the fourth quarter. DuPont 
expects to take a nonrecurring charge in the second quarter of the 
year of four cents a share for employee separation costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Charges related to asset write-offs are expected to cost an  
additional 2 cents to 4 cents a share as part of the restructuring. 
</P>
<P>
	DuPont shares, a component of the Dow industrials, shot up 3.6  
percent following the announcement, rising $2.56 1/4 to close at 
$72.81 1/4 on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent months, DuPont has planned several changes around its  
polyester business worldwide, particularly in the area of creating 
joint partnerships with other companies to manufacture and market 
products. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wilmington, Del.-based company has announced joint ventures  
with Alpek of Mexico and Teijin of Japan for polyester filament in 
the Americas, and with Sabanci of Turkey for polyester 
intermediates, resins and fibers in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	DuPont-Akra Polyester, a joint venture with Alpek for polyester  
staple in the Americas, began operations on April 1. 
</P>
<P>
	The company hopes that its joint ventures will reduce the level  
of exposure it has in a changing market while increasing 
profitability. 
</P>
<P>
	DuPont said in a release today that its employees who have their  
positions terminated can get ``transition packages'' available in 
their country or region. For instance, the company said, U.S. 
employees leaving DuPont will receive a package including payments 
based on length of service, benefit assistance and educational 
assistance. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
