<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AlliedSignal Merges With Honeywell </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- AlliedSignal and Honeywell have set an  
aggressive six-month timetable to merge their operations into a $24 
billion industrial powerhouse that makes everything from aircraft 
landing systems to home thermostats. 
</P>
<P>
	The experience may come in handy. Honeywell, as the combined  
company will be called, is looking for more acquisitions in areas 
as diverse as security access systems and pharmaceutical chemicals. 
</P>
<P>
	All of Honeywell's business areas ``represent an opportunity for  
growth through acquisition,'' said Michael Bonsignore, chairman and 
chief executive officer of Honeywell, who will lead the combined 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were quick to see the potential of the merger, bidding  
up shares of both companies in active trading on the New York Stock 
Exchange. Honeywell's shares rose $7 to $112, a new one-year high. 
AlliedSignal's stock, one of the components of the Dow industrials, 
jumped $4.43 1/2 to $62.81 1/4 and helped the Dow soar. 
</P>
<P>
	Since AlliedSignal is paying for Honeywell by issuing 236.3  
million shares of stock, the 7.6 percent rise AlliedSignal's shares 
increased the value of the deal by about $1 billion from when it 
was announced, to total $14.84 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	But first things first. AlliedSignal and Honeywell have to close  
Honeywell's headquarters in Minneapolis and move it to Morristown, 
N.J., where AlliedSignal is based. They have to cut 4,500 jobs and 
combine their work forces of 120,000 people in more than 95 
countries. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger needs regulatory approval in Europe and America, and  
top executives still have to sort out their different opinions on 
rewarding shareholders with dividends. 
</P>
<P>
	Time is of the essence.  
</P>
<P>
	``There is a clear pattern between companies that have moved  
through integration quickly, and the companies that have been 
successful,'' said John Harbison, a vice president for Booz-Allen 
Hamilton, who has written extensively on the topic. 
</P>
<P>
	AlliedSignal and Honeywell have already formed an integration  
team, which will spend the next three months creating a plan, and 
put it into action within three months after the deal closes. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first round of job cuts, Honeywell will lay off 1,000 of  
its headquarters staff, and the combined companies will eliminate 
another 1,000 positions. 
</P>
<P>
	In the second round, an additional 2,500 positions will go.  
</P>
<P>
	The synergies will save the company $500 million a year starting  
in 2002. But workers like Mike Lawrow see the faces of their 
colleagues in that number. 
</P>
<P>
	After 20 years with Honeywell, the news of the impending layoffs  
hit him hard. Standing outside the company's headquarters, smoking 
a cigarette, Lawrow said, ``There are a few people who are going to 
gain from it. A lot of us are going to lose.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mashing two corporate cultures together will force both company  
to make painful sacrifices. In exchange for keeping AlliedSignal's 
headquarters, for example, the company had to give up its name. 
</P>
<P>
	Regulators are expected to review the merger with a fine-tooth  
comb, but according to Bonsignore, AlliedSignal and Honeywell only 
overlap in two areas: collision avoidance systems and weather 
radar, which account for about $250 million in annual sales, or a 
little more than 1 percent of the combined business. 
</P>
<P>
	Shareholders of both companies clearly support the deal, though  
the Honeywell and AlliedSignal have yet to work out their dividend 
policies. Lawrence Bossidy, chairman and chief executive officer of 
AlliedSignal, promised shareholders at the annual meeting in April 
that he would raise the dividend 15 percent next year. On Monday, 
he said, those plans are now up in the air. 
</P>
<P>
	If the companies can combine their operations fast and  
effectively, the new Honeywell will be in a strong position to 
serve its largest clients, which include Boeing Co., Airbus 
Industrie and the U.S. military. One of the motives behind 
AlliedSignal's acquisition of Honeywell is that aircraft makers are 
reducing the number of parts suppliers they work with, and 
demanding those suppliers provide complete solutions. 
</P>
<P>
	``They will have strategic influence to ... dominate in their  
core markets for the next decade, said Nick Haymen, an analyst at 
Prudential Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	While the aerospace business will account for 40 percent of the  
combined company's business, the merger also gives the new 
Honeywell a stronger position in several other industries -- 
including specialty chemicals and auto parts -- which will insulate 
the company from a downturn in any one market. 
</P>
<P>
	Bosignore, who signed a five-year employment contract, plans to  
improve that level of protection by expanding in many areas. While 
he wouldn't name names, Haymen said, the new Honeywell ``can make 
$10 billion in acquisitions over the next three years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Investors started placing their bets on the next target, which  
also may be in the cross hairs of another competitor trying to keep 
up with Honeywell. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, shares of Rockwell International Corp. rose $2 to  
$61, while Litton Industries Inc. saw its stock rise $3.87 1/2 to 
$73.87 1/2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
