<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fla. Judge Acquits 3 of Fund Misuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- A judge on Monday acquitted three men accused of  
stealing $1.3 million in Port of Miami revenue and spending it on 
lingerie, vacations, bar tabs and Super Bowl tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	The defendants, who were also accused of giving $120,000 to the  
Democratic National Committee, were not guilty of misusing funds 
because the money never belonged to the government, U.S. District 
Judge Donald Middlebrooks ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling came in the middle of the trial of Carmen Lunetta,  
longtime director of the port, the nation's eighth largest in terms 
of cargo, and two others. 
</P>
<P>
	The three men were charged with misusing funds belonging to  
Miami-Dade County. But U.S. District Judge Donald Middlebrooks 
agreed with the defense that until the money was turned over to 
Miami-Dade County, it still belonged to the defendants. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, the judge wrote, ``The government has presented  
substantial evidence of greed and public corruption, the placement 
of private interests over those of the public.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors had no immediate comment.  
</P>
<P>
	The two other defendants were Calvin Grigsby, the owner of  
Fiscal Operations Inc., which operated cranes at the port; and Neal 
Harrington, a part-owner of a stevedoring company. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said stevedoring companies paid Fiscal Operations  
for crane time, and Fiscal Operations turned the money over to 
Miami-Dade County. However, Fiscal Operations first deducted 
$150,000 a year plus expenses. Prosecutors said those expenses were 
padded. 
</P>
<P>
	Grigsby faces trial next month on charges of arranging $350,000  
in kickbacks to two Miami-Dade executives in return for county bond 
business. He owned Grigsby Brandford &AMP; Co., the nation's largest 
minority-owned municipal bond underwriter until it closed in 1996. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
