<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Remains From Vietnam are Identified </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The remains of two U.S. Marine aviators who  
were unaccounted for from the Vietnam War have been identified and 
will be returned to their families for burial in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon announced Monday the positive identification of  
Marine Capt. Robert A. Holt, of Reading, Mass., and Marine Capt. 
John A. Lavoo, of Pueblo, Colo. They were flying a combat mission 
over Quang Binh Province, North Vietnam, on Sept. 19, 1968, when 
their F-4B Phantom jet crashed with no trace of survivors. 
</P>
<P>
	Hostile forces in the area precluded a search-and-rescue effort  
at the time. The remains were recovered in a series of excavations 
by a joint U.S.-Vietnamese team in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	With the accounting of these two men, there are now 2,061  
Americans listed by the Pentagon as unaccounted for from the 
Vietnam War. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
