<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded  
heavily today on the New York Stock Exchange, Nasdaq Stock Market, 
and American Stock Exchange. 

</P>
<P>
                               *NYSE    	

</P>
<P>
 *Columbia Energy Group, up 7 7/16 at 63 3/16  
</P>
<P>
 *NiSource Inc., down 5/8 at 27 9/16 
</P>
<P>
	NiSource launched a hostile bid for Columbia, a $5.7 billion  
deal that would make NiSource into one of the nation's biggest 
natural gas companies. Nisource's primary business is the 
distribution of electricity, natural gas and water. 

</P>
<P>
 *Burnham Pacific Properties Inc., up 1 7/16 at 12 9/16    	
</P>
<P>
	Schottenstein Stores Corp., a closely held retailer and real  
estate owner, is expected to make a bid for Burnham, a San 
Diego-based real estate investment trust. Schottenstein is expected 
to offer more than $1 billion in stock and assumed debt. 

</P>
<P>
 *British Steel PLC, down 2 at 23 3/4    	
</P>
<P>
	British Steel and Dutch metals producer Koninklijke Hoogovens NV  
announced today they plan to merge in a $6.5 billion deal that will 
create the world's third largest steel maker and Europe's biggest. 

</P>
<P>
                              *NASDAQ   	

</P>
<P>
 *CMGI Inc., up 12 3/4 at 107    	
</P>
<P>
	Dell Computer Corp. and Microsoft Corp. have both taken stakes  
in CMGI's NaviSite Inc. unit in exchange for their products. CMGI 
provides marketing services and invests in Internet and interactive 
media technologies. 

</P>
<P>
 *Mahoning National Bancorp Inc., up 10 3/4 at 42 1/4  
</P>
<P>
 *Sky Financial Group Inc., down 2 1/16 at 27 1/4 
</P>
<P>
	Sky plans to acquire Mahoning in a deal valued at $307 million.  
Once the merger is completed, Sky will have 230 bank branches in 
Ohio, western Pennsylvania, West Virginia and Michigan. 

</P>
<P>
 *TheStreet.com, up 3 1/16 at 32 5/8    	
</P>
<P>
	Investment firms Goldman Sachs, SG Cowen and Hambrecht &AMP; Quist  
launched coverage of the company. TheStreet.com, a financial news 
Web site, should benefit from investors' increasing appetite for 
business news, the firms said. 

</P>
<P>
 *Jevic Transportation Inc., up 3 1/16 at 13 13/16    	
</P>
<P>
	Yellow Corp., seeking to expand its regional trucking  
operations, has offered to buy Jevic for $160 million, plus about 
$40 million in assumed debt. Jevic is a motor carrier based in 
Delanco, N.J. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
