<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 10:51:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Collapse of Kosovo Talks May Be Ploy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- The collapse of talks in Macedonia to  
implement the Kosovo peace plan is a move by Yugoslavia and Russia 
to play for time in hopes Russia can force changes in the agreement 
when it goes to the U.N. Security Council. 
</P>
<P>
	The strategy appears aimed at undercutting what Belgrade  
considers the most unpalatable part of the accord: the presence of 
U.S. and other NATO troops with sweeping authority to ensure the 
safety of returning ethnic Albanian refugees and effectively run 
Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Belgrade is also gambling that the United States and other NATO  
powers will be unable to escalate the air bombardment significantly 
because of growing opposition to the campaign, especially after the 
euphoria following President Slobodan Milosevic's surprise 
acceptance of the plan Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The strategy became clear during today's meeting in Germany  
between foreign ministers of the world's seven leading industrial 
powers and Russia, who jointly put together the peace plan that 
Milosevic accepted. Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari said today 
Milosevic assured him he still stands by the agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	The meeting in Germany is to work on a resolution for the U.N.  
Security Council to authorize the peacekeeping force. British 
officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the Russian 
delegation was objecting to language affirming that NATO would be 
at the core of a peacekeeping force. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russians were also objecting to an article in the resolution  
that would empower peacekeepers to take ``robust'' military 
measures to ensure peace. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if Moscow fails to win agreement among the other members of  
the group of eight nations in the drafting stage, the Russians and 
the Chinese could block implementation once the 15-member Security 
Council begins consideration of the accord. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin played a key role in  
drafting the plan and selling it to Milosevic, Russian generals in 
his delegation spoke openly of their opposition to some of the 
terms, especially NATO's leading role in the peacekeeping force. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian President Boris Yeltsin also has not come to the defense  
of the plan hammered out by his hand-picked special envoy. 
</P>
<P>
	The meeting Sunday in Macedonia was called for the Yugoslavs to  
sign off on a timetable for the complete withdrawal of all their 
soldiers, police, border guards and paramilitary forces from 
Kosovo, a province in Serbia, Yugoslavia's main republic. 
</P>
<P>
	Once the alliance verifies that a meaningful withdrawal is  
underway, NATO would suspend the bombing campaign and move in the 
vanguard of a 50,000-member peacekeeping force ``with NATO at its 
core.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After all Yugoslav forces have gone and the air campaign  
terminated, ``hundreds but not thousands'' of Serb forces would be 
allowed back into Kosovo to protect religious shrines, clear 
minefields and other limited duties. 
</P>
<P>
	That, in effect, would remove Belgrade's control of a province  
which Serbs consider the heartland of their culture. The presence 
of thousands of NATO troops would represent a deep humiliation for 
Serbs. 
</P>
<P>
	Such a humiliation could lead to the collapse of the Milosevic  
regime, although removing the Yugoslav leader -- who has been 
indicted for war crimes -- was never a stated goal of the campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Throughout the protracted negotiations leading to the agreement,  
Belgrade had insisted it would accept only a lightly armed 
``international security presence'' under United Nations control. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia appeared to torpedo the talks to help its long-time  
Slavic ally. 
</P>
<P>
	After the first day of talks Saturday, NATO spokesmen spoke  
optimistically of progress -- but the Russian delegation did not 
appear. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, however, Russian Lt. Gen. Yevgeny Barmyantsev showed  
up three hours into the talks. According to the ITAR-Tass news 
agency, Barmyantsev said Moscow believed that a peacekeeping force 
could only be installed on the basis of a U.N. Security Council 
resolution. That could take weeks to hammer out. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russian agency said his remarks prompted NATO generals ``to  
ask for a `time-out' so they could hold private consultations.'' 
The talks were suspended 7 p.m. Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	About eight hours later, the NATO commander in Macedonia, Lt.  
Gen. Michael Jackson announced that the talks had broken down. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Robert H. Reid is The Associated Press chief of  
bureau in Vienna. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
