<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Move Higher / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices rallied early  
today on the Chicago Board of Trade with soybeans up more than 8 
cents a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say the market appeared to be reacting to reports of  
continued above-normal temperatures in the Midwest over the next 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	Hot, dry weather could damage early planted crops, eventually  
resulting in smaller crops and higher prices. 
</P>
<P>
	While wheat futures also jumped, some say the rise might not  
hold since dry weather will aid in the harvest of winter wheat. 
</P>
<P>
	In early trading, wheat for July delivery rose 4 cents to $2.60 3/4  
a bushel; July corn was up 3 3/4 cent to $2.24 1/2 a bushel; July oats 
rose 1 1/2 cents to $1.25 a bushel; and July soybeans surged 8 1/2 cents 
to $4.73 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, meat and livestock futures were mixed in early  
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle rose .10 cent to 65 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell .12 cents to 76.65 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
fell .10 cent to 51.90 cents a pound; and July pork bellies fell 
.60 cent to 52.85 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
