<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Airways, Union Strike Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- Nearly four years after the contract  
between US Airways and a mechanics' union came up for 
renegotiation, the two sides reached a tentative agreement, the 
airline said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal with the International Association of Machinists and  
Aerospace Workers covers 7,000 workers in mechanical and related 
jobs. The agreement is subject to ratification by the union 
membership. 
</P>
<P>
	After settling a number of issues, US Airways and the union  
sought the National Mediation Board's help in resolving the 
remaining issues. US Airways spokesman Rick Weintraub refused to 
say what those issues were, and calls to the union offices in 
Washington, D.C., were not answered. 
</P>
<P>
	The contract came up for renegotiation on Oct. 1, 1995,  
Weintraub said, and employees have continued to work under the 
existing contract since then. 
</P>
<P>
	The tentative agreement was reached early Sunday morning.  
</P>
<P>
	Provisions of the new agreement also will cover mechanical and  
related workers at the US Airways Shuttle. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleet service employees at US Airways, who also are represented  
by the IAM, ratified their contract with the airline on April 1, 
1999. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
