<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Stocks Move Higher; Dow Up 104.48 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose today as corporate mergers helped  
distract investors from lingering concerns about inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	At 2 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 104.48 at 10,904.32. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's  
500 index was up 3.47 at 1,331.22, and the Nasdaq composite index 
was up 46.17 at 2,524.51. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume was light as traders already began looking ahead to  
Friday, when the government's producer price index is expected to 
offer signals about inflation and perhaps an indication of whether 
the Federal Reserve will raise interest rates to keep the economy 
from overheating. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks have slipped in the weeks since the Fed warned it might  
raise rates, and volume has been lower than normal as Wall Street 
weighs the impact of a possible increase. On Friday, the Dow made 
one of its strongest rallies in weeks, gaining 136.15 to close at 
10,799.84. 
</P>
<P>
	Major corporate mergers stimulated trading today. AlliedSignal  
rose 5 1/4 to 63 5/8 and Honeywell rose 8 7/8 to 113 7/8 after the companies 
announced they will merge, creating an aerospace 
parts-and-electronics conglomerate. 
</P>
<P>
	A pair of Salt Lake City banks, First Security Corp. and Zions  
Bancorp, will merge in a deal worth $5.9 billion. First Security 
rose 6 to 24 5/8, and Zions fell 6 1/8 to 59 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	American Express rose 2 9/16 to 127 13/16 after Prudential  
Securities raised its rating on the stock. Prudential cited rising 
credit card use in the United States and overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	The broad base of good corporate news heartened Wall Street.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's one of those sessions where all is right with the  
world,'' said Ned Collins, a trader at Daiwa Securities America. 
</P>
<P>
	Airline stocks couldn't keep up with the market's rally today.  
UAL Corp., the parent of United Air Lines, warned analysts late 
Friday that its second-quarter earnings will fall below well 
estimates. Its shares fell 1 11/16 to 64 1/8, and weighed down several 
other airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 424.8 million 
shares, well behind Friday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index rose 2.67 to 637.19, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index was down 5.37 at 775.61. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
