Gold(final) -    $266.10    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Mon.

</P>
<P>
	Ore., N.H. Lead in Economic Growth  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Oregon and New Hampshire enjoyed the fastest  
economic growth among the states in 1997. A Commerce Department 
report broke down the nation's gross domestic product, the total 
output of goods and services, to show the amount contributed by 
each state. The biggest state gains in economic output were enjoyed 
by residents of Oregon, where the economy expanded by 7.6 percent, 
and New Hampshire, with an increase 7.5 percent in current dollars. 
At the other end of the scale, Hawaii saw its economic output 
shrink in 1997, down 0.2 percent, as the state's economy was hit 
hard by fallout from the Asian currency crisis. 

</P>
<P>
	UAW Pleads for Plant in Buick City  
</P>
<P>
	WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) -- Union leaders made a plea to General  
Motors management today to replace the aged Buick City car assembly 
plant in Flint, Mich., after it closes next month. But with 
declining demand for large cars, it remains unlikely the plant will 
be replaced, GM President G. Richard Wagoner Jr. said. GM has been 
plagued for years with too many car plants as more consumers have 
shifted to light trucks. Art McGee, president of United Auto 
Workers Local 599 in Flint, noted that the plant recently earned 
the top award for initial vehicle quality from J.D. Power and 
Associates. McGee urged management to keep the work force intact to 
take advantage of the teamwork that resulted in the award. GM stock 
rose 3/4 to 69 1/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Europeans End End Web Boycott  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- European Internet users have ended a 24-hour  
boycott of the World Wide Web that aimed to win a reduction in 
local telephone charges. The next stage in their campaign is to 
enroll the support of political leaders, British participants said 
today. The Campaign for Unmetered Telecommunications said Internet 
users in 15 European countries coordinated efforts to win a 
reduction in costs, including a flat-rate charge for local calls, 
similar to that in the United States. 

</P>
<P>
	NiSource Wants Columbia Energy  
</P>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- NiSource launched a hostile bid for  
Columbia Energy Group today, a $5.7 billion deal that if successful 
would make NiSource into one of the nation's biggest natural gas 
companies. The unsolicited bid came after a formal offer to 
Columbia's board of directors was rejected and Columbia's 
executives refused to discuss merging with NiSource. NiSource stock 
fell 5/8 to 27 9/16, while Columbia Energy's rose 7 7/16 to 63 3/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Rules Feds Don't Own Gas  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Billions of dollars worth of methane gas found  
with coal under federal land is not owned by the government and can 
be claimed by companies that purchase the right to drill for 
natural gas, the Supreme Court ruled today. The 7-1 decision 
resolved a big-stakes dispute between Amoco and an Indian tribe in 
Colorado. The court agreed with claims by Amoco Production Co., a 
subsidiary of BP Amoco, that its contractual right to take natural 
gas from the reservation land allows it to take the methane gas 
also. The justices ruled that coal bed methane found with coal 
under the Southern Ute Tribe's reservation should not be considered 
part of the coal the federal government owns in trust for the 
tribe. 

</P>
<P>
	WTO Members To Help Poorer Countries  
</P>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- The Netherlands said today that it and other  
European countries are spearheading efforts to create an 
independent center to give poorer countries the clout to defend 
their interests in disputes before the World Trade Organization. 
The Advisory Center for WTO Law will provide legal advice on trade 
law to least-developed and developing countries at a much lower 
cost than the usual commercial rates. The center would be entirely 
independent of the WTO and would employ lawyers to help countries 
take cases through the organization's dispute settlement procedure. 
It would also provide training to help give countries the expertise 
to fight their own cases in the future. 

</P>
<P>
	Kasparov To Play Chess Match on Web  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- World chess champion Garry Kasparov, who lost a  
tournament two years ago to a computer, now is taking on the 
Internet. Kasparov has cut a deal with Microsoft to play a match 
this summer against a ``world team'' made up of anyone who comes to 
a Microsoft Internet site and votes for suggested moves against the 
Russian grandmaster. The world team will be guided by five young 
chess experts, who will suggest possible moves and tactics. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic numbers:  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: Productivity  
</P>
<P>
	Thursday: Weekly jobless claims  
</P>
<P>
	Friday: Producer prices  

  	   	
</P>
