<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 07:44:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Serbs Argue Over Withdrawals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- Procedural talks on withdrawal of Serb  
troops from Kosovo are likely to resume, but Yugoslav commanders 
are refusing to draw down to the levels agreed to last week, a 
senior U.S. official said today. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, even if some procedural issues are addressed in  
Macedonia there is no basis for assuring the safe return of ethnic 
Albanian refugees, said the official, speaking on condition of 
anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, Russian  
Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov and six other foreign ministers worked 
on the text of a U.N. resolution that State Department spokesman 
James P. Rubin said directs the Serbs to ``stop putting forward 
proposals that are inconsistent with the agreements they signed'' 
Thursday in Belgrade. 
</P>
<P>
	The Serbs say they are required to withdraw only to  
``peacetime'' levels, or about 15,000, the official said. The NATO 
allies, however, are demanding a total pullout, with a few hundred 
Serb troops then permitted to return as a symbolic sign of Serb 
sovereignty in the province. 
</P>
<P>
	Diplomacy continued, meanwhile, with Albright and the other  
foreign ministers from the G-8 grouping working paragraph by 
paragraph on a resolution that Rubin said would endorse having NATO 
at the core of the peacekeeping force that would help hundreds of 
thousands of ethnic Albanians return to their homes. 
</P>
<P>
	Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari, who helped reach the  
settlement in Belgrade, led the discussions. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we need is a Security Council resolution that adopts  
arrangements that are necessary for implementation'' of the 
agreement, Rubin said. 
</P>
<P>
	The diplomats from eight nations also are working on a civilian  
administration for the beleaguered province. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright flew here from Washington for the sessions, and also to  
talk with three ethnic Albanian leaders. Rubin flatly blamed the 
Yugoslavs for the impasse. 
</P>
<P>
	He said that in their talks in Macedonia, Yugoslav military  
leaders had failed to give NATO commanders an adequate plan for the 
withdrawal of Serb troops from Kosovo. Rubin said NATO's bombing 
campaign would continue until they did. 
</P>
<P>
	But, he said, ``We will continue to make diplomatic efforts with  
our G-8 colleagues towards a peaceful resolution of this 
conflict.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Participating with Albright and Ivanov in the talks are the  
foreign ministers of Britain, Canada, France, Germany, Italy and 
Japan. Albright scheduled a private session with Ivanov later 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	The G-8 meeting was delayed a day, apparently because of  
Russia's disapproval of the continued NATO airstrikes. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivanov, arriving for the talks, accused NATO of trying to settle  
``political issues of principle'' in the talks with the Yugoslav 
military, including ``the format of international forces in 
Kosovo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Only the U.N. Security Council has the prerogative to decide  
these issues,'' the Tass news agency quoted Ivanov as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	In Paris, French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine said the  
sequence of the Serbs' withdrawal from Kosovo, including their 
demand to have a U.N. Security Council resolution before signing a 
peace plan, led to the collapse of the talks. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to fine-tune the sequence of events,'' Vedrine told  
France-2 TV, adding, ``We have to eliminate everything that can be 
used as a pretext.'' 
</P>
<P>
	En route to Germany, Rubin said only a few hundred Serb troops  
would be permitted to remain in Kosovo. He called it a symbolic 
force. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, he said the settlement did not promise  
independence to the ethnic Albanians. Albright is likely to stress 
that point in her talks with the Albanian leaders, Ibrahim Rugova, 
Hashim Thaci and Rexhep Qosja. 
</P>
<P>
	The G-8 framed principles for a settlement. But the terms  
accepted by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic were tougher 
terms dictated by NATO. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the presence of Russian officials in G-8 meetings gives  
them an opportunity to play peacemaker and to seek conciliation for 
the Serbs, with whom they have historic ties. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
