<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Savings Likely if Kids Get Flu Shot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Vaccinating all schoolchildren against the flu  
would save hundreds of millions of dollars annually, mainly in lost 
work time of parents who stay home with sick youngsters and end up 
catching the virus themselves, researchers reported Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Vaccination results in a net savings of $4 to $35 per child,  
according to an analysis published Monday in the journal 
Pediatrics. The savings depend on whether the child is taken to a 
doctor during work hours by a parent or gets immunized as part of a 
group, such as at school. 
</P>
<P>
	``Children are efficient spreaders of the disease and a major  
factor in the introduction of influenza into households,'' the 
researchers noted. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers used data on infection rates, wages of  
caretakers and costs of immunization to make their estimates. 
</P>
<P>
	If the estimates were applied to Census Bureau figures, which  
project about 51.8 million school-age children in 2000, the total 
savings could range from $207.2 million to $1.8 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers, led by Terry White of Virginia Commonwealth  
University School of Medicine in Richmond, said that although 
serious complications from flu vaccine have occasionally occurred 
in adults, none have been reported in children. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
