<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 15:20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Penguins Seek Way Out of 'Lease' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- It looks like a lease, acts like a lease and  
even is described as a ``lease'' 17 times in documents provided by 
the Pittsburgh Penguins. 
</P>
<P>
	But the financially troubled team today asked a judge to  
reclassify its deal with sports facility manager SMG Inc. of 
Philadelphia as a $24 million loan. 
</P>
<P>
	Reclassifying the lease potentially would reduce the amount SMG  
-- the Penguins' longtime landlord at the Civic Arena -- will be 
repaid when the team returns to normal business operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Friday, U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Bernard Markovitz invalidated  
the lease, which was negotiated in 1991, renegotiated in 1994 and 
runs through 2007. It has been described in court as the worst 
lease in the NHL. 
</P>
<P>
	The rent has varied over the years with various payment factors  
such as SMG getting 10 to 14 percent of ticket revenue. SMG was 
paid $2.274 million by the Penguins in 1996-97. 
</P>
<P>
	But before the deal was signed in 1991, Penguins owner Edward  
DeBartolo was paying $600,000 in annual rent to the Public 
Auditorium Authority. 
</P>
<P>
	Markovitz's decision would allow for penalties to be paid to SMG  
if he decides the lease was really a lease and not a loan. If the 
judge decides the lease was substantially a loan, SMG could be 
lumped in with the businesses that have the least rights in the 
case -- the unsecured creditors, including the companies that supply 
the Penguins with pucks and towels. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins asked Markovitz to rule that the multipart deal is  
not a lease. The judge gave no indication when he would make a 
decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``At all times, these documents have been described as leases,  
signed as leases, recorded as leases and held out to various third 
parties that they are in fact leases,'' SMG attorney Daniel Shapira 
said. ``There is nothing to show that they are anything but 
leases.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the Penguins arranged for Antonio G. Tavares, the former SMG  
executive who is now president of the company that runs the Mighty 
Ducks and Anaheim Angels, to testify that the deal was unusual for 
a lease. 
</P>
<P>
	The $24 million up front was atypical for the industry, Tavares  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	That money guaranteed SMG percentages of revenue from parking,  
jerseys, food and other items at the Civic Arena. Also, the 
Penguins had to repay SMG for expenses such as the Zamboni and the 
ticket office staff. 
</P>
<P>
	``The indications are that it doesn't look like a lease,''  
Tavares testified from suburban Los Angeles by a video connection. 
</P>
<P>
	The lease was valuable to the Penguins over the years. Team  
attorney Greg Cribbs said it was used as collateral to get loans 
from banks. 
</P>
<P>
	SMG and NHL Hall of Fame member Mario Lemieux each have offered  
competing plans for running the team and are negotiating to try to 
resolve their differences. The Fox Sports Net Pittsburgh broadcast 
company is backing SMG's plan. 
</P>
<P>
	The NHL offered a backup plan that would shut the team down.  
League officials said they want Lemieux, who as the Penguins center 
led the team to two Stanley Cups in the early 1990s, to run the 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Monday, Pittsburgh business leaders unveiled a marketing  
campaign aimed at helping the Penguins sell season tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is my 10th year here. Any time we've had some adversity,  
we've always come back stronger,'' Penguins general manager Craig 
Patrick said. ``This is the biggest hill we've had to climb. Once 
we get to the top, we'll be a really strong franchise.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 08:20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> State Inmates' Court Access Limited </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today limited federal court  
access for state prison inmates challenging their prosecutions. The 
6-3 decision was a defeat for an Illinois man who has spent his 
adult life behind bars for a rape conviction. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices ruled that state prisoners seeking a federal  
court's help generally cannot pursue claims that were not raised on 
direct appeal to their state's highest court. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling continued a decade-long trend in which the nation's  
highest court has narrowed state inmates' access to federal courts. 
Congress also has limited such access in a 1996 law aimed primarily 
at speeding up the executions of those convicted criminals 
sentenced to death. 
</P>
<P>
	In other court action today, the court:  
</P>
<P>
	--Ruled that billions of dollars worth of methane gas found with  
coal under federal land is not owned by the government and can be 
claimed by companies that purchase the right to drill for natural 
gas. The 7-1 decision resolved a big-stakes dispute between Amoco 
and an Indian tribe in Colorado. Amoco won. 
</P>
<P>
	--Turned away without comment an appeal from environmental groups  
that want the government to act more quickly to reduce noise from 
sightseeing planes flying over the Grand Canyon. The court turned 
away the groups' argument that the government has failed to meet 
the legally required deadlines for reducing such aircraft noise. 
</P>
<P>
	--Rejected an appeal by about 14,000 current and former federal  
law enforcement officers who say they improperly were denied 
overtime pay. The court, without comment, turned away the officers' 
effort to collect another four years' worth of overtime pay in 
addition to two years of pay they were granted in a settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	--Refused to let federal prosecutors use as evidence child  
pornography seized from a Georgia man's office in what lower courts 
called an illegal search. The court, without comment, rejected an 
appeal in which prosecutors argued that the constitutional 
protection against unreasonable searches does not apply to an area 
of someone's office outside their own work space. 
</P>
<P>
	In the state prisoner decision, Justice Sandra Day O'Connor  
wrote for the court that, ``State prisoners must give the state 
courts one full opportunity to resolve any constitutional issues by 
invoking one complete round of the state's established appellate 
review process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She noted the ruling could increase the number of appeals to  
states' top courts, acknowledging, ``This increased burden may be 
unwelcome in some state courts.'' But O'Connor said today's ruling 
does not require inmates to pursue an appeal if higher state court 
review is not available. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision means Darren Boerckel will not get a federal court  
hearing on part of his multifaceted challenge to his 1976 
convictions in the rape of an 87-year-old woman. 
</P>
<P>
	Boerckel, who as 17 when the crime occurred, contends his signed  
confession was unlawfully obtained by police in Montgomery County, 
Ill. He also says he was denied adequate legal help and contends 
that his trial was tainted by prosecutorial misconduct. 
</P>
<P>
	Boerckel's convictions for rape, burglary and aggravated battery  
drew prison sentences of 20 to 60 years. 
</P>
<P>
	His first appeal, which raised seven issues, was rejected by a  
state appeals court. Because the Illinois Supreme Court discourages 
litigants from raising every conceivable claim in their appeals, 
Boerckel's ensuing appeal to that court raised only three of the 
seven issues. The state Supreme Court refused to review his case. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, Boerckel filed an appeal in federal court. The  
so-called habeas corpus petition raised issues that had been 
included in his state appellate court case but had been left out 
when he sought the Illinois Supreme Court's help. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal trial judge refused to consider the merits of several  
issues raised in the appeal, ruling that they had not been 
``exhausted'' in state courts. The judge also denied Boerckel's 
remaining claims that had been raised before the state's top court. 
</P>
<P>
	But the 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reinstated Boerckel's  
federal appeal last year, sparking a Supreme Court appeal by state 
prosecutors. 
</P>
<P>
	The Supreme Court today said the 7th Circuit court was wrong.  
</P>
<P>
	O'Connor wrote that inmates like Boerckel must ``use the state's  
established appellate review procedures'' before presenting their 
claims to a federal court. 
</P>
<P>
	Her opinion was joined by Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and  
Justices Antonin Scalia, Anthony M. Kennedy, David H. Souter and 
Clarence Thomas. 
</P>
<P>
	Justices John Paul Stevens, Stephen G. Breyer and Ruth Bader  
Ginsburg dissented. Writing for the three, Stevens said the court 
requires inmates ``in states like Illinois to present to the state 
supreme court every federal issue that ... might possibly warrant 
some relief if brought in a future federal habeas petition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The case is O'Sullivan vs. Boerckel, 97-2048.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 13:40:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sen. Opposes Campaign Finance Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A leading opponent of proposed campaign  
finance revisions asked the Supreme Court on Monday to declare 
unconstitutional the 25-year-old $1,000 limit on contributions to 
federal campaigns by individuals. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., argued in a friend-of-court brief  
that contribution limits, adopted by Congress after Watergate, have 
a ``severe adverse effect'' on the ability of candidates to raise 
the increasing amounts of cash needed to finance a run for federal 
office. 
</P>
<P>
	In today's economy, the $1,000 is worth $302, according to the  
brief, filed as part of a Missouri campaign-finance dispute the 
high court will resolve next term. 
</P>
<P>
	Adjusted for inflation, the individual limit should be $3,306,  
the filing said. It would be $4,600 if adjusted both for inflation 
and increases in voting-age population. 
</P>
<P>
	McConnell, chairman of the National Republican Senatorial  
Committee, which raises money and recruits Republican Senate 
candidates, said ``broad agreement'' for higher contribution limits 
exists, including among many of those who want to change the 
system, such as President Clinton and Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a 
2000 presidential hopeful. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone knows that purchasing power has been eroded,''  
McConnell said at a news conference on the Supreme Court steps, 
across from the Capitol. ``Clearly this is a problem that everyone 
can agree needs to be addressed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Supreme Court upheld campaign contribution limits in 1976,  
two years after they were adopted by Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics contend that higher contribution limits would pump even  
more money into federal campaigns, foster corruption and increase 
the influence of wealthy contributors. 
</P>
<P>
	McConnell, however, blamed the 1974 limits for creating the  
``money chase,'' in which candidates spend large amounts of time on 
the fund-raising circuit. Higher limits would help them raise money 
from fewer sources, he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
