<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Julie Andrews Sings at Tony Awards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Julie Andrews, appearing with Carol Burnett as a  
Tony Award presenter, proved true her prediction of last December 
that she would sing again. 
</P>
<P>
	She and Burnett traded phrases of several songs, and kidded  
around a bit Sunday. Burnett said, ``Don't you like these keys?'', 
since they weren't always singing in the same key. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrews remarked that Burnett was singing a song she'd done in  
``Putting It Together,'' a review of Stephen Sondheim songs she'd 
appeared in off-Broadway. ``I'm taking it to Broadway,'' Burnett 
replied, ``but not until November.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before it began to look like a TV special by the two women, they  
said, they would introduce the ``Sing, Sing, Sing'' number from 
``Fosse,'' a show nominated as best musical. It won. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrews, who had throat surgery two years ago to remove nodules,  
had been reported to be despondent because her singing career was 
over. She denied the reports and told the Mail in London in 
December, ``I will sing again.'' She said she'd been making ``a 
slow vocal recovery.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Andrews was last on Broadway in ``Victor/Victoria,'' which  
opened in October 1995 and earned her a Tony nomination. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
