<HEADLINE> Brit Accused of Attacking Attendants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BANGOR, Maine (AP) -- A trans-Atlantic flight was diverted when a  
British passenger who was refused drinks tried to get into the 
cockpit and assaulted two flight attendants, airport officials said 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Delta jet was flying from Atlanta to Manchester, England,  
when Christopher Bayes, 41, became belligerent in first class, 
demanding another drink, said Jeff Russell, marketing director at 
the Bangor International Airport. 
</P>
<P>
	Bayes, from Manchester, England, tried to get into the cockpit  
to press his demand. The cockpit door was locked and two flight 
attendants and some passengers battled to subdue him. 
</P>
<P>
	They tied Bayes up until Flight 064 landed in Bangor late  
Saturday, Russell said. 
</P>
<P>
	Two flight attendants were treated at a hospital for minor  
injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	Bayes was charged Monday in federal court with assault,  
interference with a flight crew and causing an aircraft to divert. 
He was being held at the county jail. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was blotto,'' said Paul Palumbo, an agent with the Federal  
Bureau of Investigation, said Monday. ``But I saw him today and 
he's a very nice guy.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
