<HEADLINE> Canadian Paper Gets New Publisher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- The Globe and Mail, one of Canada's two  
nationally circulated newspapers, today named Phillip Crawley as 
its publisher and chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
	Crawley, who serves as the Globe's chief operating officer and  
president, will succeed Roger Parkinson, currently chairman, 
publisher and chief executive, the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Parkinson, who joined the Toronto-based newspaper in 1994, will  
stay on as chairman and will focus on long-term strategy, along 
with customer and industry relations. the paper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Crawley, 55, joined the newspaper in 1998 from the New Zealand  
Herald where he was managing director. He also spent five years as 
editor-in-chief of the South China Morning Post in Hong Kong. 
</P>
<P>
	The Globe and Mail is the flagship publication of the newspaper  
division of Thomson Corp., the Toronto-based publishing and 
information company. While Thomson has sold most of its Canadian 
newspapers, it still owns about 50 dailies in the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
