<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Candidate Kasich Takes Risks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- John Kasich is opposed to ethanol subsidies  
and corporate tax loopholes. He would cut some Social Security 
benefits, and he thinks abortion is overestimated as a voter 
concern. ``God is not a wedge issue,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	These are tough stands for a Republican presidential candidate  
to take, but Kasich said during a recent campaign stop, ``I'm not 
going to change for anything. Not even to be president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His advisers are not so fatalistic; they say the Ohio  
congressman's against-the-grain style should distinguish him from a 
crowded field and breathe new life into his long-shot campaign. 
It's a gamble several other presidential hopefuls are willing to 
take. 
</P>
<P>
	Calculated risks are an early rite of the 2000 campaign.  
</P>
<P>
	Elizabeth Dole, former president of the American Red Cross,  
called for gun control before the Colorado school shootings. Party 
activists are generally staunch Second Amendment proponents. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Sen. Bill Bradley, a Democratic candidate, is considering  
a proposed ban on hand gun sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., urged President Clinton to win the  
conflict in Yugoslavia at all costs -- even if that meant the 
deployment of ground troops. Polls show little support for a 
full-fledged war. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole, McCain and Kasich are establishment Republicans  
overshadowed by the fledging candidacy of Texas Gov. George W. 
Bush, who has a wide lead in polls and the endorsement of scores of 
GOP leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	And Bradley trails far behind the Democratic front-runner, Vice  
President Al Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	While Bush and Gore play it safe, their rivals are taking  
chances. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kasich is doing it because Mrs. Dole did it and McCain did it,  
and they had some success getting attention,'' said GOP strategist 
Eddie Mahe. ``If I were the rest of them, I would be figuring out 
some position I can take that conflicts with the party's base, 
because if it doesn't conflict it wouldn't be a story.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the attention could come at a cost if primary voters reject  
the risky stands. In Iowa, site of the nation's first presidential 
caucuses, ethanol subsidies are considered untouchable. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the fine line Kasich and them are walking,'' Mahe said.  
``They get the attention, but the attention could kill them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Henry Graff, a presidential historian at Columbia University,  
said the strategy is part of a broader trend in presidential 
politics to avoid big issues. 
</P>
<P>
	``Each of these candidates is trying to distinguish himself and  
herself from the pack,'' he said. ``It's understood that no one 
needs to have a vision anymore, just an issue that gives them some 
attention.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1992, then-Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton criticized a black rap  
singer in a calculated effort to portray himself as a centrist 
Democrat with a streak of independence. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich says he is speaking from his heart, not from polls.  
</P>
<P>
	Shouting into a mobile phone from a noisy airport tarmac in  
California, Kasich says, ``I have to stay true to the things I 
believe. Period.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He believes police should not detain people simply because of  
their race, making him the first GOP candidate to speak out against 
so-called racial profiling. 
</P>
<P>
	He believes abortion is wrong, but is too often used by fellow  
Republicans as a divisive issue. ``God is not a wedge issue,'' he 
says. ``We should not use values to divide the country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He believes Social Security cannot be overhauled without baby  
boomers sacrificing some benefits in exchange for a system that 
gives them more freedom to invest in their own retirements. 
</P>
<P>
	He believes assault-style weapons should be banned, and voted  
against the GOP majority for such a bill in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	He believes corporate loopholes -- what he calls ``corporate  
welfare'' -- should be eliminated, even if that means killing the 
ethanol subsidy beloved by Iowa Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	``They tell me that's going to kill me in Iowa, but I'm not  
going to change my position to get votes,'' Kasich told Iowans in 
April. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope you'll forgive me,'' he said, ``and be for me anyway.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
