<HEADLINE> GOP Hopeful Alexander Cuts Staff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif., (AP) -- Republican presidential hopeful Lamar  
Alexander has cut still more staff from his campaign, telling 
workers the layoffs were necessary to save money. 
</P>
<P>
	On the eve of Alexander's three-day California swing, deputy  
press secretary Valerie Walston was laid off Monday morning, said a 
campaign source, speaking on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign also told press aide John Tolsma not to report to  
work as planned June 16, the source said. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday's cuts appeared to be part of an earlier round last week  
in which Alexander laid off his communications director, legal 
counsel and several support staff. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander, who lags in presidential preference polls, is  
shifting all of his efforts to Iowa, the source said. The former 
Tennessee governor and U.S. education secretary is aiming to finish 
strong in an August straw vote in Ames, Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	Campaign representatives did not immediately respond to messages  
left Monday evening at Alexander's campaign offices in Washington, 
D.C., and Nashville, Tenn., seeking comment. 
</P>
<P>
	When the cuts were disclosed last week, Alexander adviser Tom  
Rath said Alexander was trying to survive ``Bush mania,'' hoping 
the GOP front-runner, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, would stumble. 
</P>
<P>
	In that scenario, Alexander would siphon support from Bush, his  
fellow GOP moderate, and make a comeback. 
</P>
<P>
	The Alexander campaign is leaving its fund-raising operation  
intact, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander plans stops in San Francisco, Orange County, Los  
Angeles and Sacramento during his California visit Tuesday through 
Thursday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
