<DOCNO> APW19990607.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 14:35:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sen. Opposes Campaign Finance Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A leading opponent of proposed campaign  
finance revisions asked the Supreme Court on Monday to declare 
unconstitutional the 25-year-old $1,000 limit on contributions to 
federal campaigns by individuals. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., argued in a friend-of-court brief  
that contribution limits, adopted by Congress after Watergate, have 
a ``severe adverse effect'' on the ability of candidates to raise 
the increasing amounts of cash needed to finance a run for federal 
office. 
</P>
<P>
	In today's economy, the $1,000 is worth $302, according to the  
brief, filed as part of a Missouri campaign-finance dispute the 
high court will resolve next term. 
</P>
<P>
	Adjusted for inflation, the individual limit should be $3,306,  
the filing said. It would be $4,600 if adjusted both for inflation 
and increases in voting-age population. 
</P>
<P>
	McConnell, chairman of the National Republican Senatorial  
Committee, which raises money and recruits Republican Senate 
candidates, said ``broad agreement'' for higher contribution limits 
exists, including among many of those who want to change the 
system, such as President Clinton and Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a 
2000 presidential hopeful. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone knows that purchasing power has been eroded,''  
McConnell said at a news conference on the Supreme Court steps, 
across from the Capitol. ``Clearly this is a problem that everyone 
can agree needs to be addressed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Supreme Court upheld campaign contribution limits in 1976,  
two years after they were adopted by Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics contend that higher contribution limits would pump even  
more money into federal campaigns, foster corruption and increase 
the influence of wealthy contributors. 
</P>
<P>
	McConnell, however, blamed the 1974 limits for creating the  
``money chase,'' in which candidates spend large amounts of time on 
the fund-raising circuit. Higher limits would help them raise money 
from fewer sources, he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 15:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gates Tape Played for Bristol Jurors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- Microsoft chairman Bill Gates denied in  
a deposition played for jurors today that his company had tried to 
freeze out a tiny Danbury software company after initially giving 
it access to Windows programming code. 
</P>
<P>
	But lawyers for Bristol Technology Inc. grilled Gates about an  
e-mail message in which he wrote that Microsoft was choosing 
Bristol's main competitor, Mainsoft Inc., as its partner, and 
``revving up their activities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The videotaped deposition was played Monday in U.S. District  
Court, where Bristol has filed an antitrust lawsuit against 
Microsoft. 
</P>
<P>
	Gates, who appeared combative and forgetful during a lengthy  
deposition last year for the larger antitrust case being heard in 
Washington, D.C., was generally congenial and relaxed during the 
deposition for the Bristol case. 
</P>
<P>
	During his deposition for the Justice Department case, Gates  
appeared so evasive in interviews with government lawyers that the 
judge laughed and shook his head while watching the testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	Bristol makes a product called Wind/U, which allows programs  
that were written for Windows to run on computers with different 
operating systems, such as Unix. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, Microsoft signed a three-year contract with Bristol  
giving the company access to programming code -- the software 
blueprints -- for Windows NT 3.0, a version of its operating system 
designed to work with powerful corporate computers. 
</P>
<P>
	When the contract expired in 1997, the two companies could not  
come to an agreement. Bristol claims Microsoft promised to make the 
code available into the future. Microsoft says Bristol is trying to 
get more favorable licensing terms for a new contract. 
</P>
<P>
	In the deposition, Bristol's lawyers questioned Gates about a  
September 1997 e-mail he sent to several Microsoft employees. In 
it, Gates lists eight actions Microsoft was taking, including 
choosing Mainsoft as a partner in its cross-platform program, 
called the Windows Interface Source Environment, or WISE. 
</P>
<P>
	Bristol had also been a WISE partner with Microsoft.  
</P>
<P>
	``Now what did you mean -- if you didn't mean to exclude Bristol  
from the WISE program -- then what did you mean by picking Mainsoft 
as your partner?'' Bristol attorney Patrick Lynch asked Gates. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't mean anything about whether it was Mainsoft or  
Bristol, I'm just talking about the things we're doing, so for 
total completeness, maybe I should have listed Bristol,'' Gates 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``OK, and you didn't mean to tell your people that for some  
reason you had decided to freeze Bristol out of the WISE program?'' 
Lynch asked. 
</P>
<P>
	``No,'' Gates replied.  
</P>
<P>
	The jury appeared alternately amused and bored by Gates'  
testimony. At one point, several jurors chuckled when Gates became 
animated about the competitive threat posed by Netscape -- an issue 
in the case brought by the Justice Department case and 19 states. 
</P>
<P>
	In that case, the government contends that Microsoft illegally  
wielded monopoly power from its dominant Windows product to expand 
into new markets, such as Internet software, and thus crush 
competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	``Netscape stated very clearly that their goal was to put  
Windows out of business, to make it obsolete and useless, and that 
Microsoft would go bankrupt based on their activities,'' Gates 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``And that caused you to believe that it was a serious  
competitive threat?'' asked Lynch. 
</P>
<P>
	``Generally, when people say those things, it gets my  
attention,'' Gates said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 14:50:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NiSource Wants Columbia Energy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- NiSource Inc. launched a hostile bid for  
Virginia-based Columbia Energy Group Monday, a $5.7 billion deal 
that if successful would make NiSource into one of the nation's 
biggest natural gas companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The unsolicited bid came after a formal offer to Columbia's  
board of directors was rejected and Columbia's executives refused 
to discuss merging with NiSource. 
</P>
<P>
	``A merger of our two companies has substantial benefits to our  
respective shareholders, customers, and employees,'' NiSource 
chairman and chief executive Gary L. Neale wrote in a letter to 
Oliver Richard III, Columbia Energy's chairman and CEO. 
``Unfortunately, your refusal to discuss these benefits leaves us 
no alternative but to go public with our proposal. ... We are 
confident that your shareholders will enthusiastically support our 
proposal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a response letter sent later Monday, Richard grudgingly  
conceded that NiSource's move will force Columbia to consider the 
offer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Columbia Energy Group is not for sale and is not interested in  
any merger transaction in which another company acquires control of 
Columbia,'' he wrote. ``Nevertheless, in light of the formal nature 
of the offer set forth in your letter, your offer will be 
considered by our board of directors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NiSource hopes its public announcement will force the Columbia  
board to not only consider the offer but also open talks, Neale 
said in a telephone interview. 
</P>
<P>
	He said a majority of Columbia stock is institutionally held.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to at least take our proposal to those  
shareholders,'' he said. ``Hopefully if they like the deal they'll 
put pressure on the board to sit down with us. ... We'd like to 
turn this into a friendly merger.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NiSource is offering to buy Columbia Energy for $5.7 billion in  
cash, or $68 per share. 
</P>
<P>
	The price represents a 30.7 percent premium over the average  
closing share price for Columbia common stock for the 20 trading 
days ended Friday, NiSource said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, shares of Columbia Energy closed up $7.43 3/4 to $63.18 3/4  
on the New York Stock Exchange. Shares of NiSource were down 62 1/2 
cents, to $27.56 1/4, also on the Big Board. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal would double the size of NiSource, making it one of the  
largest natural gas companies in the country with pipelines 
connecting the Texas coast of the Gulf of Mexico to the Atlantic 
Ocean. 
</P>
<P>
	In his letter to Richard, Neale said NiSource first made an  
offer for Columbia Energy on April 1. Columbia Energy canceled 
meetings to discuss that offer, and then launched an unsuccessful 
bid of its own to acquire CNG, a natural gas supplier and pipeline 
owner with holdings from Ohio to Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, CNG spurned Columbia Energy's offer and accepted a  
takeover bid from Dominion Resources Inc. After that, NiSource 
tried to reopen talks with Columbia Energy, but Columbia Energy 
refused, Neale said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Columbia Energy proposal is the latest in what has been a  
busy year for NiSource. In February, the company completed the 
acquisition of Massachusetts-based Bay State Gas Co., which 
provides natural gas service to more than 300,000 customers in 
Massachusetts, New Hampshire and Maine. In April, company 
shareholders voted to rename the corporation from Nipsco Industries 
Inc. to NiSource. 
</P>
<P>
	NiSource, based in Merrillville, Ind., is a holding company with  
a market capitalization of approximately $3.6 billion whose primary 
business is the distribution of electricity, natural gas and water 
in the Midwest and northeast. The company also markets utility 
services along a corridor stretching from Texas to Maine. 
</P>
<P>
	Herndon, Va.-based Columbia Energy is a major energy services  
company with roles in natural gas exploration and production, 
transmission, distribution and storage. Its 1998 revenues were 
nearly $6.6 billion. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
