<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 13:50:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NYC Ballet Gets Two New Jazz Ballets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- New York City Ballet dancers came out swinging --  
as though they'd been born to jitterbug instead of pirouette. 
</P>
<P>
	It was jazz night, one of four the company is dancing with the  
Lincoln Center Jazz Orchestra playing. The most fun came at the end 
of the evening Saturday. ``Duke!'' presented three choreographers' 
takes on music composed by Duke Ellington. 
</P>
<P>
	Broadway choreographer Susan Stroman got the big finish with a  
funny conceit danced to ``It Don't Mean a Thing if it Ain't Got 
That Swing.'' Maria Kowroski in blue tutu sits on a bench with six 
young women in slinky red dresses. The women in red dance, jivey 
and jazzy, with men wearing suits, red shirts and ties. Kowroski 
scoots up close, pats her foot, tries to figure out the steps. 
She's none too gently pushed aside. 
</P>
<P>
	Then she encounters a member of the on-stage band who plays the  
triangle. He turns out to be Robert La Fosse, in reality a company 
dancer. She whips off the tutu, revealing a red dress, and the two 
of them, as their grandparents might have said, really cut a rug. 
</P>
<P>
	La Fosse choreographed the first part of ``Duke!'' --''Rockin' in  
Rhythm'' -- letting the men pretend to be casual as they move to the 
rhythm and worship dancer Helene Alexopoulos. 
</P>
<P>
	Garth Fagan choreographed the second part to a section of  
Ellington's ``Far East Suite.'' His movements were limited in 
number and didn't really flow. 
</P>
<P>
	``Duke!'' was the last of three ballets the dancers performed.  
</P>
<P>
	The second, ``Them Twos,'' also was new. The music was composed  
by Wynton Marsalis, his first for orchestra. Peter Martins 
choreographed. Janie Taylor and Sebastien Marcovici danced the 
``First Love'' section, a light-hearted idyll in which she is 
frisky and coy and he shows off. 
</P>
<P>
	In ``Almost,'' dancer Nilas Martins' job was to be an attentive  
partner to Miranda Weese. When he jumped, it was around her and 
toward her. She finally slipped away from him. In ``Horror,'' Maria 
Kowroski was dramatic, and frightening, as a fatal attraction for 
Charles Askegard. And in a section titled ``Sex,'' Yvonne Borree 
and Nikolaj Hubbe, dressed for a harem scene, did much back-to-back 
arm twining and back bending. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last section, ``Loss,'' Jock Soto was sad and solitary,  
even when Darci Kistler, almost floating to indicate she's a 
memory, was at his side. 
</P>
<P>
	The evening at the New York State Theater began with the joyful,  
jumping ``Jazz,'' for which Marsalis wrote the music and Martins 
choreographed in 1993. The Lincoln Center Jazz Orchestra played 
from the pit. Jock Soto, in particular, seemed to be having the 
time of his dancing life. 
</P>
<P>
	Guest conductors were Robert Sadin and David Berger.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
