<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Big Names Supporting Shoeless Joe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DYERSVILLE, Iowa (AP) -- Some big hitters will take to the Field  
of Dreams in a call for Shoeless Joe Jackson's reinstatement to 
baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall of Famers Ted Williams, Bob Feller and Yogi Berra, along  
with former Los Angeles Dodgers manager Tommy Lasorda, will 
participate in a July tournament at the Field of Dreams in 
northeast Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	It was 80 years ago this October that Jackson and seven of his  
Chicago White Sox teammates were accused of conspiring to throw the 
1919 World Series to the Cincinnati Reds. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson was banned from baseball in 1920, but he was acquitted  
of criminal charges. He died in 1951. 
</P>
<P>
	He still has the third-highest career batting average -- .356 in  
13 seasons -- but is ineligible for the Hall of Fame as long as he 
is banned. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams plans on meeting Friday with commissioner Bud Selig to  
discuss Jackson. He will then join Iowa native Feller, Berra and 
Lasorda at the Shoeless Joe Jackson National Baseball Tournament to 
rally for Jackson's reinstatement. 
</P>
<P>
	The tournament begins July 1 at the Field of Dreams.  
</P>
<P>
	The field is the site of the 1989 movie of the same name in  
which Kevin Costner's character turns his cornfield into a baseball 
field and meets Jackson's ghost, played by Ray Liotta. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 16:10:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former NBA Player Admits Assault </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Former NBA player Dontonio Wingfield pleaded  
guilty today to assaulting two suburban Cincinnati police officers. 
</P>
<P>
	Wingfield, the former University of Cincinnati forward who went  
on to play for the Seattle SuperSonics and Portland Trail Blazers, 
could be sentenced to as many as 18 months behind bars and fined 
$5,000. 
</P>
<P>
	He will be sentenced Sept. 2 in Hamilton County Common Pleas  
Court. 
</P>
<P>
	Wingfield, 24, pleaded guilty to aggravated assault and assault  
on two officers. He was originally charged with felonious assault 
on a police officer -- with a possible punishment of up to 10 years 
and a $20,000 fine -- but reached the plea agreement with 
prosecutors to the lesser offense. 
</P>
<P>
	In August 1998, the 6-foot-8 Wingfield was visiting the  
apartment of girlfriend Christina Cornett and they became involved 
in a dispute. Police said Wingfield was verbally abusive, resisted 
arrest, and broke a finger and tore tendons of one officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Wingfield, from Albany, Ga., played for the University of  
Cincinnati in the 1993-94 season and left after his freshman year 
for the NBA. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 16:51:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Undeterred Blazers Look To Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- The Portland Trail Blazers' grand  
experiment -- trying to win an NBA title without a consistent scorer 
or a proven leader -- was a surprising success for most of the 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, the San Antonio Spurs revealed the many shortcomings  
of the system, beating the Blazers seven out of eight times this 
season, including four straight in the Western Conference finals. 
Whenever the Spurs put together a run or hit a big shot late in the 
game, the Blazers didn't have anyone who craved the ball or the 
pressure of carrying the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Portland went 35-15 in the regular season, winning their  
first Pacific Division title since 1992. They also erased the 
stigma of losing six straight years in the first round of the 
playoffs by going deeper than almost anyone expected. 
</P>
<P>
	The way they ended the season didn't discourage the Blazers from  
predicting big things for 1999-2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``I liked the way we played this year,'' said forward Brian  
Grant, whose dreadlocked hair and rebounding fury came to symbolize 
the team's resurgence. ``I think we need to maybe get a couple guys 
more established as our scorers, but I kind of like the way we did 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll have a better feel for what it takes the next time  
around,'' Blazers coach Mike Dunleavy said. ``Very few teams ever 
get there without having to pay the price of a learning experience. 
This is a start for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether their 4-0 sweep to the Spurs, in which they  
averaged just 76 points a game, tarnished their accomplishments, 
guard Isaiah Rider snapped, ``No. We went to the third round and 
had a great season. We'll be back stronger next season. ``Nobody 
expected us to get above seventh place (in the West) this year. The 
joke is on you guys and the others that doubted us. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a good team the way it is -- we almost went to the  
(NBA) finals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not quite. Despite having so many offensive threats -- including  
Rider, Jim Jackson, Damon Stoudamire, Rasheed Wallace, Walt 
Williams and Arvydas Sabonis -- showed a painful inability to score 
at times. 
</P>
<P>
	Then there was Dunleavy's much-publicized methods for parceling  
out minutes. Jackson, a 25-point early in his career with Dallas, 
averaged just 8.4 points this season as Rider's backup. Wallace, 
one of the game's most exciting young players, shared playing time 
at small forward with Williams and Stacey Augmon. 
</P>
<P>
	Stoudamire had the most trouble adjusting to his new role. The  
more the Blazers won, the more Dunleavy relied on backup point 
guard Greg Anthony late in games. The veteran, who signed a 
two-year, $2.1 million contract as a free agent before the season, 
was simply a better defender, and Stoudamire, the hometown hero, 
stewed about it. 
</P>
<P>
	After he sat out the fourth quarter in a late-season loss at  
Utah, Stoudamire destroyed the Blazers' veneer of harmony by 
allowing his agent, Aaron Goodwin, to blast Dunleavy publicly. 
Then, after the Blazers got down 2-0 to the Spurs, Stoudamire 
picked the worst possible time to air his frustrations about not 
playing more. 
</P>
<P>
	``I regret it,'' said Stoudamire. ``Unfortunately, what I said  
took the focus away from the team and put it on me. It made me look 
selfish, and I am not. What I've learned is that sometimes you've 
got to bite the tongue. I could have waited and said it after the 
season was over. I've taken some hits from it, but I'm still 
standing. I learned from it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope I can win (the fans) back,'' added Stoudamire, who was  
booed by many at the Rose Garden crowd Sunday. ``I hope they can 
accept me for what I am. And that I am learning from my mistakes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While many fans still would like to see Stoudamire run out of  
town, a trade seems unlikely. But there could be other changes. 
Backup forward Jermaine O'Neal is the only free agent, but Rider 
has an opt-out clause in his contract. But president and general 
manager Bob Whitsitt said Monday he doesn't have any plans to 
shuffle the roster -- at least yet. 
</P>
<P>
	``Do we like our team? Absolutely,'' Whitsitt said, but later  
added: ``I'm not telling you what we'll do, because I don't know 
what we will do.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 16:51:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
