<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 10:36:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Discovery's Flight Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Space shuttle Discovery and its  
astronauts are back from the international space station after 
accomplishing everything they set out to do. 
</P>
<P>
	All the headaches are now back on Earth.  
</P>
<P>
	Hanging over the successful supply mission is uncertainty about  
both the status of the next shuttle flight and scheduled follow-up 
trips to the new space station. 
</P>
<P>
	Those fears were momentarily was set aside as Discovery emerged  
like a ghost ship from the predawn Sunday sky and touched down on 
Kennedy Space Center's floodlighted runway. 
</P>
<P>
	It was only the 11th time that a space shuttle landed in  
darkness. 
</P>
<P>
	``Welcome home, Discovery, from the first docking mission to the  
international space station,'' radioed Mission Control. 
</P>
<P>
	The seven astronauts skipped the traditional shuttle walkaround  
and picture taking, and instead asked to be driven straight to crew 
quarters. They left managers waiting on the landing strip, fueling 
speculation that one or more of the crew might be nauseated, as 
sometimes happens to returning astronauts. 
</P>
<P>
	This morning, commander Kent Rominger told reporters no one was  
sick, although it took ``a while to get our Earth legs back.'' 
Because everything seemed to take longer than usual at touchdown, 
and because he and his crewmates had plans for later in the day, 
they decided ``to head on back and get on with our day off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It is so nice at wheels stop for at least a day just to,  
ahhhhhh, relax and go see family and friends ... basically get away 
from it all for a day,'' Rominger said. 
</P>
<P>
	He added: ``We had a fantastic adventure.''  
</P>
<P>
	During their 10 days in orbit, the astronauts unloaded 2 tons of  
supplies at the space station for future inhabitants, replaced bad 
electronic boxes and installed mufflers over noisy fans. 
</P>
<P>
	On their way home, they dropped off a glittering, mirrored  
satellite called Starshine that schoolchildren will track until it 
falls from orbit at the beginning of next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Astronauts aren't due back at the space station until December,  
when they're supposed to haul up more supplies aboard Atlantis. But 
that mission cannot take place -- and neither can any other missions 
to the 6-month-old space station -- until the Russians launch a 
crucial service module that will double as crew quarters. 
</P>
<P>
	The component is scheduled to fly in November, 1 1/2 years behind  
schedule, provided all the testing between now and then goes well. 
The Russian Space Agency's money problems and delays have long 
bothered NASA. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always hope for the best, plan for the worst,'' NASA  
Administrator Daniel Goldin said following Discovery's return. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA's more immediate concern involves Columbia and the $1.5  
billion observatory Chandra, also running a year late because of a 
multitude of problems. 
</P>
<P>
	The upper-stage motor on Chandra is similar to one that  
malfunctioned aboard a military satellite in April, leaving the 
spacecraft in a uselessly low orbit. An Air Force investigation 
into the failure continues. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, NASA is proceeding toward a July 22 launch of Columbia,  
the only shuttle big enough to hold the 45-foot X-ray telescope. 
Technicians moved Columbia to the launch pad today. 
</P>
<P>
	Goldin stressed, however, that he won't give the final go-ahead  
until ``the NASA team walks into my office and says they understand 
exactly what went wrong, they understand how it was fixed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NASA has until mid-August to send Columbia on the  
telescope-delivery mission without impacting other missions, said 
shuttle program manager Ron Dittemore. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem is that NASA's oldest shuttle is due for its  
regularly scheduled tune-up and, unless it flies soon, it will have 
to undergo eight to nine months of maintenance before launching 
Chandra. That would bump the mission -- the first to be commanded by 
a woman -- into late 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it takes a year, it will take a year,'' Goldin said. ``Time  
is not an issue.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 07:27:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Stock Prices Advance / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks advanced moderately today as  
investors were encouraged by the strength on Wall Street last week, 
while the dollar sank against the yen on speculation about a 
rumored call for large-scale tax cuts in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 175.14  
points, or 1.07 percent, ending the afternoon session at 16,475.89. 
On Friday, the Nikkei closed up 73.25 points, or 0.45 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 120.84 yen late afternoon, down 0.78 yen from  
late Friday in Tokyo and below its New York level of 122.22 yen 
late Friday. The currency ranged from 120.55 yen to 122.45 yen 
today in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, share prices were buoyed initially by  
Friday's 136.15-point gain in the Dow Jones industrial average, 
which closed at 10,799.84. 
</P>
<P>
	``Investors were relieved by New York's rally,'' said Hidenori  
Karaki, a manager at Ryoko Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said the rise in Tokyo was mainly futures-led, although  
individual shares in the high-technology and pharmaceutical sectors 
also put on big gains mirroring the movement of their counterparts 
in New York Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues beat retreating issues 851 to 319, while 130  
issues were unchanged. Volume on the first section was estimated at 
379.03 million shares, up slightly from 369.03 million shares 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Also boosting the stock market was news that the government  
decided on Friday to close Toho Mutual Life Insurance Co., a 
troubled medium-sized Japanese insurance company. The company's 
liabilities were found to have exceeded its assets by $1.64 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei's finish, however, ended up well below its midday  
level of 16,576.51 points because of profit-taking in the 
afternoon, said Kazunori Jinnai, deputy general manager at Daiwa 
Securities SB Capital Markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section gained 12.12 points, or 0.92 percent, to 1,328.65. 
The TOPIX closed down 1.16 points, or 0.09 percent, on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar slipped against the yen on  
speculation that the head of Japan's Liberal Party, Ichiro Ozawa, 
called for large-scale, permanent tax cuts to stimulate the 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Dealers said the comments moved the markets even though Ozawa  
has repeatedly made similar remarks and the ruling Liberal 
Democratic Party has not heeded the proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was quoted at 124.47 yen, down  
from 125.29 late Friday in Tokyo, on news that negotiations between 
NATO and Yugoslavia had collapsed. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark No. 213 10-year Japanese government bond stood at  
1.640 percent late Tuesday, up from Friday's finish of 1.635 
percent, pushing down its price to 97.93 yen from 97.97 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
