<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jones Becomes Undisputed Champion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BILOXI, Miss. (AP) -- In boxing, there are more champions than  
there are titles. And that's why Roy Jones is so unique. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones pounded out a unanimous decision that left Reggie Johnson  
battered and bleeding and made Jones the first undisputed world's 
light heavyweight champion in 14 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love championship belts,'' Jones said after adding his third  
one. ``I think there should always be an undisputed champion. That 
is something prestigious and made this fight interesting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones becomes only the third undisputed light heavyweight  
champion, joining Bob Foster and Michael Spinks. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones' speed and quickness gave him a huge edge and an easy  
victory Saturday night. He won every round and every judge scored 
it 120-106 in favor of Jones, who added Johnson's IBF title to the 
WBA and WBC crowns he already had. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've proven everything I had to prove,'' Jones said. ``After  
awhile, I was just having fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, who weighed 174 pounds, used a straight right 1:58 into  
the first round to knock down Johnson. The Houston fighter got up 
quickly, but was bleeding from his right eye. 
</P>
<P>
	In the third round, Jones countered a right from Johnson with a  
left-right combination that sent him to the canvas. Again Johnson 
got up quickly and the bell ended the round. By that time, blood 
was streaming from Johnson's eye. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson was only able to fight back in spurts by the fourth  
round. The rest of the time he was backing away or covering up. 
When he managed to get inside, Jones punished him with jabs and 
uppercuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Halfway through the 12-round fight Johnson's face was swollen,  
his white trunks streaked with blood. But Johnson (39-6-1) kept 
answering the bell. 
</P>
<P>
	``Roy was real quick,'' Johnson said. ``I didn't have time to  
counter his punches. Coming into the fight, I knew I had to give a 
lot and take a lot of punches.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones landed 273 punches to just 49 for Johnson.  
</P>
<P>
	The crowd, which included a big contingent from Jones' hometown  
of Pensacola, Fla., called for a knockout. There were some boos 
late in the fight when Jones didn't press his attack. Johnson did 
go down in the 12th after a solid right from Jones, but it was 
ruled a slip. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could have pressured him and knocked him out, but why would  
I take a chance on him getting a lucky punch and knocking me out?'' 
Jones said. ``That's not very businesslike.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Jones was not completely businesslike.  
</P>
<P>
	He couldn't resist showboating when it became apparent how  
completely he was dominating the fight. At one point, he backed 
Johnson to the ropes, looked at Michael Jordan, who was seated 
ringside, and shouted, ``Watch this!'' before throwing a flurry of 
jabs. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had the best player ever in the building and, at the same  
time, we had the best boxer in the building,'' Jones said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
