<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IBM-Microsoft Face Court Scrutiny </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The troubled on-again, off-again marriage of  
Microsoft and the IBM Corp., two of the largest companies in the 
computer industry, was laid bare in a courtroom today as a 
government witness testified against Microsoft at its antitrust 
trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Garry Norris, an IBM manager who negotiated key agreements  
between the companies in 1995 and 1996, described Microsoft's 
alleged efforts to persuade IBM to sacrifice its rival OS/2 
operating system software to favor Windows. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson appeared to be  
following Norris' testimony closely, frequently taking notes, 
asking minor questions for clarification and reading e-mails and 
other evidence on a projection screen. 
</P>
<P>
	Norris contends that after IBM rejected Microsoft's alleged  
overtures to kill OS/2, Microsoft took an unusually tough stance 
negotiating the wholesale price that IBM paid to put Windows 95 on 
the computers it sold to consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	Norris said Microsoft demanded that IBM ``make Windows 95 the  
standard operating system of your company'' and to identify Windows 
as the only operating system in IBM advertisements. 
</P>
<P>
	As incentive, Microsoft offered to reduce the price IBM would  
pay for Windows, discounts worth $40 million to $48 million 
annually. 
</P>
<P>
	``We could not agree to those provisions,'' Norris said.  
</P>
<P>
	Norris said Microsoft executives told him ``on several  
occasions'' that: ``IBM can have Compaq's (Compaq Computer Corp.) 
deal when you stop competing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Norris, who kept a journal of his communications with Microsoft,  
is expected to testify this week that Microsoft pressured IBM not 
to include ``objectionable software'' from competitors, such as 
Netscape Communications Corp. or Lotus Development Corp., on its 
line of computers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I prepared handwritten notes as well as computer notes,''  
Norris told Justice Department lawyer Phil Malone, who took over 
questioning for his colleague, David Boies. Malone, from the 
department's San Francisco office, has worked behind the scenes for 
more than a year helping build evidence against Microsoft. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM bought Lotus in the summer of 1995, as IBM was negotiating  
its price for Windows. Lotus' popular SmartSuite package of 
business software applications competes directly with Microsoft's 
lucrative Office bundle. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft was expected to rebut claims from Norris by showing  
the judge the final 1994 proposal for its alliance with IBM, which 
doesn't include encouragement for IBM to reduce or stop sales of 
its OS/2 software. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM rejected the offer during a private meeting at a trade show  
in Las Vegas in November 1994 with top Microsoft executives, 
including Bill Gates. Instead, IBM told Microsoft it planned to 
sell computers with both Windows and OS/2, which ultimately proved 
a commercial failure. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's ridiculous,'' said Mark Baber, the former Microsoft  
executive who negotiated with IBM during the period. ``In no way, 
shape or form did Microsoft -- with IBM or any other (computer 
maker) I was working with -- talk about exclusivity or the 
elimination of competitive products.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Baber acknowledged that an earlier draft of the proposal  
required IBM to promote Microsoft's products primarily on its 
computers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe the terminology was `predominantly promote Microsoft  
products.' It wasn't specific to Windows 95,'' Baber said. ``It was 
dropped because IBM said they had chosen a different strategy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Norris also told government lawyers that Microsoft pressured IBM  
during 1996 and 1997 not to include rivals' software on its 
computers, and discussed whether it was appropriate for IBM to 
participate in the debut of the latest version of Microsoft's 
Internet software in September 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's just absolutely false,'' Baber said. ``We had excellent  
relationships with other computer makers that offered competitive 
products,'' Baber said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
