<DOCNO> APW19990607.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 12:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IBM-Microsoft Relations Outlined </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An IBM Corp. manager accused Microsoft on  
Monday of offering discounts worth tens of millions of dollars to 
IBM to sacrifice its rival computer operating system and to stop 
distributing software from key competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	Garry Norris, a mid-level IBM executive, said Microsoft Corp.  
Chairman Bill Gates was so angry about IBM's defiance that he 
overheard the billionaire screaming during a private phone call in 
July 1995 to another IBM executive in the room. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was pretty loud,'' Norris said, eliciting laughter from a  
crowded courtroom. 
</P>
<P>
	Norris, who negotiated key agreements in 1995 and 1996,  
testified that IBM saw the total fees it pays to Microsoft rise 
from $40 million in 1996 to $440 million last year because it 
rejected Microsoft's alleged overtures not to compete. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who will decide the  
verdict in the antitrust trial later this year, frequently took 
notes, asked questions for clarification and studied e-mails and 
other documents on a large projection screen in court. 
</P>
<P>
	Norris is a crucial witness because none of the nation's major  
computer makers had previously been willing to testify in court in 
support of government allegations that Microsoft uses the prices 
for its dominant Windows operating system to punish enemies and 
reward allies. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was crystal clear there was no viable commercial  
alternative,'' said Norris, who kept a journal of his 
communications with Microsoft executives. ``We needed a 
relationship with Microsoft.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Norris said Microsoft proposed an alliance with IBM in 1994,  
years after a bitter feud had ended the companies' 1980s 
partnership in which they worked together on programming languages 
and helped develop the earliest versions of each other's operating 
systems. 
</P>
<P>
	But Norris accused Microsoft of setting as a condition for the  
1994 alliance the sacrifice of IBM's OS/2 operating system, which 
competed with Windows until the popularity of OS/2 waned later in 
1995. 
</P>
<P>
	He said that after IBM rejected the proposal for an alliance in  
November 1994, Microsoft took an unusually tough stance negotiating 
the wholesale price that IBM paid the following summer to put 
Windows 95 on computers it sold to consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM believed some of its competitors, such as Compaq Computer  
Corp., had negotiated lower prices. Norris said that Microsoft 
executive Mark Baber told him on several occasions: ``IBM can have 
Compaq's deal when you stop competing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baber, in a telephone interview, called Norris' claims  
``ridiculous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``In no way, shape or form did Microsoft -- with IBM or any other  
(computer maker) I was working with -- talk about exclusivity or the 
elimination of competitive products,'' Baber said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Norris produced Microsoft's 1995 contract offering discounts  
of $1 to $3 per copy of Windows, for example, if IBM were willing 
to ``adopt Windows 95 as the standard operating system for IBM'' 
and to mention Windows as the only operating system in IBM 
advertisements. 
</P>
<P>
	``We could not agree to those provisions,'' Norris said, adding  
that those inducements were worth $40 million to $48 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Norris said Microsoft also was angry about its 1995 purchase of  
Lotus Development Corp., whose popular SmartSuite business software 
competes directly with the lucrative Microsoft Office applications. 
</P>
<P>
	The government showed a memorandum from IBM's Richard Thoman  
after an August 1995 meeting with Microsoft's Joachim Kempin, who 
urged IBM not to distribute the Lotus programs on its computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Thoman wrote that Kempin suggested IBM ``not bundle Lotus  
SmartSuite on our systems for a minimum of six months to one 
year.'' Another IBM internal e-mail said Kempin was ``definitely 
worried about SmartSuite being given away and eating into their 
'Office heartland.''' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
