<DOCNO> APW19990607.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 17:50:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmaker Would Scrap GOP Primary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- A Republican lawmaker wants to replace  
California's winner-take-all GOP presidential primary with a system 
that could cause problems for the front-runner, Texas Gov. George 
W. Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	State Sen. Ray Haynes' plan would discontinue the practice of  
giving the winner of the GOP primary all of the nation's biggest 
bloc of Republican National Convention delegates. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, candidates would fight for 156 of California's  
delegates by congressional district. A victory in one district in 
the March 7 primary would be worth three delegates. 
</P>
<P>
	Another dozen to two dozen at-large delegates would go to  
candidates based on their proportion of the statewide vote, 
although Haynes said he is willing to give all those delegates to 
the overall winner. 
</P>
<P>
	Haynes, one of the Legislature's most conservative members, said  
his proposal isn't designed to derail the more moderate Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	Haynes, of Temecula, said Monday that he supports Bush and  
believes his plan would help him in the long run by forcing him to 
organize in California earlier and more extensively than he would 
with a winner-take-all primary. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you are forced to do the work for the primary you don't  
have to work as hard the September before the general election,'' 
Haynes said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some past GOP candidates have tried to set up a California  
organization after getting the presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	``It does not work,'' Haynes said.  
</P>
<P>
	Gerald Parsky, Bush's California chairman, said the Texas  
governor's campaign is willing to ``play by whatever rules are 
established by the California party.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But, he added: ``It would certainly be better to give people  
advance warning about what the rules are going to be rather than 
change them after a number of candidates have announced.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The plan would give candidates with limited budgets a chance to  
pick up California delegates by focusing on one or two areas, said 
Brian Kennedy, national political director for GOP candidate Lamar 
Alexander, a former Tennessee governor who lags in presidential 
preference polls. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal comes as California anticipates playing a bigger  
role in presidential nominations after moving its primary from June 
to March. 
</P>
<P>
	Haynes' proposal gets its first test Wednesday when the state  
party's rules committee meets in Burbank. If approved, it will be 
considered June 19 by the 100-member executive committee in 
Ontario. 
</P>
<P>
	Haynes predicts he has enough votes in the 11-member rules  
committee and is close to having enough to win executive committee 
backing. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 00:10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dallas' Cup Winners Seek 2nd Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- The Dallas Stars can be divided into two groups:  
those who've won the Stanley Cup and those who haven't. It's hard 
to tell which is more excited about being in the finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Considering that an NHL championship is about the only accolade  
missing from the career resumes of Mike Modano, Brett Hull and Ed 
Belfour, it is tempting to say the have-nots are the most 
motivated. 
</P>
<P>
	Then listen to Craig Ludwig, a 38-year-old defenseman who is one  
of eight Cup winners who will be seeking another championship 
beginning Tuesday night against the Buffalo Sabres. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot of us who know what it's like at the end of the  
rainbow,'' said Ludwig, who won with Montreal in 1986. ``We want 
that back. 
</P>
<P>
	``For a few of us, we know we don't have many kicks of the can  
left. To us, this is very important.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Guy Carbonneau falls into that group. A two-time Cup winner in  
Montreal, the 39-year-old forward can't help but smile as he 
recalls the thrill of receiving hockey's holy grail. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the ultimate, the best feeling in the world,'' Carbonneau  
said. ``It's also the hardest feeling to achieve. 
</P>
<P>
	``But once you're there, there are no other places you'd rather  
be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres are driven by the same goal, but the stories shared  
in their locker room are secondhand. Only six Buffalo players have 
been to the finals, and between them they've won a total of one 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a child I didn't even know what a Stanley Cup was, but it  
is my focus right now,'' said goaltender Dominik Hasek, who led the 
Czech Republic to the 1996 Olympic gold medal. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dallas and Buffalo franchises are 0-3 in finals. The Sabres  
lost in 1975, while the Minnesota North Stars fell in 1991 and 
1981. This is the Stars' sixth season in Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Buffalo general manager Darcy Regier equates Dallas' experience  
with age. 
</P>
<P>
	``They feel for them that the time is now,'' Regier said. ``They  
have some older players that don't have a lot of years left, and 
they have to seize the opportunity. But our players feel the same 
way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars, the top-seeded team in the West, come into the finals  
on a roll, having beaten second-seeded Colorado twice while facing 
elimination. Some viewed that series as the true finals, noting the 
Western Conference champion has won the last three Cups, each with 
sweeps. 
</P>
<P>
	Modano upset several Buffalo players by saying Dallas ``is  
anticipating a bit of a letdown in the finals'' because the Sabres 
are the East's seventh-seeded team. He clarified his stance Sunday 
and praised Buffalo for ``deserving to be there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I think everybody else was saying that there was going to be a  
letdown; I didn't think there would be,'' he said. ``I think that's 
a lot of the hockey geniuses around the NHL predicting that, 
considering Colorado and our series was a pretty good series.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres, however, are still treating Modano's initial  
comments as bulletin-board material. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think a team that's really on a mission is going to  
have one of their leaders saying that the team's going to have a 
letdown after the conference final,'' Buffalo center Michael Peca 
said. ``If a team's on a mission, those kind of statements aren't 
made. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're already setting up excuses, saying that the Western  
Conference was their Stanley Cup. But he may say things that he 
doesn't realize he's saying.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres were underdogs against Ottawa, Boston and Toronto,  
and won each series, so they don't mind the same label despite a 
playoffs-best 12-3 record. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone's saying that they're going to run away with it.  
We're fine with that,'' Buffalo defenseman Jason Woolley said. 
``We're used to that. Nobody expected us to get this far, that's 
for sure.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
