<DOCNO> APW19990607.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 23:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Miller Didn't Need Ball at the End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Reggie Miller didn't get his 25 shots. A nice  
running jumper and a fist pump were the extent of his highlights. 
</P>
<P>
	That may be the scariest thing that emerged from the Indiana  
Pacers' 90-78 victory over the New York Knicks in Game 4 of the 
Eastern Conference finals. The Pacers might not need Miller to 
carry them, after all. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm telling you, I'm starting to feel better the longer this  
series goes,'' said Miller, who followed his scoreless fourth 
quarter in Game 3 with a mere 12 points and 3-for-10 shooting 
Monday night as Indiana tied the series 2-2. ``I keep telling the 
guys, it's almost like an overflowing dam. It's getting to the top 
and it's getting ready to burst.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, urged to shoot more by Indiana coach Larry Bird after  
Game 3, wasn't a factor in this game at his favorite arena, either. 
By the time he turned a driving shot into a three-point play -- 
pumping his fist right in front of the Knicks' sideline -- the 
Pacers already had a double-digit lead with 96 seconds left. 
</P>
<P>
	``There at the end of the game, we kept telling Reggie to get  
the ball, get some shots, get some good looks at the basket,'' Bird 
said. ``He played a good defensive game. He's going to break 
loose.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But when? And are the Pacers too balanced, too tested, too  
determined for it to matter? 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a lot of guys who have been through these situations  
before,'' said Jalen Rose, one of those guys, who led the Pacers 
with 19 points. ``We're not going to panic, regardless of the 
situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, a Knicks-killer for the better part of a decade, picked  
up two fouls on successive plays in the span of a second early in 
the first quarter. He was 0-for-3 in the first half and didn't make 
his first basket until hitting a 3-pointer 3:57 into the third 
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a far cry from his scintillating 38-point performance in  
Game 4 of the conference semifinals last year -- including a 
3-pointer in front of Spike Lee that forced overtime with 5.7 left. 
The Pacers won 118-107 and won the series in five games. 
</P>
<P>
	With Miller again not at his best in this game, the Pacers  
showed the extent of their determination to avenge all the 
postseason runs that have fallen short this decade. The concurrent 
themes of payback and reconciliation have weighed heavily on their 
minds. 
</P>
<P>
	``Winning a championship is going to mean a lot to everybody,  
not just Larry,'' Miller said. ``He's toasted before. No one on our 
team, besides (assistant coach) Rick Carlisle, has toasted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After losing to Michael Jordan's Bulls in seven games in the  
Eastern Conference finals last year, they dedicated themselves to 
finishing their mission -- practicing during the lockout, never 
forgetting that the anguish they've inflicted on the Knicks in the 
playoffs will mean nothing if they don't cap it with a 
championship. 
</P>
<P>
	All along, it seemed only natural that Miller would carry them  
there. And yet he was 0-for-5 in the final four minutes of the 
first three games of this series. On the last possession of the 
Pacers' two losses, Miller didn't touch the ball. 
</P>
<P>
	``Superstars are supposed to get the basketball,'' said Bird, a  
man who understood this concept as well as anyone. ``Reggie didn't 
do that. A lot of great players do that, and he didn't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In this game, he didn't have to.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 15:10:14 </DATE_TIME>
