<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Falls on Kosovo Fears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The euro slipped even further against the dollar  
Monday as hopes receded for peace in Kosovo. The dollar fell 
against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0286, down  
from $1.0362 late Friday. The dollar also was quoted at 120.80 
Japanese yen, down from 122.22 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The standoff with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic over  
implementing the Kosovo peace agreement reached last week caused 
further jitters over Europe's new currency, which has been 
suffering since its debut in January. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said the euro could fall even further against the dollar  
unless some good news comes soon. Signs of weakness in major 
European economies such as Germany have also darkened the outlook 
for the young currency. 
</P>
<P>
	The yen, meanwhile, gained some ground against the dollar on  
reports that Japan's government may implement further fiscal 
stimulus measures in hopes of reviving that country's moribund 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.5436 Swiss francs, up from  
1.5310, and 1.4685 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4702. The British 
pound fell to $1.6005 from $1.6103. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Monday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.9015 German 
marks, up from 1.8875; 6.3776 French francs, up from 6.3291; and 
1,883.24 Italian lire, up from 1,869.16. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
