<DOCNO> APW19990607.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 12:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Baseballers Sue Over Video Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- With a click of a mouse, former Braves infielder  
Darrel Chaney can bat against the $105 million arm of Kevin Brown 
or the great Cy Young. 
</P>
<P>
	But unlike current players, who are paid through their union  
when computer game designers use their names and images, obscure 
players like Chaney don't get a dime. 
</P>
<P>
	And unlike Babe Ruth, Joe DiMaggio and Ted Williams, many  
ex-players don't have high-paid lawyers or estates to demand money 
from game designers. 
</P>
<P>
	Chaney, a .217 career hitter who had more strikeouts than hits,  
played 10 seasons for the Reds and Atlanta Braves before retiring 
in 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	He's leading a group of former major leaguers suing 10 computer  
game makers to try to get deals similar to those of current players 
-- from 8.5 percent to 9 percent of a game's net sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Chaney, who chairs the major league baseball alumni association  
committee that's pursuing the lawsuit, said the payments would be a 
big help to many retired players. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are some guys that are old and don't have much of a  
pension,'' said Chaney, who now works for an Atlanta corporate 
relocation service. ``They have no voice for them out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A similar complaint is pending in Los Angeles against Warner  
Communications' ``Hardball 5'' and the firm that distributed it. 
The suit was filed two years ago by a group that includes Don 
Newcombe and several members of the 1955 Brooklyn Dodgers. 
</P>
<P>
	Former pitcher Phil Niekro, outfielder Mike Lum and catcher  
Johnny Bench are the other plaintiffs in Chaney's suit. The players 
want to designate the lawsuit as class-action, meaning thousands of 
former players could sign on. Lawyers say they have talked to 
nearly 1,700 players interested in the lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Pete Rose, baseball's hit leader, batted .370 for the Reds in  
the 1975 World Series, while Chaney was hitless in two at-bats. But 
Chaney says they both are entitled to the same compensation from 
any company that wants to include ``The Big Red Machine'' in a 
computer game. 
</P>
<P>
	``My World Series winning check was the same as Pete Rose's, not  
a penny's difference,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The game makers, who oppose class-action status, argue the suit  
amounts to little more than a flimsy cash grab by players trying to 
profit from statistics. 
</P>
<P>
	Timothy Leyh, a Seattle lawyer for Sierra Online Inc., said the  
company used only the players' names and statistics -- ``historical 
facts that appear in any number of commercially available 
textbooks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an interesting case, but I think it's got more fluff than  
substance,'' Leyh said. ``The plaintiffs have made huge demands, 
which we think are way out of line.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sierra offered to pay 9 percent of sales on its ``Baseball '94:  
Legends and Stadiums,'' which sold poorly. The players rejected 
that offer. 
</P>
<P>
	``After all these years ... these guys want what's fair,'' said  
Atlanta lawyer Mark Van Spix, who represents Chaney's group. 
</P>
<P>
	One company, Microleague Multimedia Inc. of Lancaster, Pa.,  
settled for $350,000, plus 11 percent of future sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for the game makers say many of the companies can't  
afford the players' demands. Microleague, for example, has filed 
for bankruptcy. 
</P>
<P>
	Rex Heinke, who represents Warner in the California suit, argues  
that the players' identities are incidental to game sales. He said 
most of the games include specific teams to offer specific famous 
players. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unfortunately, the question comes down to one of what really  
is the value of someone who is an obscure player from a long time 
ago,'' said Paul Anderson, assistant director of the National 
Sports Law Institute at Marquette. 
</P>
<P>
	The players say even long-forgotten benchwarmers are important  
to the accuracy of the game. If a video game manager wants to match 
the 1975 Reds against the 1998 New York Yankees, there may come a 
point when Chaney will come off the bench to pinch hit with the 
game on the line. 
</P>
<P>
	Chaney is confident the players will prevail even if they don't  
get much money. 
</P>
<P>
	``At least it's a starting point,'' he said. ``To make people  
aware that former baseball players are people, too, and have 
certain rights.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 13:26:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Study of Mentally Ill Proposed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- At a White House conference on mental illness,  
President Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and their wives worked 
today to dispel myths about people who suffer from such illnesses 
as depression and schizophrenia. 
</P>
<P>
	``Americans with mental illness should have the same opportunity  
all Americans have to live to the fullest of their God-given 
abilities,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House used the gathering to announce a $7.3 million  
study by the National Institute of Mental Health to explore mental 
illness and a national training program for teachers to identify 
and help troubled children. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also notified the 285 health plans used by federal  
employees that they must cover mental illness and substance abuse, 
and he called on other employers to do the same. ``It is high time 
that our health plans treat all Americans equally,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Additionally, the administration was pressing Congress for  
legislation to stop forcing disabled people who are receiving 
Medicare or Medicaid to give up their benefits when they go to 
work. 
</P>
<P>
	The training program was developed with the help of the National  
Education Association and EchoStar, a satellite company based in 
Littleton, Colo., where two students killed a teacher, 12 
classmates and themselves earlier this year. EchoStar was donating 
1,000 satellite dishes and 40 hours of air time to the venture. 
</P>
<P>
	But more than changing policy, the conference was aimed at  
changing attitudes. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton drew parallels between the stigma surrounding mental  
illness and discrimination, saying the mentally disabled ``are 
perhaps just the latest in our enduring challenge as a people to 
continue the work of our founders to widen the circle of 
opportunity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tipper Gore, the vice president's wife, recounted for the  
audience at Howard University and listening nationwide how she 
sought treatment to overcome depression after her son was injured 
by a car. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want people that are within the sound of my voice, who  
perhaps are suffering with this or any other mental illness, to 
know that there is the right diagnosis and the right treatment and 
the right health care professional out there for you,'' she said. 
``Don't hold back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gore, a longtime advocate for the mentally ill, chaired the  
conference, which was linked electronically to 6,000 sites 
nationwide. CBS newsman Mike Wallace, who also overcame depression, 
joined the discussion. 
</P>
<P>
	Five Cabinet secretaries and more than 20 members of Congress  
from both parties were participating in the daylong session. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gore is working with Surgeon General David Satcher and the  
Ad Council to produce the campaign on mental illness. Clinton 
issued an executive order Friday to eliminate the government's 
stricter hiring and promotion standards for mentally disabled 
people. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 21:40:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Shopping for Stocks / Commentary  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                        *AP Business Analyst    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Neither fear nor Alan Greenspan's warnings nor  
even the lack of money seem strong enough to dampen the exuberant 
spirits of shoppers and investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Borrowing remains near all-time highs. The savings rate is down  
to zero. Demand for new cars continues at a pace unusually high for 
so aged an economy. And the same is true for housing. 
</P>
<P>
	You might as well add stocks to that list. But stocks are  
investments, not spending, you say. And it is true that some folks 
believe we should count stock purchases as savings. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics might point out major flaws in that reasoning, but the  
one that flashes in glaring red is that much of the current 
investing isn't being accomplished with cash but with credit, or as 
it's described on Wall Street, on margin. 
</P>
<P>
	In a way, you might say, the stock market is full of consumers,  
buying up stocks in the same way they buy houses and automobiles, 
which is with credit, More than $180 billion of it, as of April. 
</P>
<P>
	That figure, in fact, is for credit on only one exchange, the  
New York Stock Exchange, a relatively conservative institution. And 
it represents a one-month increase of no less than 17 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	There's nothing wrong with this, as market analysts will quickly  
argue, because stocks are more fairly valued now than just a few 
months ago and, in spite of earlier doubts, the economy is strong. 
</P>
<P>
	You don't have to look hard or in out of the way places to find  
evidence of this view of the economy. And during your search you 
might even detect a renewal of enthusiasm among brokers. 
</P>
<P>
	Morgan Stanley Dean Witter says investors might consider buying  
overseas stocks. T. Rowe Price sees good values among 
``long-neglected second-tier issues.'' Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette 
suggests investors might be underestimating future corporate 
profits. 
</P>
<P>
	But, even while regulatory officials seem unconcerned, at least  
publicly, it is hard to dismiss that margin debt. It is nine times 
the 1985 figure and 28 percent higher than last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Again, you'll find many defenses for such behavior, the most  
fascinating being the ``new era'' theory. We are, some will argue, 
in the midst of an Internet tidal wave that will transform life 
more fundamentally than the car, the radio, telephone and TV 
combined. 
</P>
<P>
	The new-era belief is so deep and so widely accepted, and the  
enthusiasm it generates so contagious, it overwhelms a sense of 
history. Past and present are far less significant than future. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past, a bullish goal was to double your money in five  
years. Today, that view sounds passe. EToys, a new issue originally 
slated to be offered at $10, closed at $76.56 on the same day. 
</P>
<P>
	In the old days, a stock was considered a good value if it  
maintained steady profits growth over a five-year span. Today, some 
of the hottest stocks earn nothing. 
</P>
<P>
	The argument for assessing these hot new stocks is that they are  
companies of the future. Building market share for tomorrow's 
Golden Age, it is explained, is more important than current 
earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe the future will prove current thinking to be correct. And  
if that is so, future historians will be compelled to concede that 
the 1990s was the beginning of a new economic and investment era. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 07:55:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Indonesia Takes Part in 'Free' Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                          *By THOMAS WAGNER    	
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- From the dense jungles of Irian Jaya  
to the rebellious province of Aceh, Indonesians got their first 
real taste of democracy since 1955 as they voted today for a new 
Parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	Wading through muddy rice fields, paddling canoes on outlying  
islands, and riding three-wheeled rickshaws through crowded cities, 
millions of people cast ballots for the assembly, which will help 
choose the next president. 
</P>
<P>
	It was another major step away from authoritarian rule that  
ended when riots by pro-democracy student groups forced President 
Suharto to resign in May 1998 after 32 years in power. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a real democracy now, not like before,'' said Muswantoro,  
a 55-year-old English teacher, after voting at a makeshift booth in 
a soccer field in the village of Rempoa near the capital, Jakarta. 
</P>
<P>
	Most Indonesians have never voted in a truly free election. The  
first and last open ballot was 44 years ago. The ones that followed 
were largely rigged to ensure that candidates from the ruling 
Golkar Party won. 
</P>
<P>
	Up for grabs are 462 of Parliament's 500 seats. The rest go to  
appointees of the powerful military, which is not allowed to vote. 
The new legislators will join 200 government appointees to choose a 
new president in November. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite heavy rain in Jakarta and other areas, a big turnout was  
expected, with an estimated 112 million registered voters in the 
world's fourth most populous nation and its largest Muslim country. 
</P>
<P>
	There were minor disturbances linked to confusion about whether  
voters could register at the last minute, said Adnan Buyung 
Nasution, chairman of the General Election Commission. Three ballot 
boxes at a station near Jakarta were set on fire in a registration 
dispute, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the commission chief said problems were insignificant  
compared with the overall success of voting in the far-flung 
Southeast Asian archipelago. 
</P>
<P>
	However, in Aceh, a province in northern Sumatra island where  
separatist guerrillas oppose the election, many people refused to 
vote, said Yusuf Ismail, a member of a local human rights group. 
``The people were too scared,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Polling was postponed in four Aceh districts because of militant  
attacks, and ballot boxes at a polling station in the area were set 
on fire. Two stations in Irian Jaya province were closed because of 
flooding. 
</P>
<P>
	Polls began closing in the afternoon to get the laborious  
counting process started before sunset. Officials go through the 
boxes ballot by ballot, with one reading out the results while 
another uses a marker on standardized forms. 
</P>
<P>
	Andi Mallerengang of the General Election Commission said early  
results showed front-runner Megawati Sukarnoputri's Indonesian 
Democratic Party for Struggle doing very well in Jakarta, the 
sprawling capital of 11 million people. 
</P>
<P>
	He estimated she could win up to 50 percent of the vote there,  
but stressed that the pattern of voting in other areas could be 
different, and more complete results should be available within two 
days. 
</P>
<P>
	Tallies from outlying areas are expected to take days, with some  
ballot boxes being ferried by foot and canoe. 
</P>
<P>
	Megawati's party was unlikely to win a majority in Parliament,  
creating the need for coalitions among the 48 parties that fielded 
at least 11,000 candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's just wait for the result,'' said Megawati, the daughter  
of Indonesia's founding President Sukarno, after voting near her 
home on the southern outskirts of Jakarta. 
</P>
<P>
	In Jakarta, President B.J. Habibie, Suharto's former protege and  
leader of the Golkar Party, voted with his wife, Hasri Ainun. ``God 
willing, this election will be free, just and fair,'' said Habibie. 
</P>
<P>
	Suharto was accompanied by three of his six children to the  
polls. The former president -- now besieged by allegations of 
massive corruption during his rule -- raised his ballot for the 
television cameras and smiled. 
</P>
<P>
	But Megawati's party won in the polling stations where Suharto  
and Habibie cast their ballots. Golkar was fourth at one and third 
at the other. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of foreign monitors, including former President Jimmy  
Carter, were on hand to help hundreds of thousands of Indonesian 
volunteers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think there's any doubt (the election) will bring an  
end to violence and open up the country to immediate economic 
improvement,'' said Carter as he toured a voting station in Rempoa. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the first areas to vote was East Timor, where many people  
see an Aug. 8 referendum on the territory's future as far more 
significant than the national election. 
</P>
<P>
	The referendum will decide whether the impoverished former  
Portuguese colony, invaded by Indonesia in 1975 and annexed the 
following year, should become an autonomous state or go its own way 
as a fledgling nation. 
</P>
<P>
	East Timorese voters said Indonesian authorities and their  
militant supporters coerced people into voting, reasoning that high 
turnout in this election equals support for staying a part of 
Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	``The authorities told me that if I didn't vote, there would be  
bad consequences,'' said independence supporter Augusto Gomes. 
``They'd come and interrogate me. I'm very afraid of that.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 07:55:26 </DATE_TIME>
