<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Election 2000 Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton won't get any help from  
a leading abortion-rights group if she runs for the Senate against 
New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. 
</P>
<P>
	Kate Michelman, president of the National Abortion and  
Reproductive Rights Action League, said Monday that her group won't 
take sides in the race because both likely candidates are 
abortion-rights advocates. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will not be choosing one over the other. She has been a  
strong advocate of a woman's right to choose and he has been 
extraordinarily strong as well,'' Michelman said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	The group's political director, Gloria A. Totten, said NARAL  
plans to help abortion-rights candidates get elected to the White 
House and Congress in 2000. Mrs. Clinton has been a champion of 
NARAL's cause, ``so it won't be easy'' to take a pass on her likely 
Senate candidacy, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``She understands that we have to be careful how we dedicate our  
resources,'' Totten said of Mrs. Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	----	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A top fund-raiser for Dan Quayle has left his  
2000 presidential campaign, as aides predict a slight dip in 
contributions from the first quarter reporting period. 
</P>
<P>
	Jennifer Hodges, finance director in Quayle's Phoenix, Ariz.,  
office, was in charge of day-to-day operations of the Quayle money 
machine. Her deputy, Liesl Hickey, also left the campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesman Jonathan Baron said the pair ``made the decision to  
depart the campaign, as often happens in presidential campaigns.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said Quayle has added staff in Iowa, New Hampshire and  
Phoenix, including fund-raisers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a very good first quarter,'' Baron said. ``We'll have a  
solid second quarter, given the realities of the fund-raising 
environment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The reality is that front-runner George W. Bush raised nearly $8  
million in the first three months of 1999, compared to Quayle who 
finished second in the GOP field with $2.1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle advisers say the former vice president has already raised  
$1 million in the second quarter -- which ends June 30 -- but 
probably won't match his first-quarter figure. On the other hand, 
the Texas governor expects to at least match his $8 million 
first-quarter showing. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican presidential candidate Steve Forbes  
has named the head of the National Restaurant Association to be 
national co-chairman of his 2000 campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Herman Cain, chairman of Godfather's Pizza, will work with Ohio  
Secretary of State Ken Blackwell who is Forbes' national chairman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
