<DOCNO> APW19990607.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 19:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orange County Reaches Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) -- Orange County has reached a $20.8  
million settlement with 12 finance and securities firms connected 
to the largest municipal bankruptcy in U.S. history, officials 
announced today. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement is subject to approval by the U.S. Bankruptcy  
Court and would bring the total amount recovered by the county to 
$860.58 million. The cases stem from the infamous $1.64 billion 
collapse of Orange County's investment pool in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	The out-of-court settlement brings to a close most of the  
numerous lawsuits the county filed in the case. Settlements were 
reached previously with 15 other firms, whose brokers and dealers 
were accused of contributing to the county's downturn. 
</P>
<P>
	Merrill Lynch agreed last year to pay the county $437.1 million  
to settle a lawsuit accusing the firm of giving bad advice that 
contributed to the financial collapse. 
</P>
<P>
	A lawsuit against the Standard &AMP; Poor's rating service has not  
been settled and is headed for trial soon in Los Angeles. The 
settlements announced Monday will have no bearing on the case, said 
Leah Johnson, director of communications for the bond rating 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	All proceeds from the lawsuit settlements will be applied to the  
county's remaining debt, said Gary Burton, the county's chief 
financial officer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're happy to have this behind us because we're working on  
financial planning and in putting good management practices in 
place,'' Burton said. ``This allows us to focus on that, rather 
than bankruptcy issues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The county would receive only 38 percent of the settlements,  
which must be shared with other participants in the failed 
investment pool, Burton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies that agreed to settle with the county include:  
Bank of America Securities; Citibank and Citicorp Securities; Fuji 
Securities; Lehman Brothers; PaineWebber; Prudential Securities; 
Smith Barney; Cantor Fitzgerald Securities Corp.; Daiwa Securities 
America Inc.; Donaldson Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Securities Corp.; Kidder, 
Peabody &AMP; Co.; Sanwa Securities USA. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 15:10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Karsay Giving Tribe Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Steve Karsay bounded off the mound to one of  
the strangest sights and sounds at Jacobs Field all season -- fans 
standing to cheer an Indians pitcher. 
</P>
<P>
	Karsay's two-strike curveball made Sammy Sosa swing at air. And  
as he headed toward the dugout, Karsay tipped his cap as Cleveland 
fans saluted a pitcher who in two months has gone from being fairly 
unknown to nearly unhittable. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's great to get an ovation like that when you're coming out  
of a game,'' Karsay said. ``Things have gone my way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't long ago Karsay wondered if he would ever pitch in the  
big leagues again, never mind having a ballpark full of 40,000 fans 
roaring for him. 
</P>
<P>
	Karsay, a career starter who has been slowed by elbow injuries,  
is pitching out of the bullpen for the first time. And although he 
longs to start once more, Karsay has flourished in his new role and 
become the MVP of Cleveland's staff. 
</P>
<P>
	He's 5-1 with a 2.06 ERA with a team-leading 25 appearances, and  
with a new splitter and fastball clocking 100 mph on a pitch to 
Sosa on Sunday, Karsay has struck out 39 in 39 1-3 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	No matter when or for how long Indians manager Mike Hargrove has  
needed him, Karsay has come through. 
</P>
<P>
	``We asked Steve to do something that he had not really ever  
done before,'' said Hargrove, booed Sunday when he pulled Karsay. 
``I think that truth be known, he probably wasn't really 
comfortable with it to begin with, but he really has taken it and 
run with it. He has done a great job for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Karsay, acquired after the 1997 season from Oakland, came to the  
Indians with a short pitching resume and an overstuffed medical 
file. 
</P>
<P>
	After being taken by Toronto with the 22nd overall pick in the  
1990 draft, Karsay began having elbow problems and underwent 
several operations. But after being traded in 1993 to the A's for 
Rickey Henderson, cartilage damage forced him to shut down after 
just four starts in '94. 
</P>
<P>
	His elbow didn't respond well and the following spring he  
decided to have ``Tommy John'' surgery. Karsay missed all of 1995 
and began his slow return in the California League pitching against 
the likes of Lake Elsinore and Rancho Cucamunga. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, he's striking out Sosa, and fanning the side in order to  
beat the Yankees in New York last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's always doubts in the back of your mind after you've  
had a major surgery,'' he said. ``'Can I come back and be as good 
as I was before I had the surgery'. A lot of hard work will pay off 
for you. It's paid off for me. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always knew I could pitch at this level and be successful.  
It was just a matter of time after the surgery that I was going to 
get the opportunity and show what I could do. It's just coming out 
now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Karsay's emergence provides Hargrove with a current luxury and a  
possible dilemma. If Jaret Wright or Dwight Gooden continue to 
struggle, Hargrove would be tempted to move Karsay into the 
starting rotation at the cost of weakening his bullpen. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's real good right now where he's at,'' Hargrove said. ``It  
remains an option for us. Having Steve in the bullpen gives us a 
legitimate chance to win every game we play. If we take Steve out 
of that mix, it still gives us a chance to win but it takes a 
little of that (bullpen) depth from us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Karsay, who has made 37 career starts, isn't knocking on  
Hargrove's office door every day to ask for a chance to make No. 
38. He's confident his time will come. And, anyway, this long 
relief gig isn't so bad. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was bred a starter, and I will probably always be a starter  
in the back of my mind,'' he said. ``I feel like I can start, but 
we have five capable guys who are doing a great job in this 
rotation. But if it's a year down the road or three years down the 
road, then so be it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 16:31:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  WNBA Adds Four Teams for 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The WNBA is growing up fast.  
</P>
<P>
	Set to enter its third season this week, the women's basketball  
league on Monday added four teams that will begin play in 2000 -- 
Miami, Seattle, Indianapolis and Portland, Ore. 
</P>
<P>
	The expansion, yet another step up for a league backed by the  
NBA's money and marketing savvy, comes six months after the rival 
American Basketball League folded, leaving the WNBA the only pro 
women's league in the country. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had not anticipated expanding this quickly,'' WNBA  
president Val Ackerman said. ``But the combination of the success 
of the league in the first two seasons and the strong interest 
expressed by NBA owners has convinced us that the time is right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The additions will bring the league to 16 teams, double the  
number from the first season. Ackerman would not disclose the cost 
of the new franchises. 
</P>
<P>
	The 12-team WNBA opens its season Thursday night, with new teams  
in Minnesota and Orlando. The league added teams in Detroit and 
Washington last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``It does something for the city of Indianapolis and the state  
of Indiana,'' Pacers president Donnie Walsh said. ``And it 
legitimizes the WNBA because, how could you have a league and we're 
not in it in women's basketball?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Purdue, in West Lafayette, Ind., won the women's NCAA basketball  
championship and it's coach, Carolyn Peck, left to coach the 
Orlando Miracle in the WNBA. 
</P>
<P>
	Ackerman said no target date had been set for further expansion,  
but she indicated more than four cities expressed interest for 
2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``The challenge now is to roll out new teams for the future,''  
Ackerman said, adding that the WNBA would award franchises only to 
NBA cities. ``It makes no sense to go to places where there is no 
NBA infrastructure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Average attendance in the WNBA last year was more than 10,000,  
an increase of 8 percent from 1997. Ackerman said the average 
ticket price in the WNBA is about $14, with some seats $5. 
</P>
<P>
	The 48 players for the teams that begin playing next year will  
come mostly from the defunct ABL, players who lost their WNBA jobs 
this season because of the influx of ABL players and college 
seniors. The teams' nicknames and logos have yet to be determined. 
</P>
<P>
	The ABL, which began as a fall-winter league in 1996, folded  
after 2 1/2 seasons, filing for bankruptcy in December. Both leagues 
began with hopes of capitalizing on the gold-medal performance of 
the U.S. women's team at the Atlanta Olympics and the growing 
popularity on the college level. 
</P>
<P>
	Several other women's leagues have come and gone over the years.  
The Women's Basketball League survived just three years before 
folding in 1981 because it ran out of money. 
</P>
<P>
	However, because the WNBA has the NBA's backing, along with  
sponsors and TV contracts, it is less vulnerable to such problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Before getting final approval, the four expansion teams must  
sell at least 5,500 season tickets by Oct. 15. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of the new teams will play in new arenas -- Indianapolis in  
the Canseco Field House, which opens in November, and Miami in the 
American Airlines Arena, which opens Dec. 31. 
</P>
<P>
	In Portland, the new team will fill the void left by the ABL's  
Portland Power. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe this is a tremendous market for women's  
basketball,'' said Harry Hutt, the Portland Trail Blazers' vice 
president of marketing, who put together the team's pitch to the 
WNBA. ``It's exciting that young girls all over the state of Oregon 
will now have their very own sports role models.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under the alignment plan next year, Indiana and Miami will be in  
the Eastern Conference, along with Charlotte, Cleveland, Detroit, 
New York, Orlando and Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Portland and Seattle will play in the Western Conference with  
Houston, Los Angeles, Minnesota, Phoenix, Sacramento and Utah. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 16:31:00 </DATE_TIME>
