<DOCNO> APW19990607.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 07:46:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets closed sharply higher  
Monday, boosted by Friday's rally on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, the blue chip Hang Seng Index rose 421.85 points,  
or 3.4 percent, closing at 12,837.39. On Friday, the index had 
gained 56.07 points, or 0.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hong Kong market was shortened to a 90-minute trading  
session because tropical storm Maggie forced a shutdown in all 
financial markets in the morning as it swept into south China. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers said prices rose in reaction to gains on Wall Street,  
where the Dow Jones industrial average rose 1.3 percent Friday 
after U.S. employment data for May came in weaker than expected and 
eased fears of an imminent rise in U.S. interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Any rise in U.S. interest rates is usually followed by a similar  
hike in Hong Kong because the Hong Kong dollar is pegged to the 
U.S. dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 175.14  
points, or 1.07 percent, ending at 16,475.89. On Friday, the Nikkei 
closed up 73.25 points, or 0.45 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said the rise in Tokyo was mainly futures-led, although  
individual shares in the high-technology and pharmaceutical sectors 
also put on big gains mirroring the movement of their counterparts 
in New York Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Also boosting the stock market was news that the government  
decided on Friday to close Toho Mutual Life Insurance Co., a 
troubled medium-sized Japanese insurance company. The company's 
liabilities were found to have exceeded its assets by 200 billion 
Japanese yen ($1.64 billion). 
</P>
<P>
	On the currency market, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 120.84 yen  
late afternoon, down 0.78 yen from late Friday in Tokyo and below 
its New York level of 122.22 yen late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	South Korean shares closed sharply higher, with the main index  
surging 5.6 percent following a fall in local interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The Korea Composite Stock Price Index rose 44.82 points to  
842.32, its highest close since July 11, 1996, when the index stood 
at 847.39. 
</P>
<P>
	The market was closed in Jakarta because of elections in  
Indonesia. The New Zealand market was also closed for a holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Share prices closed higher in a rally sparked by  
technology stocks, with the main index rising to a new high for the 
year. The Weighted Stock Price Index rose 163.39 points, or 2.1 
percent, to 7,802.69. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine stocks closed higher, boosted by a rally in  
shares of Philippine Long Distance Telephone Co. and a cut in the 
central bank's overnight rates following lower-than-expected 
inflation in May. The 30-share Philippine Stock Exchange Index rose 
48.41 points, or 2.1 percent, to 2,403.01. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian share prices closed higher, following  
Friday's gains on Wall Street. The All Ordinaries Index closed at 
2,944.10, up 14.80 points, or 0.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian shares fell as investors cautiously sat  
on the sidelines amid expectations that prices could drift lower in 
the absence of market-moving news. The benchmark Kuala Lumpur 
Composite Index fell 1.2 percent, or 8.79 points, to 731.01. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Share prices closed mostly higher, boosted by Wall  
Street's gains and the peaceful Indonesian election campaign. The 
Straits Times Index rose 27.04 points, or 1.4 percent, to 1,955.41. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai share prices closed higher. The Thailand SET Index  
rose 6.78 points, or 1.4 percent, to 483.25. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
