<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 13:30:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> British, Dutch Steel Cos. To Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- British Steel PLC's proposed $6.5 billion merger  
with Dutch metals maker Koninklijke Hoogovens NV would make it No. 
1 among Europe's steel producers, but some analysts were 
questioning whether in this case, bigger really is better. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal announced today will give the combined company a larger  
stake in the regional steel market, allow it to cut an estimated 
$313 million in annual costs and give it a stronger position as a 
supplier of steel for Europe's auto industry. Left unanswered, 
analysts said, were concerns about how the company would deal with 
with issues facing all steelmakers -- overcapacity in the industry 
and slumping demand in key markets like Russia and East Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact that you're a big volume producer is not going to  
make you a competitive producer. What matters is the quality of 
your steel and your relationship with clients,'' said Mark Horn, 
head of European research at the stock brokerage T. Hoare 
Canaccord. 
</P>
<P>
	The planned merger means the wave of consolidation sweeping  
Europe's banks and telecommunications firms is lapping also at 
heavy manufacturing firms. The combined company would be the 
world's third-biggest steelmaker. 
</P>
<P>
	Like many other companies seeking mergers, British Steel needed  
help to lift its earnings. The company had a loss equivalent to 
$130.6 million for the year ending April 3, compared to a net 
profit of $364.5 million the previous year. 
</P>
<P>
	Annual sales fell by 10 percent to $10.42 billion from $11.56  
billion. The company blamed the effects of Asia's financial crisis 
and the strong British pound, which has made British-made steel 
more costly than steel made in other European countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoogovens' net profit, meanwhile, fell 17 percent in 1998 to  
$196.7 million. 
</P>
<P>
	As Europe's largest steelmaker, the combined company would have  
annual sales worth $14.9 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal must be approved by regulators and shareholders. Upon  
approval, shareholders of both firms would receive stock in the new 
company, initially to be called BSKH. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed merger marks a major turning point in the life of  
one of Britain's best-known businesses. British Steel was once 
symbolic of the country's uncompetitive industries. Privatized in 
1988, it now employs fewer than 40,000 people in Britain, compared 
to 250,000 in the 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	British Steel, which sells commodity-grade steel along with more  
specialized varieties, has long complained that the strong pound 
has hurt its exports. It should benefit by transferring some its 
production costs outside of Britain. 
</P>
<P>
	The company will have an improved position as a supplier of  
high-quality flat steel that is used in Europe's auto industry, 
said Philippe Haspeslagh, a professor of corporate strategy at 
INSEAD, an international business school in Fontainebleau, France. 
</P>
<P>
	But Europe's steel producers face falling prices, cheap imports  
and excess supply, and the industry shows little sign of an 
immediate improvement in demand, said Eric Sardain, senior steel 
analyst in London for the investment bank Dresdner Kleinwort 
Benson. 
</P>
<P>
	Asian nations used to import 50 million tons of steel per year.  
Now, Asia is a net exporter of steel, Sardain said. 
</P>
<P>
	British Steel's stock fell 6.8 percent Monday to 150.75 pence,  
or $2.43, per share. In Amsterdam, Hoogovens' share price rose 1.6 
percent to 45.70 euros, or $47.41. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 04:40:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Uncomfortably hot weather slipped across much of the nation  
today, pushing sultry air from New England to Arizona and sparking 
storms in the Great Lakes, Gulf Coast and Plains. 
</P>
<P>
	Northern and central New England were expected to have showers,  
powerful winds and thunderstorms as a result of a mixed system 
hovering over the Northeast and Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	To the south and east, the rest of the Northeast and the  
mid-Atlantic states should have clear to partly cloudy skies and 
hot weather. The dry weather was forecast to extend as far south as 
southern Georgia. 
</P>
<P>
	Afternoon heat and abundant moisture were expected to create  
scattered showers and thunderstorms from the Tennessee Valley, 
south and west into the lower Mississippi Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	Scattered showers and thunderstorms also were forecast from the  
eastern Great Lakes and Ohio Valley, southwest into the 
mid-Mississippi Valley and southern Plains. 
</P>
<P>
	North and west of this area, clear to partly cloudy skies and  
dry weather was likely to extend from the western Great Lakes, 
south and west into the central Plains. 
</P>
<P>
	Successive waves of storms that swept across Wisconsin on Sunday  
and early today damaged buildings, uprooted trees and tore down 
power lines. Thunderstorms also swept through Michigan, knocking 
out power to more than 6,000 homes in the northwest Lower 
Peninsula. 
</P>
<P>
	Thunderstorms again were predicted today in the northern and  
central Rockies. A few of the storms also could make it into the 
western Dakotas by afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Damaging winds and hail were expected to be the primary threats  
from the storms, although a few tornadoes will be possible during 
the afternoon and evening hours. 
</P>
<P>
	A weak low pressure was expected to bring a few light rain  
showers to the Pacific Northwest. Further south, high pressure was 
forecast to bring partly cloudy skies and dry weather from 
California and Nevada, south and east into the southern Rockies and 
Southwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's forecast highs: in the 60s for the Pacific Northwest; in  
the mid- to upper-70s in the Great Lakes, central Rockies, 
California coast and Ohio Valley; in the 80s in the northern New 
England, northern Plains, Tennessee and Mississippi Valley; and in 
the 90s in New England, the mid-Atlantic states and desert 
Southwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Extremes in the Lower 48 states on Sunday ranged from a high of  
100 degrees in Del Rio, Texas, to a low of 28 degrees in Mullan 
Pass, Idaho. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 14:50:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Airliners Clip Wings in Los Angeles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Two 747 jumbo jets clipped wings on a taxiway  
at Los Angeles International Airport, forcing the evacuation of 
more than 700 passengers. No injuries were reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Philippine Airlines Flight 103 was headed to a runway for  
takeoff when it clipped wings with Corsair Flight 942, which was 
being towed to a gate after arriving from Paris. 
</P>
<P>
	The late Sunday morning collision severely damaged the wing of  
the Corsair jet and punctured its fuel tank, but no fuel spilled. 
There was minor damage to the wing of the other jet. 
</P>
<P>
	Airport officials said there were 430 people on the Philippine  
Airlines jet and 275 on the Corsair jet. 
</P>
<P>
	Philippine Airlines passengers were taken to nearby hotels and  
booked on other flights scheduled to leave for Manila on Monday, 
company spokeswoman Patricia Waln said. 
</P>
<P>
	Corsair officials did not return phone calls seeking comment.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
