<DOCNO> APW19990607.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 17:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mr. Marlin Going Home As Oriole </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Jeff Conine stood at his locker, shaking hands and  
greeting acquaintances who filed past in a steady procession worthy 
of a visiting dignitary. 
</P>
<P>
	In Miami, Conine is just that.  
</P>
<P>
	The sight of former Florida Marlins in the visiting clubhouse  
has become commonplace at Pro Player Stadium, but there's only one 
Mr. Marlin. Conine was back Monday to play his first game in Miami 
since being traded 18 months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems like I have dyslexia today -- the wrong locker room,  
the wrong side of the field,'' he said before the Marlins' game 
against Baltimore was postponed by rain. ``It's a weird feeling, 
but life goes on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Conine is now a first baseman for the Orioles, but his roots and  
winter home remain in South Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	From the expansion Marlins' first game in 1993, when Conine went  
4-for-4, he was a cornerstone of the franchise. In 1997 he was 
demoted to a platoon role, sharing first base duties with Darren 
Daulton, but still hit 17 homers for the World Series champions. 
</P>
<P>
	Then owner H. Wayne Huizenga dismantled the team, and Conine was  
among the first to go. General manager Dave Dombrowski traded him 
to Kansas City for pitching prospect Blaine Mull. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because of the nostalgia going back to opening day, it  
represented the end of an era in a way,'' Dombrowski said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The way we left was not the best circumstances,'' Conine said.  
``It's sad in that fact, but it's great to be back. I get to stay 
in my own bed for a couple of nights.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He rode to the stadium Monday with Marlins closer Matt Mantei  
and stopped by the home team's clubhouse, where he encountered few 
former teammates. They've been traded away too. 
</P>
<P>
	Conine said he's impressed by the Marlins' young talent. He  
noted a contrast in moods between Florida (which began the week 
21-36 with an $18 million payroll) and Baltimore (21-34, $78 
million). 
</P>
<P>
	``We're getting beaten down because we have a big payroll and  
we're not winning,'' he said. ``They're probably ecstatic because 
they're playing well and they've got no payroll.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although the Orioles have been a flop, Conine has personally  
rebounded from a poor year in Kansas City. He began the week 
batting .293 with four homers and 27 RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	Conine, who turns 33 this month, becomes a free agent at the end  
of the year. There's already speculation about his possible return 
to Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a guy everybody thinks the world of down here,''  
Dombrowski said. ``For the fans, he has a special place in 
everybody's heart. But I don't know what his ambitions are or where 
we'll be at that point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If the Marlins decide they're looking for a veteran first  
baseman-outfielder to provide some experience on their young team, 
Conine is interested. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously I'd be willing to listen to anyone and anything,''  
he said. ``It's a little far away to be discussing now, but it's 
always nice to play at home.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
