<HEADLINE> Soybeans, Grains, Advance / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean and grain futures prices finished higher  
in trading Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade but retreated from 
a morning rally that saw July soybeans up more than 8 cents a 
bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts attributed the early surges to reports of continued  
above-normal temperatures in the Midwest in the next week. The 
thought was that hot, dry weather could damage early planted crops, 
eventually resulting in smaller crops and higher prices. 
</P>
<P>
	But analysts say traders backed off from some of those concerns  
by midday. 
</P>
<P>
	Thoughts that dry weather will aid in the harvest of winter  
wheat also kept wheat futures in check, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery rose 1 cent to $2.57 3/4 a bushel; July  
corn was up 1 3/4 cent to $2.22 1/2 a bushel; July oats rose 3 cents to 
$1.26 1/2 a bushel; and July soybeans surged 3 3/4 cents to $4.68 1/4 a 
bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, beef futures were mostly up on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange, while pork futures were mostly lower. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle rose .90 cent to 65.80 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle were up .93 cent to 77.70 cents a pound; June lean 
hogs fell .08 cent to 51.92 cents a pound; and July pork bellies 
fell .83 cent to 52.62 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
