<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Won't Stop Canyon Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Environmental groups that want the government  
to act more quickly to reduce noise from sightseeing planes flying 
over the Grand Canyon lost a Supreme Court appeal today. 
</P>
<P>
	The court, without comment, turned away the groups' argument  
that the government has failed to meet the legally required 
deadlines for reducing such aircraft noise. 
</P>
<P>
	A 1987 federal law says Grand Canyon flights were ``causing a  
significant adverse effect on the natural quiet and experience of 
the park'' and also raised safety concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	The law gave the Interior secretary 30 days to make  
recommendations to the Federal Aviation Adminstration, which had 
another 90 days to issue a final plan to control air traffic over 
the canyon. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years after that, the Interior secretary was to report to  
Congress on whether noise had been reduced. 
</P>
<P>
	Initial federal action took months longer than the law required,  
and the report to Congress in 1994 said further noise reduction was 
needed. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA issued in late 1996 a final rule that created new  
flight-free zones, limited the hours flights could operate and 
limited the number of planes that could be used. The agency said 
that if additional rules were adopted, the law's goals would be 
reached by 2008. 
</P>
<P>
	The rules were challenged in federal court by air tour operators  
and others who said the government was moving too quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	In contrast, the seven environmental groups -- including the  
Grand Canyon Trust and the Wilderness Society -- contended that the 
government was moving too slowly. They sought an order requiring 
the government to act immediately to reduce aircraft noise at the 
park. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia  
rejected all the challenges. The court said the environmental 
groups' frustration with the government's ``slow and faltering pace 
is understandable'' but that it was unfair to say officials had 
done nothing during the past decade. 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal acted on today, the environmental groups' lawyers  
said the appeals court deferred too much to the government. ``Under 
this approach, no delay is unreasonable,'' the appeal said. 
</P>
<P>
	The government's lawyers said it had acted reasonably, adding,  
``during the day, natural quiet has been restored in much of the 
park.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Grand Canyon Trust vs. FAA, 98-1417.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
