<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Economy Losing To S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) -- The signs of South Africa's success are  
everywhere in Kenya. 
</P>
<P>
	Cartons of South Africa's Ceres juices line grocery shelves  
where there used to be cans of Kenya's Treetop orange. Bartenders 
serve up South African Castle beer alongside locally produced 
Tusker. 
</P>
<P>
	Apples. Wine. Eggs. Cheese. Barbecue grills. All bearing South  
African labels. 
</P>
<P>
	Five years ago, when South Africa was a commercial pariah, such  
sights were unthinkable. But since 1994, when South Africa held its 
first all-race elections and the heavy gates of apartheid sanctions 
swung open, the country has positioned itself as Africa's super 
exporter, and its goods have flooded central and east African 
markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Following the June 2 presidential elections, South Africa was  
expected to continue to be an economic force on the continent -- 
something that concerns many in Kenya, East Africa's biggest 
economy. Political and business circles have been abuzz for several 
weeks with talk of the massive trade imbalance and accusations of 
unfair barriers and tariffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``We no longer accept to be the dumping ground of South African  
goods,'' Kenyan Trade Minister Joseph Kamotho told African leaders 
in Nairobi for a recent regional trade summit. 
</P>
<P>
	But while Kenyan businesses say they can't get their products  
into South Africa and trade officials threaten higher tariffs, 
analysts and some locals say the blame is being misplaced. 
</P>
<P>
	Kenya became accustomed during apartheid to being the region's  
biggest economy, discouraging imports with heavy taxes until the 
early 1990s when it opened its doors. However, some analysts say it 
also failed to invest in its own industries. 
</P>
<P>
	Unused to competition, Kenyan products don't measure up here or  
in South Africa, which became highly developed and self-sufficient 
during apartheid. 
</P>
<P>
	``All countries find reasons to protect their industries, and  
here we've failed to protect ours,'' said Peter Gachuba, a 
financial consultant with KPMG Peat Marwick in Nairobi. 
</P>
<P>
	Corruption is the main problem, Gachuba says. The Kenyan  
government has allowed people to illegally import South African 
goods and dump them on the market, he says, and Kenyan executives 
know they can buy their way around safety or quality requirements. 
</P>
<P>
	``People in the streets say, 'There's so much stuff from South  
Africa,' but when they go to the store, that's what they buy. I 
think there is some feeling that our products aren't that good and 
you can't trust things,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Others say the competition benefits Kenya because it lifts  
quality. And the average consumer gains access to a wider range of 
goods -- at cheaper prices. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's good because it has made us wake up,'' said Joyce Kimuhu,  
a member of a women's craft cooperative that displayed its goods 
for export at the trade summit. 
</P>
<P>
	South Africa's defenders note that it has invested deeply in  
Kenya, building such plants as the $45 million Castle Brewery, one 
of the biggest single foreign investments in Kenya. 
</P>
<P>
	But many still feel bitter about South Africa, which in 1997  
became Kenya's leading source of imports, a role once shared by 
Europe and Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	The most common complaint is the widening trade gap: Kenya  
imports 18 times more from South Africa than it exports. 
</P>
<P>
	Comparable Kenyan products can't compete in South Africa, as  
it's cheaper to make goods in South Africa, which has a larger home 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	Many feel South Africa exacerbates the gap by creating  
unnecessary barriers, like requiring foreign tea to be mixed with 
an equal part of local tea. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an indirect way of saying 'No,' '' said Phillip Biegon, a  
Kenya Tea Packers salesman. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffiths Memela, the South African High Commissioner to Kenya,  
has publicly denied unfair trade accusations and says Kenya hasn't 
aggressively marketed its goods. 
</P>
<P>
	South African businessmen are taking the complaints seriously,  
however, and have formed the South African Business Association of 
Kenya to boost their image. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe it's a good sign that we're bringing out all these  
hidden problems,'' said Adam Fuller, the group's chairman. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
