<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 20:30:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ben Hogan Room To Be Unveiled  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FAR HILLS, N.J. (AP) -- Ben Hogan's wife spent Monday touring the  
first room at the USGA Museum to be dedicated to the life and 
career of a professional golfer. 
</P>
<P>
	Valerie Hogan donated the collection of more than 300 objects --  
including her late husband's famed 1-iron -- in July. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know he would be pleased that the public can come to see his  
things,'' Mrs. Hogan, his wife of 62 years, said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ben Hogan Room will open to the public on Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
	The display includes items from Hogan's days as a young caddie  
in Fort Worth, Texas. His recovery from a near-fatal car-bus 
accident and historic championship record also are recorded. 
</P>
<P>
	Visitors can view the set of irons that Hogan used to earn the  
Masters, U.S Open and British Open titles in 1953. His medals from 
various tournaments are also on display, as is an actual locker 
from his home club, Shady Oaks Country Club in Fort Worth. 
</P>
<P>
	An area rug in the Hogan room reads: ``The prospect that there  
was going to be golf in (my day) made me feel privileged and 
extremely happy, and I couldn't wait for the sun to come up the 
next morning so that I could get out on the course again.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Eds: The USGA Museum is open weekdays from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. and  
on weekends from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. Admission is free. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
