<HEADLINE> Former NFL QB Joins CFL's BC Lions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- Quarterback Todd Marinovich,  
a first-round pick in the 1991 NFL draft, is getting another 
chance. 
</P>
<P>
	Once the starter for the then-Los Angeles Raiders, Marinovich  
reached a one-year deal Monday with the B.C. Lions of the Canadian 
Football League, where he will sit on the bench. 
</P>
<P>
	``Todd will be given the opportunity to be the backup,'' said  
Greg Mohns, the Lions head coach and assistant general manager. 
``It was made very plain and clear from the start to Todd that 
Damon (Allen) was our No. 1 quarterback.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marinovich, 29, hasn't played football since 1994 when he  
suffered a serious knee injury during training camp with the CFL's 
Winnipeg Blue Bombers. He hasn't dressed for a game since 1992, 
when he was with the Raiders, who drafted the 6-foot-4, 220-pound 
Marinovich 24th overall in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've always had the itch (to play again), and it progressively  
got stronger,'' Marinovich said Monday at a news conference in 
Vancouver. ``I decided to get back into it before it got too old.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, he was sentenced to six months in jail after pleading  
guilty to a felony charge of cultivating marijuana. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, the NFL cleared Marinovich to pursue a comeback. He  
worked out with Chicago, Seattle, New Orleans and Washington, but 
never signed an NFL contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a growing process, everybody goes through tough times and  
it makes a person stronger,'' Marinovich said. ``It has made me 
stronger, it's something I've had to overcome and move on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marinovich said returning to the NFL remains a goal, but a  
distant one. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now I'm on the one-day-at-a-time plan,'' he said.  
``We'll see down the line.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marinovich isn't the first high-profile former NFL quarterback  
to look to the CFL to resurrect a fledgling career. 
</P>
<P>
	Art Schlichter, selected fourth overall in 1982 by the Baltimore  
Colts, joined the Ottawa Rough Riders in 1988 after being suspended 
by the NFL when it was disclosed that bookies threatened him while 
attempting to collect more than $150,000 in gambling debts. 
</P>
<P>
	Schlichter played just eight games with Ottawa and later was  
sentenced to two years in federal prison on bank fraud charges. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
