<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Harnischfeger Seeks Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Harnischfeger Industries Inc., a manufacturer  
of mining and paper-making machinery, is seeking protection from 
its creditors in a Bankruptcy Court filing Monday and said it would 
stop paying interest on its debt. 
</P>
<P>
	The Milwaukee-based company had reported a loss last week and  
disclosed a management shakeup two weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The filing in federal court in Delaware, where Harnischfeger is  
incorporated, was under Chapter 11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code, 
which enables a company to continue operating while it attempts to 
reorganize its finances under the court's supervision. The filing 
covers Harnischfeger and its U.S.-based operating subsidiaries, Joy 
Mining Machinery, P&AMP;H Mining Equipment and Beloit Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said Monday that it will continue cost-cutting, but  
spokesman David Brukardt would not say if those initiatives 
includes eliminating more jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Just last week, in its quarterly financial report, Harnischfeger  
said it had exceeded its goal of reducing 3,100 positions from 
early 1998 to the end of 1999, cutting more than 3,400 by the end 
of the second quarter ended April 30. 
</P>
<P>
	Harnischfeger did not trade until the final half hour of  
Monday's session on the New York Stock Exchange, then plunged 55.6 
percent in a rising market by dropping $1.25 to close at $1 a share 
in heavy trading. The NYSE said it was reviewing the issue to see 
if the company still qualifies for listing. 
</P>
<P>
	John Nils Hanson, the company's new chief executive officer,  
said the company had been hurt by economic problems around the 
world. 
</P>
<P>
	Harnischfeger, which had a loss of $90.7 million in the six  
months ended April 30, has debts of approximately $1.3 billion. In 
its announcement Monday, Harnischfeger said it would stop interest 
payments on its debt. 
</P>
<P>
	In disclosing the filing, Harnischfeger said it has received  
commitments for $750 million in financing. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the company's view, staying out of Chapter 11, given the  
current conditions affecting the company and its highly leveraged 
capital structure, could well have led to a far worse situation and 
potentially a greater loss of value for creditors as well as equity 
holders,'' said Robert B. Hoffman, the company's new chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe this action will give us the ability to preserve  
the value of the company and begin the rebuilding process for the 
benefit of all of our constituencies. 
</P>
<P>
	Hanson, who had been serving as the company's president, chief  
operating officer and vice chairman, was named chief executive 
officer two weeks ago when Jeffrey T. Grade resigned. Hoffman, who 
had been an independent outside director, replaced Grade as 
chairman. Francis M. Corby, Jr. also resigned as executive vice 
president, finance and administration and chief financial officer 
at that time. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
