<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 09:00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Noon EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Milosevic Says He'll Carry Out Deal  
</P>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic  
insisted today that he still plans to carry out the peace agreement 
on Kosovo despite a breakdown in talks yesterday. A State 
Department spokesman says Milosevic gave assurances to the 
president of Finland by telephone and the Finnish leader has 
relayed it to Secretary of State Albright and other foreign 
ministers. Officials said the Finnish leader told Milosevic that 
NATO allies don't want to allow any gap between the time Serb 
forces leave Kosovo and the time international peacekeepers arrive. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Attacks Intensify  
</P>
<P>
	TABANOVCE, Macedonia (AP) -- NATO warplanes struck targets in  
Kosovo today in intensified airstrikes against Yugoslavia, after 
talks on implementing a Kosovo peace plan collapsed and left the 
entire settlement in question. NATO said its planes hit four Serb 
tanks, 20 artillery pieces and 17 armored personnel carriers in 
attacks over the previous 24 hours. Two waves of NATO jets attacked 
the Podujevo area, 20 miles north of the Kosovo capital of 
Pristina, the state-run Tanjug news agency reported. Tanjug said 
alliance aircraft launched more than 100 attacks on targets 
throughout Kosovo over the last 24 hours. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Won't Stop Canyon Flights  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court turned away an argument  
today by environmental groups hoping to end sightseeing flights 
over the Grand Canyon. The groups said the government has failed to 
meet the legally required deadlines for reducing such aircraft 
noise. The Federal Aviation Administration in 1996 issued a rule 
that created new flight-free zones, limited the hours flights could 
operate and limited the number of planes that could be used. But 
the environment groups said the government was acting too slowly to 
enforce the rules. 

</P>
<P>
	Congress To Get New Security Package  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration will send Congress  
this week a legislative package that would add $300 million to next 
year's spending on construction to improve security at overseas 
U.S. diplomatic missions. But Retired Adm. William Crowe, who 
headed State Department panels that studied embassy security, and 
some members of Congress denounced the funding, which is at $3 
billion over the next five years, as woefully inadequate. Bomb 
blasts at embassies in Nairobi, Kenya, and Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, 
last year prompted the systemwide survey of security facilities at 
missions abroad. 

</P>
<P>
	Belgium Food Scandal Spreads  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The dioxin food pollution scandal  
escalated today when authorities were forced to release the only 
suspects in the case and the government added butter to its list of 
banned foods. More nations, from Malaysia to the United States, 
banned meat and dairy products from Belgium and the entire 
15-nation European Union. Suspects Lucien and Jan Verkest, who run 
an animal feed-fat production company suspected of causing the 
cancer-causing dioxin pollution, were freed because of lack of 
evidence. Sales of Belgian poultry, eggs, fatty beef and pork have 
already been banned. 

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft Ships Office 2000  
</P>
<P>
	REDMOND, Wash. (AP) -- Microsoft began shipping its Microsoft  
Office 2000 today, a program that allows for easier conversion of 
PC documents from HTML, the Internet's basic document structure. 
Office 2000 is fully compatible with Office 97. Documents can also 
make a ``round trip'' into HTML and back again to the PC format, 
the software giant said. Office 2000 also targets small companies 
with its Small Business Tools package, offering programs for 
customer management, financial management, business planning and 
direct mail. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 51  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before noon EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 51.60 to 10,851.44. Advancing issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led decliners 1,353-1,229. The Nasdaq was up 25.78 to 
2,504.12. 

</P>
<P>
	Ron Low Quits As Oilers Coach  
</P>
<P>
	EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) -- Ron Low quit as coach of the Edmonton  
Oilers today after refusing an offer to return for another season 
at the same salary he earned in 1998-99. Low, 48, coached the 
Oilers for 4 1/2 seasons and was offered the same $325,000 he received 
last season, the newspaper reported. The Oilers barely made the 
playoffs this season, and were swept by the Dallas Stars. Low's 
final regular-season record is 139-162-40. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
