<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Signs Letter for Gore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After acknowledging concerns about the slow  
start of Al Gore's campaign, President Clinton lent a hand by 
signing a fund-raising letter mailed to 750,000 Democrats by the 
vice president's team. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's letter promoting Gore as his successor includes a  
swipe at unidentified ``powerful forces'' -- a clear reference to 
congressional Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	``They continue to resist change -- trying, over and over again,  
to return our country to the policies that have failed,'' Clinton 
wrote. ``They struggled against our economic plan. They shut the 
government down. And they tried to poison our country with 
partisanship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The letter is dated May 18 -- five days after The New York Times  
quoted the president as expressing concern about the start of 
Gore's presidential campaign but declaring it ``in a lot better 
shape now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has said he will formally endorse Gore once the vice  
president officially declares his candidacy. He is wading into an 
intraparty fight, since former Sen. Bill Bradley also is seeking 
the Democratic presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore campaign spokesman Roger Salazar said the fund-raising  
letter was just one indication of Clinton's willingness to help his 
vice president succeed him. 
</P>
<P>
	``The president has said many times that he is going to do  
everything he can to be helpful to the campaign,'' Salazar said. 
``We very much appreciate what he's doing here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the two-page letter, Clinton praises Gore's record on the  
economy, education and the environment. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have done my best to serve our country and build our bridge  
to the 21st century,'' Clinton wrote. ``When I think of Al Gore 
leading our nation, it gives me confidence that our progress can 
continue. ... I hope my strongest supporters will be in the 
vanguard of his efforts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During the three-month period ending March 31, the last date for  
which figures are available, Gore led all presidential hopefuls by 
raising $8.9 million. Second was Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who 
raised $7.6 million. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
