<HEADLINE> Heist Gets Attorney 8 Year Sentence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- An attorney convicted of laundering money  
stolen from an armored car company was sentenced Monday to eight 
years in prison and ordered to pay more than $1.1 million in 
restitution. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal jury in January found Jeffrey Guller, 56, guilty of  
money laundering and conspiracy to launder money for his role in 
the $17 million Loomis, Fargo &AMP; Co. heist. 
</P>
<P>
	Guller was convicted of helping his onetime client, Steven  
Chambers, launder the stolen money so Chambers could buy a $635,000 
house, knowing the money was obtained illegally. 
</P>
<P>
	Chambers, one of two ringleaders in the robbery scheme, was  
represented by Guller in closing the sale of the house. 
</P>
<P>
	Guller was the only one of 21 defendants to go on trial. All of  
the others pleaded guilty. Chambers was sentenced in April to 11 
years and three months in prison and ordered to pay more than $3.8 
million in restitution. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
