<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sara Lee Extends Offer To Coffee Co. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Shareholders representing the majority of coffee  
roaster Chock Full o'Nuts' shares have opted to tender their shares 
to Sara Lee, the food and consumer products maker said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Control of such shares could give Sara Lee officials more clout  
in their hostile takeover bid of New York-based Chock Full o'Nuts, 
said Jeff Kanter, a senior food analyst for Prudential Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	``It certainly takes it one step closer,'' Kanter said.  
</P>
<P>
	As of Monday, Sara Lee said 56 percent of Chock Full o'Nuts  
shares have been tendered. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chicago-based Sara Lee also said it has extended until June  
18 its cash tender offer to purchase all outstanding shares of the 
New York company's common stock for $10.50 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, Chock Full o'Nuts rejected a $225 million offer from  
Sara Lee, which seeks to expand its $2.8 billion-a-year coffee 
business. Sara Lee's Superior Coffee unit sells such brands as 
Superior, Douwe Egberts, Hillshire Farms, Continental, Metropolitan 
and Java Coast. 
</P>
<P>
	Chock Full o'Nuts, which has annual sales of $396.4 million,  
sells its own self-named brand of coffee, as well as others 
including Cain's LaTouraine. The coffee roaster also owns a chain 
of 40 drive-through coffee outlets called Quikava. 
</P>
<P>
	Kanter said acquiring Chock Full o'Nuts was not a ``make or  
break deal'' for Sara Lee. But he said the business fit well with 
Sara Lee's existing brands. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a good little business for Sara Lee,'' Kanter said.  
``That's about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sara Lee said discussions with Chock Full o'Nuts officials were  
continuing. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Chock Full o'Nuts rose 25 cents to $10.75 in trading  
on the New York Stock Exchange. Shares of Sara Lee slipped 6 1/4 cents 
to $24.56 1/4, also on the NYSE. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
