<HEADLINE> Griffey Leads AL All-Star Voting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Ken Griffey Jr. lead AL players in voting for  
next month's All-Star game in Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey leads outfielders with 473,436 votes, followed by Manny  
Ramirez (217,751) and Kenny Lofton (195,350) of the Cleveland 
Indians. Juan Gonzalez of Texas, the AL MVP, is fourth at 143,461. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey has started every All-Star game in the 1990s. He was the  
AL's leading vote-getter in 1991 and 1993 and led all players in 
1994, 1996, 1997 and 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other Indians lead their positions: first baseman Jim Thome  
(128,163) and second baseman Roberto Alomar (367,655). 
</P>
<P>
	Despite an injury-plagued season, Baltimore's Cal Ripken leads  
at third base (174,202) and is on track for his 17th consecutive 
All-Star start. 
</P>
<P>
	The closest race is at shortstop, where Derek Jeter of the World  
Series champion New York Yankees (154,051) leads Boston's Nomar 
Garciaparra (147,002), Seattle's Alex Rodriguez (94,214) and 
Cleveland's Omar Vizquel (86,046). 
</P>
<P>
	Ivan Rodriguez of Texas (317,471) leads at catcher, and Jose  
Canseco of Tampa Bay (248,343), who began the day with a major 
league-leading 21 homers, topped designated hitters. 
</P>
<P>
	The All-Star game is scheduled for July 13 at Boston's Fenway  
Park. Starters will be announced the week of July 5. 
</P>
<P>
	An update on NL totals will be released Tuesday.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
