<HEADLINE> Mets 8, Blue Jays 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Benny Agbayani hit two solo home runs, Mike  
Piazza homered for the second straight day and the New York Mets 
beat the Toronto Blue Jays 8-2 Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Orel Hershiser (5-5) earned his 195th career victory, giving the  
Mets their second win in a row following an eight-game losing 
streak. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Woodward, making his major league debut, drove in both  
runs for the Blue Jays. Toronto opened a six-game interleague trip 
after a 3-6 homestand. 
</P>
<P>
	The crowd of 21,457 was below the Mets' home average of 26,723.  
</P>
<P>
	Agbayani and Roger Cedeno, who had three hits and stole his  
major league-leading 31st base, each continued to be productive in 
place of slumping outfielders Rickey Henderson and Bobby Bonilla. 
</P>
<P>
	Rey Ordonez tripled and added a two-out, two-run single off  
Woodward's glove at shortstop in the seventh. That key hit came 
after a double steal by former Toronto star John Olerud and Piazza 
-- the first stolen base for each this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Agbayani, quickly becoming a fan favorite at Shea Stadium, hit a  
leadoff home run in the fourth that put the Mets ahead to stay at 
3-2. 
</P>
<P>
	Agbayani connected in the next inning, too, giving him eight  
homers in only 63 at-bats this season. The 27-year-old rookie is 
batting .429. 
</P>
<P>
	Piazza, whose homer off Roger Clemens spurred the Mets to a 7-2  
win at Yankee Stadium on Sunday night, hit his 11th home run to 
start the fifth against Roy Halladay (4-3). 
</P>
<P>
	Cedeno singled leading off the first and stole second. Edgardo  
Alfonzo hit an RBI double and later scored on Piazza's groundout. 
</P>
<P>
	Cedeno later singled and tripled, raising his average to .324.  
</P>
<P>
	Hershiser pitched six innings and gave up six hits, improving to  
6-2 against Toronto. He helped himself in other ways, hitting a 
sacrifice fly and also flawlessly fielding five groundballs. 
</P>
<P>
	Halladay allowed 11 hits in five innings. He made his first  
start since May 25 and pitched in place of Chris Carpenter, 
temporarily out because of inflammation in his right elbow. 
</P>
<P>
	Woodward was batting .322 at Triple-A Syracuse when he joined  
the Blue Jays before the game. He had a sacrifice fly in his first 
plate appearance and an RBI single in his first official at-bat. 
</P>
<P>
	Down 8-2, the Blue Jays loaded the bases with no outs in the  
eighth against Turk Wendell. But Jacob Brumfield and Woodward 
struck out and pinch-hitter Willie Greene grounded out. 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* Piazza and Toronto's Tony Fernandez each extended their  
hitting streaks to 12 games. ... Cedeno was caught stealing for the 
fifth time in the fourth. ... The Mets are 5-2 against Toronto in 
interleague play. ... Carpenter visited Dr. James Andrews in 
Birmingham, Ala., on Monday and was found to be OK. Manager Jim 
Fregosi said Carpenter may be able to pitch this weekend at 
Philadelphia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
