<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cisneros Trial Moved Back 2 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The trial of former Housing Secretary Henry  
Cisneros was postponed for two months Monday because of the 
presiding judge's concern over the difficulty of convening a pool 
of 300 potential jurors during the summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisneros was indicted in December 1997 on charges he lied to the  
FBI about $250,000 in payments he made to a former mistress after 
their affair ended. 
</P>
<P>
	Originally scheduled for July 6, the trial now is to begin in  
mid-September. At a hearing Monday, U.S. District Judge Stanley 
Sporkin set the start of jury selection for Sept. 7, with the trial 
expected to begin a week later. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, Cisneros' defense team filed a motion Monday seeking  
a psychiatric examination of the woman, Linda Jones, who has agreed 
to cooperate with the independent counsel prosecuting her former 
lover. 
</P>
<P>
	In requesting the exam, Cisneros lawyer Barry Simon cited both  
Ms. Jones' addiction to a prescription medication used to treat 
depression and a recent competency motion she filed. In it she 
denied she was competent when she pleaded guilty in January 1998 to 
multiple counts stemming from the Cisneros investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Jones, who previously went by her married name Medlar, is a  
major part of the government's case against Cisneros. Currently 
serving a 3 1/2-year prison sentence, she is due to testify at a 
hearing Sporkin has set for June 21 on the admissibility of tapes 
she secretly made during telephone conversations with Cisneros. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Jones' mental competency at the time she made the tapes,  
pleaded guilty and agreed to cooperate with Independent Counsel 
David Barrett's office is relevant, Simon said. ``She's been 
treated by, I don't know, six to eight doctors over the course of 
the years,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Mark Jackowski opposed the request. He noted a  
federal judge in Lubbock, Texas, where Ms. Jones was sentenced, 
rejected a motion she filed in March seeking to vacate her guilty 
plea on the ground that she was incompetent because of her 
prescription drug usage. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was found to be competent,'' Jackowski said. He added that  
a psychiatrist who has examined her during her incarceration ``has 
found no cognitive dysfunction or reduction in intelligence from 
use of this drug.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sporkin delayed further arguments on the psychiatric exam until  
the June 21 hearing, at which Ms. Jones is expected to testify for 
the government. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisneros served as housing secretary from 1993 to 1996 and heads  
the Spanish-language television network Univision. He has pleaded 
innocent to accusations that he vastly underreported his payments 
to Ms. Jones as well as lying about the timing of the payments. 
</P>
<P>
	Two longtime Cisneros aides, John Rosales and Sylvia  
Arce-Garcia, also are charged with conspiracy to conceal the 
financial arrangements from the FBI. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Jones, who still faces a similar conspiracy charge, may have  
an ally in the independent counsel's office. Barrett has indicated 
a willingness to support a reduced prison sentence for her based on 
her cooperation in Cisneros' trial. 
</P>
<P>
	The 49-year-old woman, who worked as a Cisneros fund-raiser  
while he was mayor of San Antonio, pleaded guilty to 28 counts 
involving fraud, conspiracy, money laundering and obstruction of 
the independent counsel's investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	The special prosecutor turned his attention to her after federal  
investigators discovered that she had lied about the taped 
conversations and that some of the tapes had been altered. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
