<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crashed Plane Cleared For Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- The twisted and charred chunks of an  
American Airlines jet were hauled Monday to a hangar where 
investigators plan to spend months analyzing what caused the crash 
that killed the pilot and eight passengers. 
</P>
<P>
	A salvage crew, working in the early morning dark, moved the  
pieces on a procession of four tarpaulin-covered flatbed trailers. 
</P>
<P>
	The jet had rested in soggy lowlands near the Arkansas River  
since June 1, when it skidded off a runway at the Little Rock 
airport during a storm, tore open and caught fire. 
</P>
<P>
	The airplane's pieces -- minus engines that were sent to Tulsa,  
Okla., for inspection -- could remain in the hangar for up to a 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	National Transportation Safety Board investigators have been  
focusing on whether mechanical problems, pilot error or severe 
weather -- or a combination of those factors -- played a role in the 
crash. 
</P>
<P>
	Placing the plane's pieces in a hangar should allow  
investigators to more closely study such things as the plane's 
onboard computers, which were buried under wreckage at the crash 
site. 
</P>
<P>
	The computers could disclose why the plane's spoilers -- panels  
that pop up to slow the plane down on landing -- did not open when 
the jet touched down. 
</P>
<P>
	The cockpit voice recorder tape has been transcribed and  
analyzed, but the text will not be released until more 
investigation is done, a high-level NTSB source said in Washington, 
speaking on condition of anonymity. The source said the flight-data 
recorder is also still being analyzed. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Associated Press Writer Glen Johnson contributed to this report  
from Washington. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
