<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Comic Book Writer Paul Newman Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBIA, Md. (AP) -- Paul S. Newman, who was so prolific a  
comic-book writer that he got listed in the Guinness Book of World 
Records, has died. He was 75. 
</P>
<P>
	The cause of Newman's death May 30 was a heart attack, according  
to Newman's son, Peter. 
</P>
<P>
	Newman wrote scripts for Superman, Mighty Mouse, The Lone Ranger  
and Jungle Jim comic books, among others. Beginning in 1947, he 
wrote more than 4,100 published stories totaling about 36,000 
pages, the equivalent of 120 mystery novels. His stories included 
dialogue and panel-by-panel descriptions of what the artist was 
supposed to draw. 
</P>
<P>
	``To get my 4,000-plus stories approved, I had to submit another  
5,000 plots that were not approved,'' he said. ``In the old days, 
you wrote a comic book for about $10 a page or about $300 an issue. 
I'm not a millionaire but I made a very good living.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1993, the comic-book historian Robin Snyder named Newman King  
of the Comic Book Writers. The Guinness book listed him as most 
prolific comic book writer under a headline, ``Lots of plots!'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also wrote a few newspaper comic strips, as well as  
screenplays and television sketches for such stars as Boris 
Karloff. 
</P>
<P>
	Newman was born in Manhattan in 1924 and enrolled at Dartmouth  
College. He served in World War II. He hoped to be a playwright, 
but he found he could make a living writing stories for comic 
books. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 07:31:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Knicks To Start Sprewell Vs. Pacers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Knicks are changing their starting  
lineup. The Indiana Pacers are changing their offensive focus. 
</P>
<P>
	Look for Latrell Sprewell and Reggie Miller to play much bigger  
roles tonight in Game 4 of the Eastern Conference finals. New York 
leads the best-of-7 series 2-1. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anything's a gamble right now,'' said New York coach Jeff Van  
Gundy, who announced Sunday that Sprewell would start alongside 
Allan Houston, Charlie Ward, Larry Johnson and Chris Dudley, with 
Kurt Thomas moving to the bench. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the way I think we can win the series,'' Van Gundy said.  
``We caught a miracle last night, we all know it. You need one if 
you're going to move on, but you can't rely on it. It was a great 
hang around, hang in there, hard-fought win. But looking back at 
it, we were dominated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Pacers, who got little offense from anyone other than Rik  
Smits in Game 3, will look for more production from Miller. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller has attempted 33 shots, including 11 3-pointers, and is  
shooting 42 percent. He attempted only nine shots in Game 3, and 
the Pacers were unable to get him the ball for the final shot in 
Games 1 and 3. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no question I've got to be more aggressive, I've got  
to shoot more -- 15 to 20, even 25 shots,'' Miller said. ``And I 
think that's going to be the case more in Game 4.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to getting Miller more shots, Bird says he plans to  
run more plays for Jalen Rose -- especially if Travis Best's groin 
pull keeps him out of the game and forces Rose, averaging 7.7 
points in the series, to be the backup point guard. Best said his 
status was 50-50. 
</P>
<P>
	The Knicks won Game 3 Saturday night when Larry Johnson made a  
rare four-point play with 5.7 seconds left for a 92-91 victory. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pacers were still upset with the ruling by official Jess  
Kersey on the play, saying the referee should have disallowed the 
shot since the whistle came at least a half-second before Johnson 
released the shot. But the Pacers also knew that they blew a chance 
to lock up the game by failing to score from the field over the 
final 3:20. 
</P>
<P>
	``No question a lot of breaks have gone New York's way, but  
we've given them a lot of breaks as well. A few of these games 
we've kind of handed it to them on a silver platter,'' Miller said. 
``We've played terrible the last three minutes of each and every 
game and were lucky to win one of them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Knicks, on the other hand, have played poorly in the first  
few minutes of each game. That was one of the reasons why Van Gundy 
has decided to start Sprewell. 
</P>
<P>
	Another concern is the potential for foul trouble with the  
Knicks' remaining big men in the absence of Patrick Ewing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't like that Kurt and (Chris) Dudley were out there  
together when they're both the primary defenders on (Rik) Smits,'' 
Van Gundy said, referring to the Pacers' 7-foot-4 center. 
``Secondly, I didn't like our second unit defense giving up 30 
points in the second quarter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Van Gundy started Dudley in place of Ewing in Game 3,  
Indiana used 6-7 Chris Mullin to guard the 6-11 Dudley. In Games 1 
and 2, New York had exploited the matchup of Mullin trying to guard 
the faster, stronger Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	``Instead of being able to go at Mullin, we couldn't. And so it  
really got us off to a bad start, and I think it would continue to 
get us off to a bad start,'' Van Gundy said. ``I know I would have 
made the change if the miracles wouldn't have happened last night, 
and miracles happening don't change what I think we need to do to 
win this series.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
