<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Goldman Sachs Woos Japan on TV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Stocks. Bonds. Actresses. Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co. is  
betting the combination on a new TV show the New York investment 
firm is sponsoring will encourage wary Japanese investors to buy 
mutual funds. 
</P>
<P>
	The show -- ``Money Angel'' -- debuts in the Tokyo area on June 26  
with Goldman Sachs as its sole sponsor. The program will feature 
three actresses who explain various types of investments. 
</P>
<P>
	The project, which Goldman says is the first of its kind, is  
aimed at overcoming one of the greatest roadblocks foreign 
securities companies face in Japan: traditional distrust of the 
stock market. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan would seem the perfect place for a mutual fund boom. The  
country has one of the world's highest savings rates, an aging 
population worried about nest eggs and low interest rates on 
savings accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	Those factors, however, have not made much of a dent in the view  
that investing in stocks is akin to gambling. The Tokyo market's 
loss of about half its value in the past decade has reinforced that 
belief. 
</P>
<P>
	But with deregulation throwing open the doors to foreign firms,  
brokerages are doing what they can to get a piece of the Japanese 
pie. Goldman has been the most successful: with more than $12 
billion in mutual fund assets, it is the No. 1 foreign mutual fund 
group in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Goldman sees the new program, broadcast on Saturdays on TV  
Tokyo, as a way of educating individual investors about the 
alternatives to squirreling away their money in low-yeilding 
savings accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	``Television is the most appropriate medium that can help  
(people to) understand the concept of `money' in a simple, yet 
comprehensive way,'' the firm said in a statement. ``This program 
will certainly help raise the awareness of asset management.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The show will also be accompanied by a new TV advertising  
campaign by Goldman that started on Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
