<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Racing Horse Put To Sleep </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLTS NECK, N.J. (AP) -- Niatross, harness racing's Horse of the  
Decade for the 1980s, was euthanized Monday evening after a large 
cancerous mass was discovered in his abdomen. 
</P>
<P>
	The 22-year-old stallion exhibited signs of discomfort on Friday  
and was transported to the veterinary center early Saturday morning 
where an examination revealed the large mass. After two days of 
monitoring and treatment, Niatross was put to sleep. 
</P>
<P>
	The breed's first sub-1:50 performer, Niatross was unbeaten in  
13 starts as a 2-year-old in 1979. His winnings that season of 
$604,900 were the most any 2-year-old of any breed had earned. He 
was voted Harness Horse of the Year in 1979, one of only three 
2-year-olds ever voted overall champion. 
</P>
<P>
	Bred by Elsie Berger of Niagara Acres and owned during that  
season by Berger and trainer-driver Clint Galbraith, 50 percent of 
Niatross was sold to the Niatross Stable for $5 million and insured 
for $20 million. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1980, Niatross won 24 of 26 starts, losing only when he fell  
over the rail at Saratoga and when he broke stride at the 
Meadowlands. He swept the Pacing Triple Crown and Meadowlands Pace, 
then put his name into the record books with a 1:49.1 time trial at 
Lexington's Red Mile. 
</P>
<P>
	Once again, he was named Horse of the Year. The New York Post  
named Niatross its 1980 Athlete of the Year, the only time a 
racehorse has won that newspaper's honor. 
</P>
<P>
	Niatross retired with earnings of $2,019,213, the first horse of  
any breed to earn over $2 million in only two racing seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	He began his stud career at Castleton Farm in Kentucky and sired  
Little Brown Jug winners from his first two crops, including 
Nihilator and Barberry Spur. He remained active as a stallion until 
a few days before his death. 
</P>
<P>
	Niatross sired 648 pacers with records of 2:00 or faster. To  
date, they have earned more than $57.3 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The stallion will be cremated and his remains interred at the  
Harness Racing Museum and Hall of Fame in Goshen, N.Y. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
