<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Slightly Higher / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Treasury prices edged higher Monday in light  
trading on the bond market as investors awaited key economic 
reports later this week. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 1/32  
point, or $0.31 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in 
the opposite direction, was at 5.96 percent, slightly below 
Friday's, which was the highest level since mid-May of last year. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the Labor Department is scheduled to report on  
producer price inflation and the Commerce Department is expected to 
release a report on retail sales. Strong increases in either could 
heighten fear of inflation and sway the Fed to raise interest 
rates. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market Monday, prices of short-term Treasury  
securities were between unchanged and up 1/32 point, and 
intermediate maturities were up 1/16 point, reported Bridge 
Telerate, a financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.61 percent as the  
discount was unchanged at 4.49 percent. Six-month yields were 4.95 
percent, as the discount was unchanged at 4.76 percent. One-year 
yields were 5.05 percent as the discount fell by 0.01 percentage 
point from late Friday to 4.80 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 4.75 percent from 4.63 percent late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 1/32 to 121 5/32. The average yield to 
maturity was unchanged at 5.42 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
