<DOCNO> APW19990607.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 09:00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 2 British Cigarette Companies Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- British American Tobacco PLC, the world's No. 2  
cigarette company and maker of brands including Kent and Lucky 
Strike, has completed a $8.2 billion acquisition of its smaller 
rival, Rothmans International NV. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal has cleared its final regulatory hurdle -- approval by  
Australia's Securities and Investments Commission -- BAT spokeswoman 
Denise Hart said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	BAT's purchase of Rothmans depended on the commission's approval  
of the merger of their two subsidiaries in Australia. A second 
Australian government agency, the Competition and Consumer 
Commission, signed off on the deal last Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition gives British American a 16 percent share of the  
global cigarette market, just behind Philip Morris Cos., which has 
17 percent. BAT bought Rothmans, the world's fourth-biggest 
cigarette producer, in exchange for a special issue of 604 million 
ordinary shares and 242 million preference shares. 
</P>
<P>
	Rothmans International is owned by Switzerland's Compagnie  
Financiere Richemont and South Africa-based Rembrandt Group. They 
now own a combined 35 percent of the enlarged BAT. 
</P>
<P>
	The two companies announced their planned merger in January.  


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
