<DOCNO> APW19990607.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 12:00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `Death in Venice' Is No.1 Gay Novel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Contributing yet another end-of-the-century  
list, an organization of gays in publishing has compiled the 100 
greatest gay novels of all time, with Thomas Mann's ``Death in 
Venice'' coming in at No. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	The novella about a writer's infatuation with a teen-age boy was  
followed by James Baldwin's ``Giovanni's Room,'' the story of an 
expatriate's struggle with his sexual identity, and ``Our Lady of 
the Flowers,'' Jean Genet's fantasy about a male prostitute in the 
Parisian underworld. 
</P>
<P>
	Two classic French novels finished fourth and fifth: Marcel  
Proust's ``Remembrance of Things Past'' and Andre Gide's ``The 
Immoralist.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The list was compiled by Publishing Triangle, which consists of  
more than 250 gay and lesbian writers, editors, agents and 
publishers. 
</P>
<P>
	The criteria for what constitutes a ``gay novel'' were hazy.  
Titles apparently could make the list if the author was gay, if the 
book had gay subject matter, or the text was simply open to gay 
interpretation. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, the judges disagreed, for instance, over the  
inclusion of Herman Melville's ``Moby-Dick.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Each of these books contributes to the understanding of the  
outsider mentality,'' said one of the judges, novelist Dorothy 
Allison, whose own ``Bastard Out of Carolina'' made the list. 
``'Moby-Dick' is very much about the survival of the different. And 
that's pretty much the situation for gay and lesbian people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``You could say that about a leper colony, too,'' countered  
fellow judge M.E. Kerr, a novelist. ``You have to consider the 
writer's intention. If you're supposed to choose a gay novel, I 
should think that it's not just because it has a group of men or 
women interacting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The exercise was a response to the Modern Library's list last  
summer of the century's best English-language novels. That list was 
widely criticized as a stodgy compilation of white male literature. 
The Modern Library is a division of Random House. 
</P>
<P>
	``That list got me thinking about what novels by gays and  
lesbians were overlooked,'' said Charles Flowers, chairman of the 
Publishing Triangle. 
</P>
<P>
	The Publishing Trangle list covers the best novels ever, not  
just those of the 20th century. There are far more women and 
nonwhites, and all languages were eligible. 
</P>
<P>
	Fourteen judges were on the Publishing Triangle selection  
committee, among them John Loughery, art critic for The Hudson 
Review, and Anthony Heilbut, author of a prize-winning biography of 
Mann. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Modern Library could be faulted for disregarding  
alternative voices, the current list could be cited for excessive 
loyalty to those voices. 
</P>
<P>
	Few critics, for instance, would call ``Giovanni's Room'' a  
better novel than ``Remembrance of Things Past'' or rank Patricia 
Highsmith's ``The Price of Salt'' (No. 36) above ``The Turn of the 
Screw'' by Henry James (No. 40) and Louisa May Alcott's ``Little 
Women.'' (No. 43). 
</P>
<P>
	``Many elements went into the voting,'' Flowers said. ``Social  
influence. Cultural influence. Literary quality. I don't believe 
there's a single objective standard.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 14:35:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Study of Mentally Ill Proposed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- At a White House conference on mental illness,  
President Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and their wives worked 
today to dispel myths about people who suffer from such illnesses 
as depression and schizophrenia. 
</P>
<P>
	``Americans with mental illness should have the same opportunity  
all Americans have to live to the fullest of their God-given 
abilities,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House used the gathering to announce a $7.3 million  
study by the National Institute of Mental Health to explore mental 
illness and a national training program for teachers to identify 
and help troubled children. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also notified the 285 health plans used by federal  
employees that they must cover mental illness and substance abuse, 
and he called on other employers to do the same. ``It is high time 
that our health plans treat all Americans equally,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Additionally, the administration was pressing Congress for  
legislation to stop forcing disabled people who are receiving 
Medicare or Medicaid to give up their benefits when they go to 
work. 
</P>
<P>
	The training program was developed with the help of the National  
Education Association and EchoStar, a satellite company based in 
Littleton, Colo., where two students killed a teacher, 12 
classmates and themselves earlier this year. EchoStar was donating 
1,000 satellite dishes and 40 hours of air time to the venture. 
</P>
<P>
	But more than changing policy, the conference was aimed at  
changing attitudes. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton drew parallels between the stigma surrounding mental  
illness and discrimination, saying the mentally disabled ``are 
perhaps just the latest in our enduring challenge as a people to 
continue the work of our founders to widen the circle of 
opportunity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tipper Gore, the vice president's wife, recounted for the  
audience at Howard University and listening nationwide how she 
sought treatment to overcome depression after her son was injured 
by a car. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want people that are within the sound of my voice, who  
perhaps are suffering with this or any other mental illness, to 
know that there is the right diagnosis and the right treatment and 
the right health care professional out there for you,'' she said. 
``Don't hold back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gore, a longtime advocate for the mentally ill, chaired the  
conference, which was linked electronically to 6,000 sites 
nationwide. CBS newsman Mike Wallace, who also overcame depression, 
joined the discussion. 
</P>
<P>
	Five Cabinet secretaries and more than 20 members of Congress  
from both parties were participating in the daylong session. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gore is working with Surgeon General David Satcher and the  
Ad Council to produce the campaign on mental illness. Clinton 
issued an executive order Friday to eliminate the government's 
stricter hiring and promotion standards for mentally disabled 
people. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 14:35:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Study of Mentally Ill Proposed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- At a White House conference on mental illness,  
President Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and their wives worked 
today to dispel myths about people who suffer from such illnesses 
as depression and schizophrenia. 
</P>
<P>
	``Americans with mental illness should have the same opportunity  
all Americans have to live to the fullest of their God-given 
abilities,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House used the gathering to announce a $7.3 million  
study by the National Institute of Mental Health to explore mental 
illness and a national training program for teachers to identify 
and help troubled children. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also notified the 285 health plans used by federal  
employees that they must cover mental illness and substance abuse, 
and he called on other employers to do the same. ``It is high time 
that our health plans treat all Americans equally,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Additionally, the administration was pressing Congress for  
legislation to stop forcing disabled people who are receiving 
Medicare or Medicaid to give up their benefits when they go to 
work. 
</P>
<P>
	The training program was developed with the help of the National  
Education Association and EchoStar, a satellite company based in 
Littleton, Colo., where two students killed a teacher, 12 
classmates and themselves earlier this year. EchoStar was donating 
1,000 satellite dishes and 40 hours of air time to the venture. 
</P>
<P>
	But more than changing policy, the conference was aimed at  
changing attitudes. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton drew parallels between the stigma surrounding mental  
illness and discrimination, saying the mentally disabled ``are 
perhaps just the latest in our enduring challenge as a people to 
continue the work of our founders to widen the circle of 
opportunity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tipper Gore, the vice president's wife, recounted for the  
audience at Howard University and listening nationwide how she 
sought treatment to overcome depression after her son was injured 
by a car. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want people that are within the sound of my voice, who  
perhaps are suffering with this or any other mental illness, to 
know that there is the right diagnosis and the right treatment and 
the right health care professional out there for you,'' she said. 
``Don't hold back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gore, a longtime advocate for the mentally ill, chaired the  
conference, which was linked electronically to 6,000 sites 
nationwide. CBS newsman Mike Wallace, who also overcame depression, 
joined the discussion. 
</P>
<P>
	Five Cabinet secretaries and more than 20 members of Congress  
from both parties were participating in the daylong session. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gore is working with Surgeon General David Satcher and the  
Ad Council to produce the campaign on mental illness. Clinton 
issued an executive order Friday to eliminate the government's 
stricter hiring and promotion standards for mentally disabled 
people. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
