<DOCNO> APW19990607.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 07:36:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Supreme Court Denies Overtime Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- About 14,000 current and former federal law  
enforcement officers who say they improperly were denied overtime 
pay lost a Supreme Court appeal today. 
</P>
<P>
	The court, without comment, turned away the officers' effort to  
collect another four years' worth of overtime pay in addition to 
two years of pay they were granted in a settlement. Today's action, 
however, leaves open part of the officers' claim. 
</P>
<P>
	The 14,122 officers worked between 1984 and 1995 as criminal  
investigators or in other law enforcement positions for agencies 
including the Customs Service, the Secret Service, the Internal 
Revenue Service and the Drug Enforcement Administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Their lawsuits, filed between 1990 and 1995, said they wrongly  
were classified as exempt from federal overtime pay requirements, 
and sought back pay. The employees also filed administrative claims 
with the Government Accounting Office. 
</P>
<P>
	The Court of Federal Claims ruled for the officers, and in a  
1994 settlement they were granted two years' worth of back overtime 
pay. 
</P>
<P>
	The officers' claims with the GAO sought an additional four  
years' overtime under a federal policy that allowed six years' 
worth of compensation in administrative claims. But in 1994, the 
GAO ruled that such administrative claims would be limited to two 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Later in 1994, Congress passed a law intended to allow six  
years' worth of compensation, but changed the law the following 
year to ensure it would not apply to the officers. One congressman 
said the 1994 law would have cost the government up to $460 million 
in back pay. 
</P>
<P>
	In late 1995, the officers asked a federal judge to let them  
seek the additional four years' pay. The judge ruled against them, 
and the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia 
upheld that ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	But the appeals court said the officers' claim that the policy  
change unlawfully took their property without compensation might 
have to be decided by a different court. The federal judge was 
ordered to restudy that issue. 
</P>
<P>
	The appeal acted on today said the government violated the  
officers' due-process rights in trying to ``avoid paying legitimate 
debts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Justice Department lawyers said the GAO is entitled to change  
its mind on how much back pay could be awarded to government 
workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Adams vs. Hinchman, 98-1265.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0190 </DOCNO>
