<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Stocks Push Ahead; Dow Up 92.45 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose broadly today as corporate mergers  
helped distract investors from lingering concerns about inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 92.45 at 10,892.29. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's  
500 index was up 5.73 at 1,333.48, and the Nasdaq composite index 
was up 45.23 at 2,523.57. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume was light as traders already began looking ahead to  
Friday, when the government's producer price index is expected to 
offer signals about inflation and perhaps an indication of whether 
the Federal Reserve will raise interest rates to keep the economy 
from overheating. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks have slipped in the weeks since the Fed warned it might  
raise rates, and volume has been lower than normal as Wall Street 
weighs the impact of a possible increase. But prices have turned 
around in recent sessions, and on Friday, the Dow made one of its 
strongest rallies in weeks, gaining 136.15 to close at 10,799.84. 
</P>
<P>
	Major corporate mergers stimulated trading today. AlliedSignal  
rose 5 1/16 to 63 7/16 and Honeywell rose 8 1/2 to 113 1/2 after the 
companies announced they will merge, creating an aerospace 
parts-and-electronics conglomerate. AlliedSignal, a component of 
the Dow, was a major contributor to the index's gains. 
</P>
<P>
	A pair of Salt Lake City banks, First Security Corp. and Zions  
Bancorp, will merge in a deal worth $5.9 billion. First Security 
rose 5 1/4 to 23 7/8, and Zions fell 8 1/8 to 57 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	American Express rose 2 9/16 to 127 13/16 after Prudential  
Securities raised its rating on the stock. Prudential cited rising 
credit card use in the United States and overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM, which saw its price slump last month, rose 4 to 120 today.  
A J.P. Morgan analyst said IBM's stock could reach 150 within 12 
months, citing strong sales of its electronic business software. 
</P>
<P>
	The broad base of good corporate news heartened Wall Street.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's one of those sessions where all is right with the  
world,'' said Ned Collins, a trader at Daiwa Securities America. 
</P>
<P>
	But airline stocks couldn't keep up with the market's rally  
today. UAL Corp., the parent of United Air Lines, warned analysts 
late Friday that its second-quarter earnings will fall below well 
estimates. Its shares fell 1 11/16 to 64 1/8, and weighed down several 
other airlines. 
</P>
<P>
		   Advancers outnumbered decliners by an 8-to-7 margin on the New  
York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 512.0 million shares, 
well behind Friday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index rose 1.70 to 636.22, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index was down 5.54 at 775.44. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
