<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Driving Through Poland Is Difficult </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SOCHACZEW, Poland (AP) -- For 22 years, Piotr Deja has driven  
trucks over the mostly two-lane, never-divided road that bisects 
Poland from Belarus in the east to Germany in the west. He knows 
every turn, every pothole. 
</P>
<P>
	The bypass around the western city of Poznan is ``so  
pothole-ridden that axles and suspensions get broken,'' the 
weathered 45-year-old complained, sitting in the Warsaw office of 
his Bielmagistral transport company. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten Bielmagistral trucks broke down last year, most of them on  
that rutted stretch, he said with a sigh. 
</P>
<P>
	Rough roads aren't the only problems for Poland's truckers.  
</P>
<P>
	It takes at least half an hour to travel through Sochaczew, a  
town of 5,000 people about 30 miles west of Warsaw that has three 
traffic lights along a 1,000-foot stretch, Deja said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Driving through Poland is like breaking stones,'' he concluded  
with a broad-shouldered shrug. 
</P>
<P>
	A decade after communist rule ended and Poland embarked on  
market reforms, it enjoys steady economic growth that has attracted 
tens of billions of dollars in foreign investment. 
</P>
<P>
	But the economic success has created a paradoxical transport  
situation -- the more wealth created and investment attracted, the 
more traffic on an already overloaded road system. 
</P>
<P>
	With only 160 miles of modern highways, road transport means  
losses for businesses that must get goods from Baltic ports inland 
or from factories to retailers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Investors point more to roads in Poland (as a problem) than in  
other east European countries,'' said William Crisp, senior vice 
president at the Economist Intelligence Unit. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the early 1990s, telecommunications were seen as a great  
limitation for business, but that has been generally overcome by 
lots of investment,'' Crisp said. ``Now, lack of roads is going to 
be the same kind of limitation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many businessmen limit car trips as much as possible, choosing  
to go by train or plane instead, said Krzysztof Klapa, a spokesman 
for the McDonald's hamburger chain in Poland. 
</P>
<P>
	``When somebody is told to drive to Poznan, he is terrified. It  
is like risking your life,'' Klapa said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stanley Urban, financial director at Thomson Polkolor, Poland's  
sixth biggest exporter to the European Union, has complained to 
Prime Minister Jerzy Buzek about the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of the rough roads, Thomson Polkolor now uses sturdy  
plastic packaging -- instead of the foam popular in Western 
countries -- to protect its products during transport from the 
factory in Piaseczno, outside Warsaw. Last year, almost 5,000 
cathode ray tubes were damaged during shipment. 
</P>
<P>
	``What counts is the opinion about the product,'' Urban said.  
``Our customers had objections.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The problem appears unsolvable, at least in the near future.  
</P>
<P>
	According to the Transport Ministry, 37 percent of Poland's  
roads need immediate repair and an additional 42 percent require 
work within three years. Improving the roads to European Union 
standards would cost the equivalent of $23 billion, or roughly 60 
percent of this year's national budget. 
</P>
<P>
	Police spokesman Marek Fitos said 5,400 miles of Poland's main  
roads -- 25 percent of the total -- have ruts more than two-thirds of 
an inch deep, which is considered dangerous for traffic. The 
problem comes from heavy trucks that grind down asphalt constructed 
for lighter vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	Fitos blamed poor roads as a factor in 30 percent of crashes.  
The Transport Ministry noted vehicle accidents in 1997 caused 
losses worth 7 percent of the country's gross domestic product, 
more than three times the 2 percent threshold recommended by the 
World Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Poor lighting, few sidewalks and a lack of bypasses around small  
towns also cause a disproportionate number of pedestrian deaths -- 
about half Poland's 7,500 total traffic fatalities in 1998, Fitos 
said. The European Union average is 15 percent to 20 percent, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Compounding the problem is increased traffic.  
</P>
<P>
	Obstacles to owning a car during the communist years -- poverty,  
shortages, bureaucratic wrangling -- have diminished. Over the past 
decade, foreign automakers flooded the formerly closed market and 
increased the number of Polish-registered cars by 50 percent to 
13.5 million -- a number the communists had not expected to reach 
until the second decade of the 21st century. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, more cars carrying foreign visitors are  
driving across Poland's borders -- 27 million last year, almost 
triple the number from the early 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	Grzegorz Bielowicki, head of the U.S. company Euroad that is  
Poland's biggest private transport business, said the traffic and 
poor roads mean Euroad trucks average 28 mph in Poland compared to 
50 mph in neighboring Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	Compared to Germany, he said, ``we need 50 percent more trucks  
to do the same number of orders.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
