<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Free Voice Mail Service on Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- People juggling a flood of messages  
pouring in from e-mail, answering machines, and pagers can now 
organize the calls with free services offered through the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	San Mateo-based Onebox.com announced its services Monday,  
joining a growing list of companies offering free communications on 
the Web. 
</P>
<P>
	Onebox.com touted itself as the first to combine voice mail, fax  
and e-mail. 
</P>
<P>
	Users get a free, personal local telephone number and e-mail  
address. Anyone who calls the telephone number can leave voice 
mails and faxes. Users can then instantly retrieve those messages 
over the phone or log on to a Web site, where they can click on 
audio files that will play the voicemail message. 
</P>
<P>
	Onebox.com is introducing the service later this month in the  
New York area, northern California and Austin, Texas with plans to 
expand later. 
</P>
<P>
	``Onebox.com is the one way to bring your life together. The one  
place to manage all your communications,'' said CEO Ross Bott. 
</P>
<P>
	Bott has brought in more than $20 million in private investments  
for Onebox.com, including the venture capital firms IVP and 
Brentwood Venture Capital, and ZDNet, a technology news Internet 
site. 
</P>
<P>
	``Giving away free stuff has a lot to do with the culture of the  
Internet,'' said Alan Alper, an analyst at Gomez Advisors, a market 
research firm in Concord, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	``It started as a place to share information for free. Now the  
businesses are giving consumers something and in return, they hope, 
they're getting something back more valuable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That return is threefold: revenue from advertising, information  
on the customer for future marketing purposes, and establishing a 
relationship with customers who may be willing to pay for new 
services later. 
</P>
<P>
	Among Onebox.com's competitors, Telebot, which launched in  
February, has 35,000 users. eFax.com, which also launched in 
February, has signed over 600,000 users taking advantage of the 
free fax-to-email service. 
</P>
<P>
	Hotmail, a free e-mail service launched in 1996 and now owned by  
Microsoft, is the world's largest e-mail service, with more than 40 
million active members. 
</P>
<P>
	Hotmail member Jay Schorr of Miami, Fla., said he didn't see any  
reason to pay for e-mail elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hotmail has everything I need in one place. It's fast,  
reliable and free,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
