<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 18:06:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  NASCAR Matriarch Hawkins Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) -- Eloise Hawkins, chairman and chief  
executive of the authority which ran stock-car races at Bowman Gray 
Stadium, died Monday after a battle with cancer. She was 82. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1970, Hawkins was head of the Winston-Salem Speedway,  
Inc., which conducts NASCAR-sanctioned stock-car racing at the 
municipal stadium under a lease from the city. She remained active 
in its operation until the illness struck her earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Hawkins was born Sept. 1, 1916, in Spartanburg County, S.C., and  
was one of 11 children. She entered the auto racing industry when 
she married J. Alvin Hawkins, who co-founded the stadium's racing 
in 1949 in a partnership with NASCAR founder William France. 
</P>
<P>
	France withdrew from the enterprise in the 1960s and Hawkins  
became the stadium's racing chief after her husband died in 1970. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include five daughters, 16 grandchildren and 12  
great-grandchildren. 
</P>
<P>
	Funeral services will be held at 11 a.m. at the Hayworth-Miller  
Funeral Home. Memorials may be made to West Side Baptist Church in 
Winston-Salem. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 07:20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Miller, Hagen Honored at Tonys </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Both playwright Arthur Miller and actress Uta  
Hagen spoke eloquently and passionately about theater when they 
received Tony Awards for lifetime achievement in the theater. 
</P>
<P>
	Hagen, who received her Tony in the Gershwin Theater before the  
television cameras rolled Sunday, exclaimed, ``What a wonderful 
80th birthday present.'' She made her Broadway debut in 1938 in 
``The Seagull.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She thanked her mentors, the Lunt family, actress Eva Le  
Gallienne, director Harold Clurman and her late actor-teacher 
husband, Herbert Berghof, ``for never letting me forget it was my 
destiny to answer my calling to a noble art, the theater, the 
stage. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's sad to think our destinies are now ruled by economics,''  
she said. ``I want to throw out a battle cry to those who think as 
I do -- that this transcendental art will become insignificant only 
as we allow it to do so.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hagen, who acted this season off-Broadway in ``Collected  
Stories,'' said, ``I'm not going to be embalmed by this award. I 
will stay young, in my passionate fight to do the work the way I 
think it should be done, to be of service to the community, to 
provide food for the soul.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, 83, whose ``Death of a Salesman'' won the Tony Award for  
best revival Sunday, 50 years after it won as best new play on 
Broadway, had his first play produced at the University of Michigan 
in 1934. His latest play, ``Mr. Peters' Connections,'' was 
presented off-Broadway last season. 
</P>
<P>
	He said, ``Thank you for this honor. Just being around to  
receive it is a great pleasure. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to share a hope with you that I have nursed for a  
long time.'' Mentioning Eugene O'Neill's ``The Iceman Cometh,'' 
which also is running on Broadway now, Miller said that if such 
plays, long and with big casts, arrived at producers' desks now, 
``they would be unlikely to end up on a Broadway stage. The 
Broadway economy would make them too expensive and risky to be 
presented. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope that a new dimension and fresh resolve will inspire the  
powers that be to welcome fiercely ambitious playwrights. And that 
the time will come again when they will find a welcome for their 
big, world-challenging plays, somewhere west of London and 
somewhere east of the Hudson River.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
