<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oakland Designates Candiotti </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Tom Candiotti, a knuckleball pitcher who  
has won 150 games in a 16-year major league career, was designated 
for assignment today by the Oakland Athletics. 
</P>
<P>
	The A's have 10 days to trade Candiotti, release him or assign  
him to the minor leagues. Oakland general manager Billy Beane said 
he thinks Candiotti will end up with another major league team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe there may be some interest,'' Beane said. ``I  
believe Tom will be pitching in the major leagues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Candiotti was 3-5 this season with a 6.35 ERA in 11 starts. Over  
his last seven starts, he was 1-3 with a 7.53 ERA. 
</P>
<P>
	Candiott signed a two-year deal with the A's before the 1998  
season. He went 11-16 last season, leading the club in losses. 
</P>
<P>
	``He really meant a lot to this organization,'' Beane said. ``He  
was a class act on and off the field. That's why this is 
difficult.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Oakland Athletics called up pitcher Tim Hudson to fill  
Candiotti's spot on the roster. Hudson will make his major league 
debut on Tuesday as the A's starter against San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
	Candiotti, who had his 150th career victory on May 28 against  
Baltimore, has played for Milwaukee, Cleveland, Toronto, Los 
Angeles and Oakland. He has a career record of 150-163. 
</P>
<P>
	The A's made the move more because of Hudson's performance than  
Candiotti's, Beane said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Tim Hudson, if anything, led to this,'' Beane said.  
``He's pitched so well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After his promotion to Triple-A Vancouver on April 24, Hudson  
was 4-0 with a 2.20 ERA in eight starts. Prior to that, he was 3-0 
with a 0.50 ERA in three starts for Double-A Midland. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
