<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 15:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tony Telecast Drops Musical Number </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- ``It Ain't Nothin' But the Blues'' is singing  
the blues over its treatment on the 1999 Tony Awards telecast. 
</P>
<P>
	A four-minute production number from the Tony-nominated musical  
was dropped from the telecast when the Sunday night television show 
threatened to go longer than the two hours allotted by CBS. 
</P>
<P>
	Television exposure is one of the perks for the nominated  
musicals. It gets their productions in front of a national audience 
of potential ticket buyers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't register anywhere on the radar of what is playing on  
Broadway,'' James Morrison, a spokesman for ``Blues,'' said Monday. 
``It is quite hurtful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The telecast's overnight ratings were hardly blockbuster.  
Preliminary figures indicate a drop of 24 percent, down to a 7.9 
rating and a 13 share, compared with a 10.3 and a 16 share last 
year, when Rosie O'Donnell was the host, said Tony spokesman Keith 
Sherman. This year's telecast had a succession of hosts. 
</P>
<P>
	``Blues'' producer Eric Krebs said he has hired a lawyer to  
advise him on a course of action, but added, ``The Tony management 
committee has been responsive to exploring various options for 
rectifying the damage to our show.'' He did not elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	Tony Award Productions, which produced the television show,  
issued a statement saying it regretted the exclusion of ``It Ain't 
Nothin' But the Blues,'' but added that many ``cuts were made 
throughout the telecast.'' All of the cut material ``fell prey to 
one of the inherent perils of live television.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Blues'' was nominated for four Tonys, including best musical,  
but didn't win any. 
</P>
<P>
	The three other nominated musicals -- ``Parade,'' ``The Civil  
War'' and the Tony winner, ``Fosse'' -- put on production numbers, 
as did the four nominees for best musical revival. The decision to 
cut ``Blues'' was not mentioned on the air. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike the Oscars, which run longer and longer every year, the  
CBS portion of the Tony Awards operates under a strict two-hour 
time limit. Another hour, preceding the CBS telecast, is seen on 
public television. 
</P>
<P>
	The elimination of scenes from nominated musicals has happened  
only once before. In 1995, a segment from ``Smokey Joe's Cafe'' was 
cut from the Tony show, but a number from that revue also opened 
the evening, so the musical was still represented on the television 
program. 
</P>
<P>
	``Blues'' cast members were philosophical about their omission  
from the Tony show. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to go out on stage again tomorrow night and sing  
the blues and it will be a little more bluesy this week,'' said Ron 
Taylor, who also co-created the revue. ``But we will recover.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The number deleted from the telecast was a bitter anthem of  
exclusion called ``Members Only.'' The lyrics include: ``It's 
members only. It's a private party. Don't need no money to qualify. 
Don't bring your checkbook. Bring your broken heart. It's members 
only tonight.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0227 </DOCNO>
