<HEADLINE> 3 Die in Church Group Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLOVERDALE, Calif. (AP) -- With tears streaming down their faces,  
members of a church group held hands and prayed on the edge of a 
highway following a crash that claimed three of their number. 
</P>
<P>
	About 50 members of Redwood City-based Templo La Luz were  
traveling south on U.S. Highway 101 near Cloverdale on Sunday when 
the van, carrying 13 people, blew its left rear tire. 
</P>
<P>
	The driver, Perfecto Rodriguez, 37, lost control of the van and  
it plunged 50 feet down an embankment, the California Highway 
Patrol said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I heard groaning, people calling out for God, saying, 'Lord,  
help us!''' said Rudy Zamora, who was enjoying a picnic on the 
Russian River when the sound of crashing metal echoed through the 
canyon. 
</P>
<P>
	A Menlo Park man was pronounced dead at the scene, and a  
12-year-old boy, also of Menlo Park, died later at Sutter Medical 
Center in Santa Rosa, officials said. Their identities were 
withheld until relatives could be notified. 
</P>
<P>
	The third victim, Faustino Castenada, 40, died today at Sutter  
Medical Center, said nursing supervisor Dwayne Stincelli. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten others were injured, one critically.  
</P>
<P>
	The group goes to Lake Mendocino every year for a retreat.  
Members spent the weekend studying the Bible, singing, playing 
soccer, horseshoes and volleyball, and swimming. 
</P>
<P>
	The afternoon accident closed the state's main coastal highway  
in both directions for an hour. Cloverdale is about 80 miles 
northwest of San Francisco. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
