<DOCNO> APW19990607.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 17:40:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Money Approved To Identify Missing Persons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House on Monday approved spending of $6  
million over the next three years to help states and the FBI in 
searches of missing persons. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation, passed 370-4, would cover state costs of  
entering profiles of unidentified persons in a nationwide FBI file 
so that the FBI can cross-reference that information with its 
missing persons file. 
</P>
<P>
	``Without this funding, thousands of families will be deprived  
of a chance of closure,'' said Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y., sponsor of 
the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI created a missing persons file within its National Crime  
Information Center in 1975, and eight years later established an 
unidentified persons file. 
</P>
<P>
	But matching the information from the two files is not always  
possible because states are not required by law to report 
unidentified bodies to the FBI. 
</P>
<P>
	Lazio named the bill ``Jennifer's Law'' after a 21-year-old  
woman in his Long Island district, Jennifer Wilmer, who disappeared 
in 1993 while living in California. The bill now moves to the 
Senate for consideration. 
</P>
<P>
	The House on Monday also passed and sent to the White House a  
trade bill that, among other provisions, suspends duties on certain 
imported pharmaceutical products used for AIDS and cancer drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Jerry Weller, R-Ill., said the legislation, already  
approved by the Senate, could significantly reduce the costs of 
some AIDS and cancer drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, passed 375-1, also extends permanent normal trade  
relation status to Mongolia and gives duty-free treatment to 
individuals associated with the 1999 Special Olympics, the 1999 
Women's World Cup, the 2001 International Special Olympics, the 
2002 Salt Lake City Winter Olympics and the 2002 Winter 
Para-Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	---	 
</P>
<P>
	The missing persons bill is H.R. 1915.  
</P>
<P>
	The trade bill is H.R. 435.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
