<HEADLINE> Paula Jones' Husband Wants Divorce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Paula Jones' husband has filed for divorce,  
citing irreconcilable differences with the woman who accused 
President Clinton of sexual harassment. 
</P>
<P>
	In Monday's filing, Stephen Jones also asks for joint legal and  
physical custody and joint visitation of the couple's sons, 
Stephen, 6, and Preston, 2. 
</P>
<P>
	The couple separated in February, and the boys currently live  
with their mother in Cabot, Ark., according to the filing in Los 
Angeles Superior Court. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Jones acknowledged in March that she and her husband were  
living apart but said they would be reunited in Arkansas and their 
marriage wasn't in jeopardy. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is now,'' said Susan Carpenter-McMillan, Mrs. Jones' friend  
and former advisor. Carpenter-McMillan declined to elaborate, 
adding only that ``at this time, the boys will remain with her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The couple, who married in 1991, disagreed over strategy in her  
now-settled sexual harassment lawsuit against Clinton, Mrs. Jones 
has said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Jones and Clinton reached an out-of-court settlement of  
$850,000 in November on her claim that Clinton made an improper 
sexual advance to her in a Little Rock hotel room in 1991. Her 
share of the money came to $201,000, with the rest going to 
lawyers. 
</P>
<P>
	A message left with Stephen Jones' lawyer, Lee Salisbury, was  
not returned. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
