<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Members To Help Poorer Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- The Netherlands said today that it and other  
European countries are spearheading efforts to create an 
independent center to give poorer countries the clout to defend 
their interests in disputes before the World Trade Organization. 
</P>
<P>
	The Advisory Center for WTO Law will provide legal advice on  
trade law to least-developed and developing countries at a much 
lower cost than the usual commercial rates. 
</P>
<P>
	``For developing countries this really constitutes a very  
important step in order to be able to exercise our rights and 
obligations in this organization,'' Colombian trade Ambassador 
Nestor Ossorio told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	The center would be entirely independent of the WTO and would  
employ lawyers to help countries take cases through the 
organization's dispute settlement procedure. It would also provide 
training and intern schemes to help give countries the expertise to 
fight their own cases in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute procedure allows countries to bring cases where they  
feel other nations are discriminating against imported goods, but 
smaller countries have complained that they do not have the 
resources to go up against the might of trading powers such as the 
United States or the European Union. 
</P>
<P>
	Some six to eight sponsoring developed countries are needed to  
provide the bulk of the funds for setting up the center. 
</P>
<P>
	Gerrit Ybema, the Dutch minister of foreign trade, said the  
Netherlands will provide the largest amount announced so far -- 
about $2.25 million. Sweden, the United Kingdom, Norway and Denmark 
have pledged a million dollars each. 
</P>
<P>
	Other developed countries, such as Japan and New Zealand, have  
shown interest in supporting the project. Organizers said they hope 
the United States will contribute, but it has yet to commit any 
funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Developing countries, including Colombia, Zimbabwe, Egypt and  
the Philippines, also have pledged their support. They will be 
asked to pay up to $300,000 each to set the center up. 
</P>
<P>
	The organizers hope to have enough countries on board to launch  
the center officially during the WTO ministerial meeting in Seattle 
in November. 
</P>
<P>
	``The dispute settlement mechanism is the cornerstone of the  
success of the WTO, and we believe that a fair and effective 
mechanism which is above all accessible to all members of the WTO -- 
including the developing members -- is the key to the future of the 
multilateral trading system,'' said Stuart Harbinson, 
representative of Hong Kong, China. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
