<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Paige One of Best in Negro Leagues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Buck Leonard and Satchel Paige were selected  
the best Negro Leagues figures in a survey conducted by the Society 
for American Baseball Research. 
</P>
<P>
	Leonard, a first baseman with the Homestead Grays, helped led  
the Grays along with catcher Josh Gibson to nine consecutive Negro 
National League titles from 1937-45. He was elected to baseball's 
Hall of Fame in 1972 and died two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Paige, elected to the Hall of Fame in 1971, was regarded as the  
greatest Negro Leagues pitcher and made his major league debut in 
1948, going 6-1 for the Cleveland Indians. He died in 1982. 
</P>
<P>
	Cool Papa Bell was third followed by Oscar Charleston, also an  
outfielder. SABR had about 100 Negro Leagues writers, historians 
and researchers take part in its survey. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the top 40 Negro leaguers, SABR will release four  
other surveys on June 25 at its annual convention: top 40 19th 
century figures, top 15 major league umpires, 40 greatest 
contributors to baseball and 100 greatest 20th century players. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
