<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Milosevic Says He'll Carry Out Deal  
</P>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- Daylong talks between Secretary of State  
Madeleine Albright and the foreign ministers of six Western nations 
and Russia broke up today without Moscow's agreement on tough NATO 
peace terms for Kosovo that are laid out in a draft U.N. Security 
Council resolution. Despite the stalemate, Yugoslav President 
Slobodan Milosevic offered assurances that he intends to carry out 
a peace agreement, a U.S. official said. Finnish President Martti 
Ahtisaari, who had spoken to Milosevic by telephone, relayed the 
assurances to Albright and the seven foreign ministers drafting the 
resolution that would endorse the peace plan the Yugoslav 
government agreed to Thursday. 

</P>
<P>
	Jackson Wants To Return to Belgrade  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Rev. Jesse Jackson said today he hopes to  
make another trip to Yugoslavia to seek the release of two 
Australian aid workers who were convicted by Yugoslavia as spies. 
Jackson also criticized a U.S. policy against assistance to 
Yugoslavia unless President Slobodan Milosevic is removed from 
power. He said that is unfair to Yugoslav citizens who must rebuild 
their nation's economy while recovering personally from the 
bombings. Jackson helped last month win the release of three U.S. 
soldiers held in captivity by Yugoslavia. 

</P>
<P>
	New Hampshire Approves King Day  
</P>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- Gov. Jeanne Shaheen signed a bill today  
creating Martin Luther King Jr. Civil Rights Day, making New 
Hampshire the last state in the country to honor the slain civil 
rights leader with a holiday. The holiday will be observed for the 
first time Jan. 17, 2000. The bill ends years of attempts to put 
King's name on the holiday, which had been celebrated as Civil 
Rights Day under a legislative compromise passed in 1991. King's 
son, Martin Luther King III, represented the King family at the 
signing. 

</P>
<P>
	Indonesia Takes Part in 'Free' Vote  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Indonesians got their first real taste  
of democracy since 1955 as they voted today for a new Parliament, 
which will help choose the next president. It was another major 
step away from authoritarian rule that ended when riots by 
pro-democracy student groups forced President Suharto to resign in 
May 1998 after 32 years in power. Most Indonesians have never voted 
in a truly free election. The first and last open ballot was 44 
years ago. The ones that followed were largely rigged to ensure 
that candidates from the ruling Golkar Party won. 

</P>
<P>
	Ore., N.H. Lead in Economic Growth  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Oregon and New Hampshire enjoyed the fastest  
economic growth among the states in 1997, and California's economy 
remained the biggest. A Commerce Department report broke down the 
nation's gross domestic product, the total output of goods and 
services, to show the amount contributed by each state. The total 
U.S. economy grew in 1997 by 4.3 percent. Hawaii saw its economic 
output shrink in 1997, declining 0.2 percent, as the state's 
economy was hit hard by fallout from the Asian currency crisis. 

</P>
<P>
	Scientists Research Body Odor  
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- More than 50 scientists here are focusing  
their research exclusively on body odor. The researchers at the 
Monell Chemical Senses Center target smells, tastes and chemical 
irritation in hopes of providing crucial information about disease, 
dangerous chemicals and food safety. More than 50 companies in the 
fragrance, food, pharmaceutical and household product industries 
provide funding to the center and benefit from the research. Their 
projects test, for example, which fragrance people like best in 
deodorants and which food flavors are popular. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Push Ahead; Dow Up 112.71  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose broadly today as corporate mergers  
helped distract investors from lingering concerns about inflation. 
Just before the close, the Dow Jones industrial average was up 
112.71 at 10,912.55. Advancing issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led decliners 1,586-1,335. The Nasdaq composite index was 
up 49.71 at 2,528.05. 

</P>
<P>
	Doc Rivers Hired To Coach Magic  
</P>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Doc Rivers was hired as coach of the  
Orlando Magic today, succeeding Chuck Daly and taking over a team 
that was upset in the first round of the playoffs. He signed a 
four-year contract worth about $8 million. Although Rivers has no 
previous coaching experience, he played for some of the league's 
best -- Pat Riley, Larry Brown and Mike Fratello. Daly retired May 
24, saying he was weary of the travel. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  
  	   	
</P>
