<HEADLINE> EU Unemployment Holds at 9.6 Pct. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- Unemployment in the European Union  
remained at 9.6 percent in April, unchanged from March, the EU's 
statistics office said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The jobless rate was down from 10.1 percent in April 1998,  
according to Eurostat's report. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 11 euro-zone nations, unemployment fell slightly to 10.4  
percent in April from 10.5 percent in March. In April 1998, the 
unemployment rate in the euro region was 11.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The EU's unemployment rate in April remained more than double  
those of its main trading partners, with the U.S. jobless rate 
standing at 4.3 percent and Japan's at 4.7 percent, Eurostat noted. 
</P>
<P>
	Luxembourg continued to register the lowest unemployment in the  
EU, at 2.9 percent. Spain's was highest at 17.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Eurostat gave the following April 1999 figures for the 15 EU  
countries: 
</P>
<P>
	Luxembourg, 2.9 percent in April, compared with 2.8 percent in  
March; Portugal, 4.3 percent, up from 4.2 percent; Ireland, 6.8 
percent, down from 6.9 percent; Sweden, 7.4 percent, down from 7.5 
percent; Belgium, 9 percent, down from 9.1 percent; Germany, 9.1 
percent, down from 9 percent; Finland, 10.6 percent, down from 10.7 
percent; France, 11.3 percent, down from 11.4 percent, and Spain 
17.3, down from 17.4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The unemployment rate in Austria was unchanged at 4.5 percent,  
and Denmark's was unchanged at 4.7 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	April figures were not available for the Netherlands, which  
registered a 3.4 percent unemployment rate in March. No data was 
released on Britain, Greece and Italy. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
