<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court To Clarify Racketeering Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today agreed to clarify the  
reach of a federal law that allows people to file lawsuits alleging 
existence of a racketeering conspiracy. 
</P>
<P>
	The court said it will use a Florida case to decide, probably  
sometime in 2000, whether someone can file such a lawsuit even if 
the harm suffered was caused by an act that did not amount to 
racketeering. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert A. Beck II was hired in 1983 as president and a director  
of the Southeastern Insurance Group, a Florida-based company whose 
subsidiaries wrote bonds for construction companies. 
</P>
<P>
	His lawsuit contends he became aware in 1988 that other company  
leaders were engaging in misconduct, such as creating false 
financial statements and diverting company money to their personal 
use. 
</P>
<P>
	Beck says that after he reported the alleged improprieties to  
state insurance officials, the company hired a consultant that 
issued a report criticizing his performance. He was fired in May 
1988, he said, for refusing to participate in illegal conduct and 
for being a whistleblower. 
</P>
<P>
	The company filed for bankruptcy in 1990.  
</P>
<P>
	Beck sued members of the company's board of directors under  
conspiracy provisions of the federal Racketeer Influenced Corrupt 
Organizations law, which allows triple-damage awards. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge ruled that Beck could not sue under RICO because  
any harm to him was not caused by racketeering acts. The 11th U.S. 
Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the dismissal. 
</P>
<P>
	``A terminated whistleblower, although he may have a wrongful  
termination claim, has not suffered an injury that was proximately 
caused by the defendants' racketeering activities,'' the appeals 
court ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal acted on today, Beck's lawyers said other federal  
appeals courts have allowed lawsuits in which people contend they 
were harmed by acts committed as part of a racketeering conspiracy, 
even though those specific acts did not amount to racketeering. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for the former company directors said Beck failed to  
show a RICO conspiracy or that he was fired in retaliation for his 
actions. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Beck vs. Prupis, 98-1480.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
