<DOCNO> APW19990607.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 18:10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Low Turns Down Oikers' Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) -- Ron Low turned down a contract offer  
today to return as coach of the Edmonton Oilers. 
</P>
<P>
	``The deal I was offered, I just can't accept it,'' said Low,  
who declined a no-raise $307,000 contract for next season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think I should be the lowest-paid coach in the NHL,''  
the 48-year-old told CBC Radio. ``That's the way I feel and I feel 
very strongly about that. And that's where this would have left me, 
and I think that's wrong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kevin Lowe and Walt Kyle are the leading candidates to take over  
as coach of the Oilers. 
</P>
<P>
	Lowe, a former defenseman who helped the Oilers win five Stanley  
Cup championships, was an assistant to Low last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Kyle is coach of the Hamilton Bulldogs of the American Hockey  
League. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have not offered the job of head coach to anyone,'' Bill  
Tuele, the team's vice-president of public relations, said Monday. 
``Ron didn't reject the offer until 11 p.m.'' on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	While Low's contract expires June 30, Sather said he'd allow Low  
to begin looking for work elsewhere immediately. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have nothing in the fire,'' Low told CBC Radio.  
</P>
<P>
	The Oilers were 139-162-40 in regular-season play since Low  
replaced George Burnett during the strike-shortened 1994-95 season. 
</P>
<P>
	They were 33-37-12 last season, a respectable showing  
considering they lost goalie Curtis Joseph to free agency and top 
forwards Doug Weight and Ryan Smyth slumped. But there was 
dejection when, after the first-round playoff triumphs of 1997 and 
1998, the Oilers were swept in the first round by Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	In a news release, general manager Glen Sather stated: ``Ron  
exercised his prerogative not to accept our offer and stated he 
wanted to explore other opportunities with other teams. Ron has 
been a tremendous asset over the years, bringing enthusiasm and 
hard work to the rink ever day, but now we have to look to the 
future with a new coach at the helm.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Oilers' offense was 10th-best in the NHL, but the power play  
ranked 18th. Critics said Low became too close to his players. 
</P>
<P>
	The Oilers never finished a regular season above .500 with the  
Low, an Oilers assistant coach for six years before getting the top 
job, running the bench. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 16:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Prudential Payments in Suit Top $1B </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Within two years after a huge class-action  
settlement with aggrieved policyholders was approved, Prudential 
Insurance Co. of America has sent $1 billion in checks to 250,000 
claimants. 
</P>
<P>
	The remainder of the 650,000 claimants who sought compensation  
for Prudential's admittedly deceptive sales practices, and were 
found to be eligible, can expect payment by the end of the year, 
company spokesman Robert DeFillippo said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Prudential has acknowledged that some of its sales agents  
persuaded customers to trade in their old life insurance policies 
for newer, more expensive ones without telling them the old 
policies would lose their value. 
</P>
<P>
	The $1 billion in direct payments does not include the value of  
other remedies Prudential has given customers, such as paid-off 
policies. 
</P>
<P>
	Prudential has set aside $2.6 billion for compensation to more  
than 1 million customers and expects to stay within those 
parameters, DeFillippo said. 
</P>
<P>
	All 650,000 of the claimants have been notified of what they can  
expect in the settlement, the company said in providing figures 
through April to insurance regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	About 20 percent qualified for the highest level of relief, a  
full refund with interest, or a paid-up policy. The bulk, 64 
percent, are to get partial refunds or adjustments to their policy. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 81,000 claimants, or more than 12 percent, were told they  
probably will not get anything because they failed to prove they 
were misled or were victims of the types of abuse the settlement 
was intended to remedy, Prudential said. 
</P>
<P>
	The remainder, about 3 percent, purchased policies during years  
not covered by the settlement, or products not covered in the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 650,000, some 48,000 have told Prudential they will use  
the settlement's arbitration provision to appeal their award, while 
95,000 have not yet said how they intend to proceed. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement was approved in March 1997 by a federal judge in  
Newark, where Prudential is based. The payout could be among the 
largest ever in class-action litigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 8 million people who bought 10.7 million life insurance  
policies from 1982 to 1995 were notified that they might qualify 
for compensation. 
</P>
<P>
	Prudential got replies from more than 1 million who thought they  
had a claim, and 650,000 said they wanted to seek the largest 
amounts of compensation by demonstrating they were misled. The 
others were allowed to purchase Prudential products at a discount. 
</P>
<P>
	Some policyholders opposed the settlement, but it was upheld on  
appeal and the U.S. Supreme Court declined to rule on the matter in 
January. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the class-action compensation, Prudential has  
paid about $70 million in penalties to the 50 states and 
Washington, D.C. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 19:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hastert Proposes Shifting Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hoping to break a logjam that has kept the  
House from passing any annual spending bills for the coming fiscal 
year, Speaker Dennis Hastert is proposing to shift roughly $7 
billion extra to domestic programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan, which involves proceeds from anticipated sales of  
portions of the public broadcast spectrum and transferring money 
from defense and other bills, was described Monday by top House 
Republican aides speaking on condition of anonymity. They said it 
would allow Republicans to continue claiming they are obeying 
spending limits enacted in the 1997 budget-balancing pact between 
Congress and President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Hastert spokesman Pete Jeffries declined to discuss details of  
the plan, saying only that it would involve ``a reallocation of 
funds'' and that spending legislation ``will remain within budget 
guidelines.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As lawmakers returned to the Capitol after a Memorial Day  
recess, Hastert, R-Ill., and other Republican leaders presented 
their plan to groups of key GOP lawmakers. And though none of the 
legislators would reveal what they had been told, there was a sign 
of progress. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., a leader of conservatives who have  
been blocking an agriculture spending bill because of 
dissatisfaction with leadership strategy, said he would probably 
end the delays. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm satisfied with what he's doing,'' Coburn said of Hastert's  
plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Leaders hope to push the agriculture bill -- the first of the 13  
spending measures for fiscal 2000, which begins Oct. 1 -- through 
the House as early as Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hastert's proposal represents an effort to avoid another  
damaging autumn spending showdown in which President Clinton, as he 
has in past years, wins billions in extra spending from a GOP 
nervous that a politically costly government shutdown would 
otherwise result. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans hope when those negotiations occur again this fall --  
as seems all but certain -- they will be able to limit spending 
increases and win something else in return, such as tax cuts, said 
GOP aides. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican hopes of quickly approving spending bills this year  
have so far been dashed. The main reason has been internal 
Republican dissension over how to deal with spending limits 
required by the 1997 budget agreement -- limits Republicans promised 
to obey when they passed their fiscal 2000 budget in April. 
</P>
<P>
	Under those limits, lawmakers must hold spending to $538 billion  
for all federal programs, excluding Social Security, interest to 
federal debt holders and other automatically required benefits and 
payments. The overall federal budget is $1.7 trillion. 
</P>
<P>
	Under plans approved last month, House Republicans would spend  
$270 billion for the Pentagon, $19 billion more than this year. 
That leaves $268 billion for the 12 other bills: $25 billion less 
than this year, and more than $30 billion below what Clinton has 
requested. 
</P>
<P>
	Conservatives and other critics have said that under that  
blueprint, about six of the domestic spending bills covering 
education, veterans and other popular programs would not have 
enough money to even pass the House, let alone get Clinton's 
signature. That would leave Republicans in a weakened bargaining 
position for end-of-year talks with the White House, they argued. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the new Hastert plan, about $7 billion would be  
distributed among many of the bills in hopes of increasing the 
number the House can pass and that Clinton would sign. 
</P>
<P>
	About $2.6 billion would come from revenue projections from  
government sales of parts of the broadcast spectrum. 
</P>
<P>
	The rest would be money shifted from the defense, military  
construction, agriculture, transportation and other bills. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
