<DOCNO> APW19990607.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 17:20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Hampshire Approves King Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- The son of Martin Luther King Jr. stood  
next to the governor here on Monday as she ended the state's 
distinction as the only one without a holiday named for the slain 
civil rights leader. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin Luther King III said it was fitting that Gov. Jeanne  
Shaheen, New Hampshire's first female governor, was the one to sign 
the legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	``My father believed that democracy ought to be inclusive of  
everyone, and I think your signature on this bill signifies the 
progress we've made,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin Luther King Jr. Civil Rights Day will be officially  
observed for the first time in New Hampshire on Jan. 17, 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a result of the hard work of all the men, women and young  
people of this state, all 50 states will be unanimously observing 
the birthday of Martin Luther King Jr.,'' King said. ``It's 
certainly appropriate as we go into the new millennium.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The change, approved by the state House and Senate last month,  
ends 20 years of attempts to put his name on the holiday, which had 
been celebrated as Civil Rights Day under a compromise passed in 
1991. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents had argued that singling out King would detract from  
other American heroes such as George Washington and Abraham 
Lincoln. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all knew this day would come -- we always knew we would  
overcome,'' said state Sen. Beverly Hollingworth, a Democratic 
sponsor of this year's legislation. ``We're doing for the state 
what Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. did for the nation -- turning a 
source of shame into a source of pride.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
