<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bidding for Norway Oil Co. Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OSLO, Norway (AP) -- The bidding war for Norway's third largest  
oil company, Saga Petroleum ASA, heated up Monday when France's Elf 
Aquitaine raised its offer by more than 8 percent, while Norsk 
Hydro ASA mulled its next move. 
</P>
<P>
	Elf raised its takeover bid to $2.36 billion, up from $2.16  
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Norsk Hydro, which is 51 percent owned by Norway's government,  
opened bidding for economically troubled Saga on May 10 with an 
offer to trade one of its shares for three of Saga's shares. 
</P>
<P>
	Norsk Hydro also made a deal with the Norwegian state oil  
company Statoil AS, which owns 20 percent of Saga, to split the 
smaller company's assets between them. Statoil would end up with 25 
percent of Saga, and Norsk Hydro would take the rest. 
</P>
<P>
	On May 28, Elf, which has operated in Norway since 1965, made a  
cash offer to buy Saga, promising to let the smaller company 
continue operating under its own name. 
</P>
<P>
	A Saga news release said the company welcomed Elf's latest bid,  
and ``sees this as a positive development.'' It said the offer 
would be discussed at a board meeting on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Norsk Hydro did not immediately comment, or disclose whether it  
might make a counteroffer before Saga's board meets. News reports 
said a new Norsk Hydro bid was expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Early this year, Saga announced austerity measures after posting  
losses for 1998. The company nevertheless is attractive as a 
takeover target because it controls vast oil and natural gas 
reserves of nearly 1.5 billion barrels of oil equivalents. 
</P>
<P>
	Norsk Hydro, with petroleum, light metals and fertilizers  
divisions, is the largest company listed on the Oslo Stock 
Exchange. It employs about 40,000 people worldwide. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 11:10:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court: Feds Don't Own Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Billions of dollars worth of methane gas found  
with coal under federal land is not owned by the government and can 
be claimed by companies that purchase the right to drill for 
natural gas, the Supreme Court ruled today. 
</P>
<P>
	The 7-1 decision resolved a big-stakes dispute between Amoco and  
an Indian tribe in Colorado. Amoco won. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices ruled that coal bed methane found with coal under  
the Southern Ute Tribe's reservation should not be considered part 
of the coal the federal government owns in trust for the tribe. 
</P>
<P>
	The methane at issue in the Colorado case has an estimated worth  
of more than $200 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Writing for the court, Justice Anthony M. Kennedy said a pair of  
90-year-old federal laws that gave the government ownership of the 
coal did not apply to the methane found with it. 
</P>
<P>
	The court agreed with claims by Amoco Production Co., a  
subsidiary of BP Amoco, that its contractual right to take natural 
gas from the reservation land allows it to take the methane gas 
also. 
</P>
<P>
	``The common understanding of coal in 1909 and 1910 would not  
have encompassed CBM gas, both because it is a gas rather than a 
solid mineral and because it was understood as a distinct substance 
that escaped from coal as the coal was mined, rather than as a part 
of the coal itself,'' Kennedy said. 
</P>
<P>
	Amoco Production President Andy Inglis said the ruling affects  
``over 3,000 individual royalty and working-interest owners and 
various oil and gas producers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For most of this century, methane gas was considered only a  
dangerous element of coal mining, but relatively recent 
technological developments have made coal bed methane commercially 
valuable. 
</P>
<P>
	When the case was argued before the court in April, Justice  
Sandra Day O'Connor accused the government, which once renounced 
ownership of the methane gas, of changing its stand only after the 
gas became valuable. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg was the sole dissenter. She said the  
ambiguity in the two old laws should be construed in the 
government's favor. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice Stephen G. Breyer did not participate in the case. A  
financial-disclosure statement he filed with federal court 
officials last month stated that his wife owns between $15,000 and 
$50,000 worth of Amoco stock. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Amoco Production Co. vs. Southern Ute Indian Tribe,  
98-830. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 20:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: UK Opposed to Joining Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Opposition to Britain joining the beleaguered  
single European currency is growing among Britons, according to a 
poll published Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The telephone poll for the Guardian newspaper, conducted Friday  
and Saturday, indicated that 61 percent of Britons said they would 
vote against joining the euro. That is up from 53 percent a month 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The decline in support for the new regional currency comes as  
its value continues to slide to new lows. It has plunged 12 percent 
against the dollar since its January debut. 
</P>
<P>
	At that time, the Guardian poll indicated 52 percent were  
against Britain joining. 
</P>
<P>
	In this month's poll of 1,067 people, those in favor of monetary  
union fell back seven percentage points from 34 percent in May to 
27 percent, while the number of ``don't knows'' remained unchanged 
at 13 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll, conducted by research group ICM, had a margin of error  
of 3 percentage points. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 07:46:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Khmer Rouge Commander Convicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) -- A former Khmer Rouge commander was  
convicted and sentenced to life in prison today for ordering the 
1994 killing of three kidnapped Western tourists. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial of Nuon Paet was considered a test case for Cambodia's  
court system. Foreign experts have questioned whether it can 
properly try Khmer Rouge leaders for crimes against humanity 
connected to their genocidal 1975-79 rule. 
</P>
<P>
	In a surprise move, prosecutors at the start of today's  
proceedings also accused two former Khmer Rouge guerrilla leaders 
now loyal to the Cambodian government in the killings of the three 
tourists. 
</P>
<P>
	The charges relate to a Khmer Rouge operation that took place  
long after the group was forced out of power and had launched a 
guerrilla war against the government. 
</P>
<P>
	The tourists -- Frenchman Jean-Michel Braquet, Briton Mark Slater  
and Australian David Wilson -- were kidnapped from a train and held 
at Nuon Paet's mountaintop base. The government negotiated for 
three months with the guerrillas, at one point agreeing to pay 
$150,000 in ransom. 
</P>
<P>
	But the deal broke down. When government troops overran the  
mountain in October 1994, the bludgeoned bodies of the three 
backpackers were found in a shallow grave. 
</P>
<P>
	Nuon Paet, who maintained his innocence throughout the one-day  
trial, listened to the verdict in silence. As he was being taken in 
handcuffs to a waiting police vehicle, he shouted to reporters: 
``Unjust!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dorothy Slater, Mark Slater's mother, said: ``I'm happy. It was  
worth the trip.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, Jean-Claude Braquet, father of Jean-Michel Braquet,  
called the trial a farce. ``It isn't today that they will offer the 
real truth,'' he had said earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Braquet and Wilson's family believe Nuon Paet is a scapegoat for  
the killings. Wilson's family boycotted the proceedings. 
</P>
<P>
	As Nuon Paet's trial began, the chief prosecutor surprised the  
packed courtroom by introducing charges against two of the man's 
former superiors in the Khmer Rouge: Sam Bith, who left the 
guerrilla movement in 1997 and is now a general in the Cambodian 
army, and Col. Chhouk Rin, who also defected to the government. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief prosecutor Yeth Chakriya said he had received clearance  
from Prime Minister Hun Sen's office to charge them. He said they 
would be tried separately from Nuon Paet. It was unclear if they 
would be taken into custody. 
</P>
<P>
	The two were present as witnesses, and in their testimony they  
denied any role in the tourists' killing. 
</P>
<P>
	Nuon Paet was found guilty on all charges: illegal detention,  
terrorist activities, being an accomplice to murder, forming an 
armed group for the purpose of robbery and destruction of public 
property. 
</P>
<P>
	He blamed Sam Bith, Chhouk Rin and a third rebel commander, Vit  
Von, for the killings. Vit Von was killed several years ago in an 
apparent internal Khmer Rouge dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	Nuon Paet was ordered to pay about $30,000 in compensation to  
three families of Cambodians killed or injured in the train attack 
and $5,500 in damages to the railroad company. 
</P>
<P>
	He was also ordered to pay an unspecified amount to the Wilson  
family, who have demanded $50,000 for David Wilson's death -- his 
share of the ransom money. The Wilsons' lawyer has said the family 
would give the money to a Cambodian charity. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990607.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-07 07:46:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
