<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PUERTO OBALDIA, Panama (AP) -- The government deployed police  
along the Colombian border Monday to protect towns that have 
repeatedly been invaded by Colombian rebels. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the police were sent to the Kuna Yala region in the  
southern province of Darien, which the government declared a ``risk 
zone'' last week, limiting access to outsiders. 
</P>
<P>
	Panama, which has no army, last week dispatched additional  
police to guard two villages near the Colombian border after some 
residents fled in fear of the guerrillas. 
</P>
<P>
	The presence of the Colombian guerrillas is seen as a potential  
security problem as U.S. troops withdraw from the Panama Canal 
zone, which the United States is to hand over to Panama on Dec. 31. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) -- A young man opened fire with a  
semiautomatic rifle at a neighborhood soccer game, killing two 
players and wounding three people, police said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 17-year-old man pulled the M-16 rifle from a suitcase during  
the game in northern San Salvador Sunday and began shooting in all 
directions, a police official said on customary condition of 
anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of the players were killed instantly, while three of the  
20-odd spectators suffered bullet wounds, he said. Others suffered 
minor injuries as they tried to flee. 
</P>
<P>
	Police, who had a post only yards from where the game was being  
played, jumped the man after he ran out of ammunition, police said. 
The motive for the shooting was unclear. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) -- A team of International Monetary Fund  
economists arrived Monday to review Brazil's economy, part of an 
agreement for a $41.5 billion aid package approved last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil has received $19 billion so far, but additional payouts  
depend on the government's success in cutting spending and reducing 
its huge budget deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	The economy has shown an unexpectedly strong recovery after a 30  
percent devaluation of its currency, the real, in January. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, the government announced it had surpassed all its  
goals for the first quarter. The primary budget surplus -- revenue 
minus expenses, but not including interest payments -- was $5.3 
billion, way above the target of $3.5 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The goal for the year is a surplus of $17.5 billion, and  
authorities say it will be achieved easily. 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF team is expected to stay in the capital until June 17.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- The presidents of Argentina and  
Brazil on Monday cited the need to revitalize and deepen Mercosur, 
South America's leading trade bloc, reports said. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil's Fernando Henrique Cardoso met Argentine counterpart  
Carlos Menem at his residence and they also reiterated calls for 
the European Union to eliminate its agriculture subsidies. 
</P>
<P>
	Cardoso said Mercosur's revitalization would be achieved thanks  
to the ``growing convergence'' of the member countries' economic 
policies, reported the Diarios y Noticias news agency. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mercosur bloc has been unsettled by the devaluation of the  
Brazilian real in January. The bloc, formally known as the Southern 
Cone Common Market, also includes Uruguay and Paraguay. Chile and 
Bolivia are associate members. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
