<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Apple Growers File China Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- First steel, now apples. American apple  
growers filed a trade case today alleging that imports of Chinese 
apple juice concentrate are being sold at unfairly low prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. apple producers asked the Commerce Department to impose  
penalty tariffs on apple juice concentrate from China of up to 91 
percent in order to protect the American industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``A flood of cheap apple-juice concentrate imports from China is  
drowning much of our industry in a sea of red ink,'' said U.S. 
Apple Association President Kraig R. Naasz. 
</P>
<P>
	The apple growers asked for the penalty tariffs to counteract  
what they charged was the unfair Chinese practice of selling juice 
concentrate in the American market at prices below the cost of 
production or the home market price, a practice known as dumping. 
</P>
<P>
	The steel industry has filed a number of similar dumping cases  
asking for penalty tariffs as protection against a flood of cheap 
imported steel. 
</P>
<P>
	Other industries are likely to follow suit, reflecting growing  
pressures as America's trade deficit has soared to record levels 
because of the global financial crisis, which started in Asia in 
1997. 
</P>
<P>
	With one-third of the globe in recession, foreign producers have  
sought to unload their products in the U.S. market, the only major 
economy doing well at present. The steep devaluations in many 
foreign currencies mean that the price of the foreign products has 
fallen. 
</P>
<P>
	In their complaint, U.S. apple growers said that apple juice  
concentrate imports from China had soared more than 13-fold between 
1995 and 1998, rising from 3,000 metric tons in 1995 to 40,000 
metric tons in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	China is now the world's largest producer of apples, with a 70  
percent increase in production over the past five years. China's 
share of the U.S. market has risen from 1 percent to 18 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The surge in Chinese apple juice concentrate shipments has been  
accompanied by a huge drop in prices, the group said. The average 
price for apple juice concentrate from China declined from $7.65 
per gallon in 1995 to $3.57 per gallon in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result of what American growers called China's unfair  
pricing policies, the average price for American concentrate has 
been cut by 50 percent, forcing many producers to let their juice 
apples rot in the orchards this past growing season because the 
cost of harvesting the apples was higher than the price they would 
bring. 
</P>
<P>
	``The U.S. apple industry is united in its pursuit of relief  
from the adverse economic impact of China's unfair pricing 
practices,'' Naasz said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The apple producers asked the U.S. International Trade  
Commission for a finding that their industry is being harmed by the 
Chinese imports and it requested a ruling from the Commerce 
Department on the levels of penalty tariffs that can be imposed. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department is expected to initiate a formal dumping  
investigation within 20 days and the ITC is required to make a 
preliminary determination of whether the U.S industry is being 
harmed within 45 days. 
</P>
<P>
	The trade case was brought by apple interests in Michigan,  
California, Pennsylvania and Washington state. The U.S. Apple 
Association represents individual apple companies and 30 state 
apple associations representing more than 9,000 apple growers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
