<HEADLINE> Rangers' Gunderson on Rehab </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- Texas Rangers left-hander Eric Gunderson  
was sent today to Triple-A Oklahoma for a medical rehabilitation 
stint that can last up to 30 days. 
</P>
<P>
	Gunderson, 0-3 with a 5.19 ERA in 68 games with the Rangers in  
1998, has a 7.20 ERA in 11 relief appearances with Texas this 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	On May 9 he was placed on the 15-day disabled list, retroactive  
to the previous day, because of a small rotator cuff tear and a 
small labrum tear in his left shoulder. He has been throwing off 
the mound for the past week. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas also agreed to minor league contract with three players  
selected in last week's amateur draft -- third-round pick Hank 
Blalock, fifth-round selection Victor Hillaert of and 13th-round 
pick Jason Jones. The Rangers also signed free-agent Jamie Hill, a 
left-handed pitcher from Alabama-Huntsville. 
</P>
<P>
	Hill, Blalock and Hillaert were assigned to the Rookie League  
Gulf Coast Rangers. Jones will report to Pulaski in the Appalachian 
League. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
