<HEADLINE> Bengals Reinstate Tremain Mack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- The Cincinnati Bengals today reinstated  
Tremain Mack, a kick returner and defensive back who was jailed 
last season because of drunken-driving arrests. 
</P>
<P>
	Mack, 24, missed the final four games last season because of his  
latest drunken-driving arrest, in October. He has been released 
from jail after serving time for a probation violation and has been 
undergoing an NFL-mandated alcohol evaluation program. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bengals have said they expect Mack to attend the June  
mini-camp and training camp, which begins in late July. 
</P>
<P>
	He had a history of drinking problems when the Bengals drafted  
the University of Miami standout in the fourth round of the 1997 
draft. Mack had been arrested six times in less than four years, 
with at least three of the arrests related to alcohol. 
</P>
<P>
	Mack will be subject to random drug and alcohol testing  
throughout the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Mack set team records in kickoff return average (25.9) and yards  
(1,165) in the first 12 games last season, with one touchdown. 
</P>
<P>
	He was jailed beginning in December after violating his  
probation stemming from a drunken-driving arrest Oct. 13, 1998, in 
the Cincinnati area. He underwent a mandatory two-month treatment 
program and was evaluated by the NFL under its substance-abuse 
program. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
