<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                         *Randolph Bullock    	
</P>
<P>
	OCEANSIDE, N.Y. (AP) -- Randolph Bullock, a curator emeritus of  
arms and armor at the Metropolitan Museum of Art, died May 28. He 
was 96. 
</P>
<P>
	Bullock helped build the museum's collection in the 40 years he  
worked there. One of his most important contributions was the 
design of the arms and armor installation that opened in the 
museum's J.P. Morgan wing in 1956. Arms and armor previously had no 
permanent home in the museum. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Bruno Caravaggi    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW HYDE PARK, N.Y. (AP) -- Bruno Caravaggi, co-owner of Quo  
Vadis, one of New York's trendiest Continental restaurants for 
almost 40 years, died May 30. He was 83. 
</P>
<P>
	Caravaggi and Gino Robusti opened Quo Vadis on East 63rd Street  
between Madison and Park avenues in 1946. The restaurant, decorated 
with columns, red velvet and Italian mosaics, became a favorite of 
Jacqueline Kennedy, Frank Sinatra, Truman Capote and Nat King Cole, 
among others. 
</P>
<P>
	The partners sold the restaurant in 1982 but returned to run it  
a year later after the new owners filed for bankruptcy. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Ralph Chamberlain    	
</P>
<P>
	FLY CREEK, N.Y. (AP) -- Ralph Chamberlain, a philanthropist and  
businessman who publicized the Salvation Army with national 
television and magazine campaigns in the 1970s, died Wednesday. He 
was 72. 
</P>
<P>
	Chamberlain founded several businesses, including Precise Kit  
Promotions, a manufacturer of disaster aid kits. 
</P>
<P>
	He attended the Salvation Army School for Officer Training in  
Suffern, N.Y., in 1946. He achieved the rank of captain. 

</P>
<P>
                        *William Eberline Sr.    	
</P>
<P>
	HEBRON, Neb. (AP) -- William Eberline Sr., a retired Associated  
Press reporter, died May 30 of cancer. He was 79. 
</P>
<P>
	Eberline retired from the AP in 1985. He also was a member of  
the Press Club of Des Moines and the Iowa State Bar Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include a son, William L. Jr.; two daughters, Judith  
Marcus of Plano, Texas, and Joan Barry; two sisters, Betty 
Jorgenson and Jeannette Lawson; and four grandchildren. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Harold S. Fawcett    	
</P>
<P>
	MORGANTOWN, W.Va. (AP) -- Harold S. ``Jabo'' Fawcett, a Navy  
photographer who captured images of the Japanese bombing of Pearl 
Harbor, died Saturday. He was 82. 
</P>
<P>
	Fawcett served in the Navy for 19 years, including on the USS  
Utah and the USS Argonne, then attended the Naval School of 
Photography at Pensacola, Fla., in 1939. 
</P>
<P>
	His aviation squadron was moved to Pearl Harbor in May 1940.  
Some of his photographs of the December 1941 bombing were published 
in U.S. newspapers and in the Dec. 14, 1942, issue of Life 
magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	Fawcett later became a decorated pilot, serving in Bikini in the  
South Pacific, where he photographed two atom bomb test explosions. 
</P>
<P>
	Fawcett is survived by his wife, Norma Webb Fawcett; two  
daughters; a stepson; a brother, sister, stepsister and six 
grandchildren. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Eloise Hawkins    	
</P>
<P>
	WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) -- Eloise Hawkins, chairman and chief  
executive of the authority which ran stock-car races at Bowman Gray 
Stadium, died Monday of cancer. She was 82. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1970, Hawkins was head of the Winston-Salem Speedway,  
Inc., which conducts NASCAR-sanctioned stock-car racing at the 
municipal stadium under a lease from the city. She remained active 
in its operation until the illness struck her earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	She entered the auto racing industry when she married J. Alvin  
Hawkins, who co-founded the stadium's racing in 1949 in a 
partnership with NASCAR founder William France. 
</P>
<P>
	France withdrew from the enterprise in the 1960s and Hawkins  
became the stadium's racing chief after her husband died in 1970. 

</P>
<P>
                         *F. Steele Langford    	
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- F. Steele Langford, former chief federal  
magistrate in San Francisco and a prosecutor of Sara Jane Moore and 
Patricia Hearst, died Friday night after heart surgery. He was 67. 
</P>
<P>
	Langford was prosecutor of Sara Jane Moore, convicted of  
attempting to assassinate President Gerald Ford in 1975. He also 
took part in the 1975 prosecution of Ms. Hearst for bank robbery. 
</P>
<P>
	He presided over the extradition hearing of William Quinn, the  
first Irish Republican Army member extradited from the United 
States to Britain. 
</P>
<P>
	He ruled that the shooting of an off-duty British police  
officer, of which Quinn was accused, was an ordinary murder rather 
than a political crime exempt from extradition. The ruling was 
upheld on appeal, and Quinn was extradited and eventually convicted 
of murder by a London jury. 
</P>
<P>
	Langford retired in 1996 after 17 years as a magistrate,  
handling bail and other pretrial matters for judges in the Northern 
District of California, who had appointed him. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Ruth Lawrence    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Ruth Lawrence, an Austrian Jewish swimmer who  
refused to take part in Hitler's 1936 Olympic games and eventually 
fled to England, died May 2. She was 77. 
</P>
<P>
	She was 14 when she broke the Austrian records for the 100-meter  
and 400-meter freestyle and was one of three Jewish girls who were 
to have represented their country at the 1936 Olympics in Nazi 
Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	The World Federation of Jewish Sports Clubs asked competitors  
not to go to the Berlin games because of Adolf Hitler's persecution 
of Jews. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawrence and the other two Jewish swimmers declined to compete  
and were banned from participating in Austrian competitions. 
</P>
<P>
	Her Austrian swimming records were removed from the national  
list and not reinstated until 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Her photograph and records are part of a display at the  
Holocaust Museum in Washington, D.C. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Paul S. Newman    	
</P>
<P>
	COLUMBIA, Md. (AP) -- Paul S. Newman, a prolific comic-book  
writer who got listed in the Guinness Book of World Records, died 
May 30 of a heart attack. He was 75. 
</P>
<P>
	Newman wrote scripts for Superman, Mighty Mouse, The Lone Ranger  
and Jungle Jim comic books, among others. Beginning in 1947, he 
wrote more than 4,100 published stories totaling about 36,000 
pages, the equivalent of 120 mystery novels. His stories included 
dialogue and panel-by-panel descriptions of what the artist was 
supposed to draw. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1993, the comic-book historian Robin Snyder named Newman King  
of the Comic Book Writers. The Guinness book listed him as most 
prolific comic book writer under a headline, ``Lots of plots!'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also wrote a few newspaper comic strips, as well as  
screenplays and television sketches for such stars as Boris 
Karloff. 

</P>
<P>
                          *David Nicolette    	
</P>
<P>
	GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) -- David Nicolette, The Grand Rapids  
Press theater writer and former city editor, died Sunday at his 
Grand Rapids home. He was 80. 
</P>
<P>
	He began his newspaper career in 1949 at the Evansville (Ind.)  
Press and joined The Grand Rapids Press on Nov. 9, 1950. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten years later, while serving as assistant city editor, he  
began writing his Words and Music entertainment column. He became 
city editor in 1971, and in 1977 took over the newly created 
entertainment/features department. 
</P>
<P>
	At Civic Theater in Grand Rapids, Nicolette's regular reviewer's  
seat for opening night -- halfway back and on the aisle -- will be 
left unoccupied Thursday night for the opening performance of 
``Steel Magnolias'' as a tribute to him, director Paul Dreher said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicolette is survived by his wife of 51 years, Emma Louise (Dr.  
MacAdams) Nicolette, a daughter, four sons, a brother and four 
sisters. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Nancy Richard-Akers    	
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Nancy Richards-Akers, who penned romance  
novels, was fatally shot Saturday night -- apparently by her 
estranged husband, who police said later took his own life in front 
of the Vietnam Veterans Memorial. She was 45. 
</P>
<P>
	District of Columbia police said they were investigating the  
case as a murder-suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said Jeremy Akers shot and killed himself as U.S. Park  
Police officers approached him near the memorial. His vehicle was 
found nearby. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Richards-Akers wrote 16 historical romance novels, including  
such titles as ``Devil's Wager'' and ``Miss Wickham's Betrothal.'' 
Her latest offering was ``So Wild a Kiss.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
