<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Helps His Vice President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With a swipe at congressional Republicans,  
President Clinton is going to bat for Al Gore by signing a 
fund-raising letter for the vice president. 
</P>
<P>
	The letter is dated May 18 -- five days after The New York Times  
quoted the president as expressing concern about the start of 
Gore's presidential campaign but declaring it ``in a lot better 
shape now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's letter promoting Gore as his successor criticizes  
unidentified ``powerful forces'' -- a clear reference to the 
Republicans who control the House and Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	``They continue to resist change -- trying, over and over again,  
to return our country to the policies that have failed,'' Clinton 
wrote. ``They struggled against our economic plan. They shut the 
government down. And they tried to poison our country with 
partisanship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has said he will formally endorse Gore once the vice  
president officially declares his candidacy. He is wading into an 
intraparty fight, since former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey also 
is seeking the Democratic presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	``Al Gore has been a loyal vice president to Bill Clinton for  
several years, loyally standing beside him during the 
administration,'' Bradley spokeswoman Anita Dunn said. ``We're not 
surprised that Bill Clinton is repaying that loyalty by helping him 
in the campaign.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore campaign spokesman Roger Salazar said the fund-raising  
letter was just one indication of Clinton's willingness to help his 
vice president succeed him. 
</P>
<P>
	``The president has said many times that he is going to do  
everything he can to be helpful to the campaign,'' Salazar said. 
``We very much appreciate what he's doing here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During the three-month period ending March 31, the last date for  
which figures are available, Gore led all presidential hopefuls in 
seeking campaign funds by raising $8.9 million. Second was Texas 
Gov. George W. Bush, who raised $7.6 million. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
