<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Jets Pound Yugoslavia  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO jets pounded Yugoslavia today  
after the alliance warned President Slobodan Milosevic to expect 
intensified bombing until he orders his troops out of Kosovo. 
Milosevic, meanwhile, sought to assure key Western countries and 
Russia that he still intends to abide by terms of a peace plan to 
which he agreed last week. His pledge was relayed to a meeting of 
foreign ministers from the Group of Eight -- the world's seven 
leading industrial nations and Russia -- in Bonn, Germany. Fear of 
ambushes by the Kosovo Liberation Army is another reason Yugoslavia 
has been reluctant to endorse NATO's pullout terms. 

</P>
<P>
	Bin Laden, Kopp on Most-Wanted List  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The FBI put alleged terrorist mastermind Osama  
Bin Laden and anti-abortion activist and accused doctor killer 
James Charles Kopp on the bureau's list of the Ten Most Wanted 
fugitives today. FBI Director Louis Freeh said the U.S. government 
is offering a reward of up to $5 million for information that leads 
to the arrest and conviction of bin Laden, indicted as the 
architect of the bombings of American embassies in Kenya and 
Tanzania. Meanwhile, $650,000 is being offered for information 
leading to the arrest of Kopp, who is charged with gunning down Dr. 
Barnett Slepian last fall in his home in Buffalo, N.Y. Slepian 
performed abortions. 

</P>
<P>
	NRA Tries To Rally Lawmakers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In the wake of the school shootings this  
spring in Colorado, House Republican leaders discussed legislation 
today that would restrict youth access to video games, movies and 
other items containing violent as well as sexually explicit 
material. The proposal also would require the music industry to 
provide stores with copies of song lyrics as a means of allowing 
adults to keep questionable products from their children. The 
provisions were among several prepared by Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., 
chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, for inclusion in 
legislation cracking down on juvenile crime. 

</P>
<P>
	Pinochet Won't Challenge Ruling  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Lawyers for Gen. Augusto Pinochet said today they  
will not appeal a High Court decision to allow extradition 
proceedings against the former Chilean dictator. Last month, a High 
Court judge refused Pinochet permission to challenge the home 
secretary's decision allowing Spain to try to extradite him on 
human rights charges. Pinochet could have appealed the single 
judge's decision to a three-judge panel, but has decided not to, 
his attorney said. That means the next phase in the drawn-out legal 
battle -- which began Oct. 16 with Pinochet's arrest in London -- 
will come this fall, when the extradition proceedings are due to 
open. 

</P>
<P>
	Tropical Storm Slams SE Asia  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- A storm packing typhoon-force winds slammed  
into Hong Kong and southern China today, causing blackouts and 
swelling rivers. The storm hit the city overnight with winds of up 
to 87 mph, but quickly weakened. In China's southern Guangdong 
province, Tropical Storm Maggie blew down power lines and caused 
blackouts, but no injuries were reported. Heavy rain swelled rivers 
and streams and destroyed tens of thousands of acres of crops in 
Huilai county. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan: Economy Has Stopped Worsening  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's economy has stopped deteriorating as a  
result of government spending, though risks remain, the government 
said Tuesday. The Economic Planning Agency upgraded its assessment 
of the nation's economy in June for the first time in three months. 
The agency said that the economy ``has stopped deteriorating and is 
fluctuating sideways.'' Since March, the assessment had said 
``downward movement continues to slow to a halt.'' The report is 
considered a key indicator of government thinking on the state of 
the economy and can sometimes anticipate policy initiatives. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Stocks Gain 20.15  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stock prices edged higher in early trading  
Tuesday following an overnight rise on Wall Street. The Nikkei rose 
20.15 to 16,496.04 in the first 30 minutes of trading. In New York, 
the Dow Jones industrial average today closed up 109.54 at 
10,909.38. 

</P>
<P>
	Low Turns Down Oilers' Offer  
</P>
<P>
	EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) -- Ron Low turned down a contract offer  
today to return as coach of the Edmonton Oilers. ``The deal I was 
offered, I just can't accept it,'' said Low, who declined a 
no-raise $307,000 contract for next season. ``I don't think I 
should be the lowest-paid coach in the NHL.'' Kevin Lowe and Walt 
Kyle are the leading candidates to take over. Lowe, a former 
defenseman who helped the Oilers win five Stanley Cups, was an 
assistant to Low last season. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  
  	   	
</P>
