<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Limits Use of Backyard Field </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Baseball may be as American as Apple Pie,  
but a judge says a New Jersey man who built a regulation size field 
in his backyard is getting too much of a good thing. 
</P>
<P>
	Superior Court Judge Victor Ashrafi said Bill Ingraham's  
round-the-clock games broke zoning laws and Ingraham must limit 
playing time at the Tewksbury Township field. 
</P>
<P>
	The man built the diamond along with an indoor field house for  
nearly $300,000 in 1996, a move reminiscent of the 1989 movie 
``Field of Dreams'' in which Kevin Costner's character turns his 
cornfield into a baseball field. 
</P>
<P>
	Neighbors and the township -- the hometown of Gov. Christie  
Whitman -- sued Ingraham, saying his schedule of Little League and 
semi-pro games violated their privacy and peace of mind. 
</P>
<P>
	Ingraham has said Tewksbury overreacted to his version of  
All-American fun. 
</P>
<P>
	``This court agrees that children playing baseball can not  
easily be branded a nuisance,'' Ashrafi wrote. ``One might as well 
say that apple pie is poison.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``But the fact that baseball for kids is wholesome and patriotic  
does not mean that full-scale games, practices and training can be 
held anywhere,'' Ashrafi added. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashrafi said that Ingraham, his wife and two children can play  
baseball anytime they want on the field with up to eight guests. He 
can play games with more people than that once a month until Dec. 
31, 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The opinion didn't say what would happen after that, confusing  
attorneys who said they would probably return to court for an 
explanation. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling also bans uniforms, aluminum bats, night games,  
loudspeakers and outdoor lighting from the field. 
</P>
<P>
	Ingraham also can't bring organized, league teams or paid  
officials onto the field, and can only invite paid instructors to 
give lessons to his family, Ashrafi said. 
</P>
<P>
	Township officials and neighbors had asked that Ingraham only be  
allowed to play regulation-size games at the field three times a 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Tewksbury's deputy mayor, Tres Arnett, called the lawsuit's end  
``a reasonable result.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We weren't looking to have him plow the field under,'' Arnett  
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
